export const MOR_UNITS = [{"id":"u7","title":"Understanding the MOR Process","chapters":["m71","m72","m73"]},{"id":"u8","title":"Desk Review Preparation","chapters":["m81","m82","m83"]},{"id":"u9","title":"Tenant Files & Certifications","chapters":["m91","m92","m93","m94"]},{"id":"u10","title":"Income, Assets & EIV Compliance","chapters":["m101","m102","m103"]},{"id":"u11","title":"Waiting List, TSP & Fair Housing","chapters":["m111","m112","m113"]},{"id":"u12","title":"VAWA, Leases & Financial Management","chapters":["m121","m122","m123"]},{"id":"u13","title":"Building Your MOR Consulting Business","chapters":["m131","m132","m133"]}];
export const MOR_CHAPTERS = [{"id":"m71","unit":"u7","number":1,"title":"What Is a MOR? Purpose, Authority & HUD Form 9834","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Purpose and Legal Authority of the MOR","body":"A Management and Occupancy Review (MOR) is HUD's primary tool for assessing whether a multifamily housing property is being managed in compliance with HUD requirements. It focuses entirely on paperwork, processes, policies, and management practices — not physical conditions. Physical inspections are conducted under NSPIRE.\n\nThe legal authority flows from the National Housing Act, the U.S. Housing Act of 1937 (as amended), and HUD's regulatory authority under 24 CFR Part 200. The HAP contract requires the owner to permit HUD or its designee to conduct management reviews. Owners who refuse can be found in breach of their HAP contract.\n\nHUD Handbook 4350.3 REV-1 Change-4 governs most MOR topics including tenant eligibility, rent calculation, certifications, and waiting list management. Change-4 incorporates HOTMA amendments that became fully effective January 1, 2025.\n\nFrom a consulting standpoint, you are helping a client meet binding contractual and regulatory obligations — not just pass a test. A failed MOR can trigger repayment demands, management agent removal, or even HAP contract termination. The stakes justify your fee."},{"heading":"HUD Form 9834 — The MOR Instrument","body":"HUD Form 9834 (Management Review for Multifamily Housing Projects) is the official instrument used to conduct every MOR. Every item a reviewer evaluates maps directly to a line on Form 9834. If it is not on 9834, it is not scored — but it may still be noted as a finding.\n\nForm 9834 is organized into major review areas: Occupancy (tenant eligibility, certifications, rent calculations), Maintenance (work orders, preventive maintenance, unit turnaround), Financial Management (budgets, audits, RFR, insurance), Tenant-Management Relations (lease enforcement, grievance procedures), and Site/Project Management (staffing, record-keeping, fair housing).\n\nEach area contains individual items scored as Acceptable (A), Not Applicable (N/A), or Deficient (D). The aggregate of deficiencies across all areas produces the overall project rating.\n\nOwners and agents should maintain a copy of Form 9834 and use it as a self-assessment tool at least quarterly. As a consultant, one of your most valuable services is walking through a mock MOR using Form 9834 before the official review. Form 9834 is publicly available on HUD's website and HUDCLIPS."},{"heading":"Who Conducts the MOR — HUD Staff vs. Contract Administrators","body":"Not all MORs are conducted by HUD employees. The review may be performed by: (1) HUD Field Office staff, (2) a HUD-approved Performance Based Contract Administrator (PBCA), or (3) a HUD-designated monitoring contractor.\n\nPBCAs are private entities contracted with HUD to administer Section 8 contracts in a given state or region. Their reviewers are generally very experienced and may have detailed familiarity with specific state-level issues. HUD Field Office reviews often carry more formal weight in terms of potential enforcement actions.\n\nRegardless of who conducts the review, the instrument (Form 9834) and regulatory standards are the same. Different reviewers may have different documentation preferences or communication styles. When preparing a client, find out who will conduct their MOR and review any prior MOR reports from that reviewer.\n\nSince January 1, 2024, HUD has required all MORs to be conducted on-site. Remote or virtual MORs, which were briefly permitted during COVID-19, are no longer allowed."},{"heading":"MOR Frequency — What Triggers a Review","body":"MOR frequency is determined primarily by the property's risk profile, prior performance, and HUD's monitoring schedule.\n\nStandard frequency: Properties performing satisfactorily are typically reviewed every two to three years. HUD's risk-based approach means that better-performing properties are reviewed less often.\n\nAnnual reviews: Properties with a current MOR rating of Below Average or Unsatisfactory, properties under a Performance Improvement Plan, or properties flagged by HUD's risk-scoring systems may receive annual MORs until their performance improves.\n\nTriggered reviews: A MOR may be triggered outside the normal cycle by tenant complaints, fair housing complaints, audit findings, REAC score failures, EIV noncompliance flags, or referrals from HUD's Office of Inspector General.\n\nNew ownership or management agent: When a property changes ownership or management agent, HUD typically schedules a MOR within 12–18 months to assess the new team's compliance posture."},{"heading":"MOR Consequences — From Findings to Enforcement","body":"The consequences of a MOR finding depend on severity, pattern, and the property's history.\n\nMinor findings: Most first-time findings result in a corrective action letter requiring the owner to submit a written plan addressing how and by when each deficiency will be corrected. Typical cure periods range from 30 to 90 days.\n\nSignificant findings: Repeated or uncorrected findings, or findings involving fair housing violations, EIV noncompliance, or material misrepresentation, can escalate to formal enforcement. HUD may issue a Notice of Default, require replacement of the management agent, or place a property on a Performance Improvement Plan.\n\nFinancial consequences: HUD can require repayment of overpaid rental assistance if certifications are found to be incorrect. These repayment demands — sometimes covering multiple years — can be financially devastating.\n\nContract termination: In the most severe cases, persistent noncompliance can result in termination of the HAP contract. Once a HAP contract is terminated, the property loses its subsidy stream entirely.\n\nFor your consulting business, positioning yourself as the person who prevents these outcomes — rather than the person called in after disaster strikes — commands premium fees."}]},{"id":"m72","unit":"u7","number":2,"title":"MOR Ratings — Understanding the Five-Level Scale","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"The Five MOR Ratings Explained","body":"HUD uses a five-level rating scale on Form 9834. Every MOR concludes with one of these ratings: Superior, Above Average, Satisfactory, Below Average, or Unsatisfactory.\n\nSuperior: Exceptional management across all review areas with no or minimal deficiencies. Few properties consistently earn Superior ratings.\n\nAbove Average: Strong performance with only minor, isolated deficiencies. The management team demonstrates proactive compliance and good documentation habits.\n\nSatisfactory: The baseline passing rating. The property meets HUD requirements with acceptable compliance in all major areas. Most properties in good standing receive Satisfactory.\n\nBelow Average: Significant deficiencies in one or more review areas, or a pattern of minor deficiencies suggesting systemic problems. Triggers corrective action requirements and increases likelihood of annual follow-up MOR.\n\nUnsatisfactory: The most serious rating, indicating widespread or severe noncompliance. Almost always triggers formal enforcement action which may include management agent replacement, Performance Improvement Plan, or HAP contract notice."},{"heading":"How Deficiencies Are Weighted and Accumulated","body":"The overall MOR rating is not a simple average — it reflects the nature, severity, and pattern of deficiencies found across all review areas.\n\nHigh-impact deficiency areas include: Fair Housing violations, EIV noncompliance (given the mandatory nature of 24 CFR 5.233), certification errors affecting tenant eligibility or rent calculations, and financial mismanagement that threatens the property's viability.\n\nPattern vs. isolated deficiencies: A single incorrectly calculated rent might be a data entry error. Ten incorrectly calculated rents suggest a systemic training or process failure. Reviewers look for patterns because patterns indicate the problem will recur.\n\nCarry-forward findings: If a prior MOR identified deficiencies that were supposed to be corrected, and the current review finds they were not corrected — or the same type of deficiency recurred — the reviewer will treat this as an aggravating factor. Repeat findings are taken very seriously.\n\nSeverity designations: Some items on Form 9834 are marked as critical. A single critical deficiency can, by itself, significantly pull a rating down. Know which items are critical and make sure your client is clean on every one."},{"heading":"The Corrective Action Plan (CAP) Process","body":"Every MOR finding must be addressed through a Corrective Action Plan. The CAP specifies: what the deficiency is, what corrective steps will be taken, who is responsible, and the target completion date.\n\nCAP timelines: HUD typically requires submission of the CAP within 30 days of receiving the MOR report. Corrective actions may have 30, 60, or 90-day completion timelines depending on complexity.\n\nCAP format: There is no single required template, but the plan must be specific and actionable. Vague commitments such as 'we will improve our tenant file procedures' are not acceptable.\n\nEvidence of completion: Once corrective actions are implemented, the owner must submit documentation to HUD demonstrating completion — revised policies, copies of retrained staff acknowledgments, corrected tenant file documents, or evidence of financial remediation.\n\nMonitoring: After a Below Average or Unsatisfactory rating, HUD may schedule a follow-up monitoring visit to verify that corrective actions were actually implemented. This is separate from the next full MOR.\n\nAs a consultant, offering to draft and manage the CAP process is a high-value service — many management agents are unfamiliar with the process."},{"heading":"Performance Improvement Plans and Management Agent Replacement","body":"For properties with persistent poor ratings — particularly two or more consecutive Below Average or Unsatisfactory ratings — HUD may require the owner to enter into a Performance Improvement Plan (PIP). A PIP is a formal agreement specifying detailed performance benchmarks, timelines, and consequences for failure.\n\nPIP components typically include: specific measurable goals, monthly or quarterly reporting requirements, scheduled HUD monitoring visits, and clear escalation triggers if benchmarks are not met.\n\nManagement agent replacement: HUD has the authority under the Regulatory Agreement and HAP contract to require the owner to replace the management agent when the current agent is incapable of achieving compliance. This is a significant consequence that disrupts operations and requires transition of all records.\n\nOwner liability: Owners cannot fully insulate themselves from MOR liability by blaming the management agent. The owner has a non-delegable duty to maintain the property in compliance.\n\nConsulting opportunity: An owner who has just received a PIP or been told to replace their management agent is a highly motivated potential consulting client. They need help selecting a new agent, establishing compliance systems, and demonstrating to HUD that management has genuinely changed."},{"heading":"Reading and Using Prior MOR Reports","body":"One of the first things you should do when engaging a new client is obtain and thoroughly read their most recent MOR report. Prior MOR reports are arguably the most valuable diagnostic tool available.\n\nObtaining reports: The owner should have copies of all prior MOR reports. If not, they can request them through their HUD Field Office or PBCA. FOIA requests are also available but slower.\n\nWhat to look for: Focus on recurring findings across multiple years. A deficiency that appeared in two or three successive MORs is almost certainly still present unless deliberate corrective action was taken.\n\nComparing with Form 9834: Map prior findings to specific line items on Form 9834. This lets you create a prioritized checklist for your pre-assessment — you know exactly which items to test first because HUD has already told you they were deficient.\n\nRating trajectory: A property moving from Unsatisfactory to Below Average to Satisfactory shows a positive trajectory, which HUD views favorably. The trajectory matters as much as the most recent rating.\n\nConfidentiality: MOR reports may contain sensitive information. Handle them with the same confidentiality you would apply to any client document."}]},{"id":"m73","unit":"u7","number":3,"title":"The On-Site Review — What Happens During a MOR","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Scheduling, Notice, and Pre-Visit Preparation","body":"MORs are announced in advance — HUD is not conducting a surprise inspection. Typically, the reviewer will contact the owner or management agent at least two to four weeks before the review date.\n\nThe advance notice letter will specify: the scheduled review date(s), the desk review documents required and submission deadline (usually one to two weeks before the on-site visit), the reviewer's name, and any specific areas of focus.\n\nUpon receiving notice, the management agent should immediately: pull and review all tenant files for completeness, run all required EIV reports, verify that the waiting list is current and documented, confirm all lease and HAP contract dates, and schedule a staff briefing on what to expect.\n\nA two-to-four week prep window is workable if the property has good compliance habits. If not, it is a scramble. This is why your consulting value is highest when you work with a client on an ongoing basis — not just in crisis mode.\n\nPreparing staff: Every staff member who will interact with the reviewer should be briefed — including the property manager, leasing agent, maintenance supervisor, and any on-site bookkeeper."},{"heading":"Tenant File Sampling — The Statistical Logic","body":"One of the most important elements of the on-site review is the tenant file sample. The reviewer will not look at every file — but enough to draw conclusions about the quality of certifications, documentation, and income verification practices.\n\nStandard sampling guidance: HUD typically reviews a sample of 20% of occupied units, with a minimum of 10 files and a maximum of 50 files for very large properties. The reviewer selects the sample — it is not the management agent's choice.\n\nWhat the reviewer looks for in each file: complete application package, correct calculation of annual income, proper verification of all income sources, correct identification and valuation of assets, proper certification timing, required signatures on all forms, current leases, income limits compliance, and EIV documentation.\n\nMove-in files vs. recertification files: Reviewers often pay extra attention to recent move-ins (last 12 months) because initial eligibility determinations are high-stakes. They also examine recent annual recertifications closely because HOTMA changes have created new compliance requirements as of January 1, 2025.\n\nFile organization: A disorganized file takes three times as long for the reviewer to examine and creates the impression of poor management. Implement a standard file organization with a cover sheet checklist so every file is in identical order."},{"heading":"Unit Inspections During the MOR","body":"Although the MOR is not a physical inspection in the NSPIRE sense, reviewers do conduct brief unit walkthroughs as part of the on-site visit. These unit visits verify that units are actually occupied by the persons listed in the tenant files, that unit transfers and vacancies are properly documented, and to assess general maintenance responsiveness.\n\nWhat the reviewer observes: Physical condition is noted but not formally scored using NSPIRE criteria. The reviewer is looking for evidence of deferred maintenance that might indicate financial mismanagement or neglect. They will also note obvious lease violations and flag any habitability concerns for follow-up.\n\nTenant interviews: The reviewer may conduct brief, voluntary interviews with tenants during the unit visits about: their understanding of their rent and utility allowance, maintenance issues and whether they were addressed, management responsiveness, and whether they felt treated fairly in the application process.\n\nTransfer documentation: Unit transfers must be fully documented with a new certification, updated lease, and transfer letter. Reviewers often check that transfer documentation is complete because transfers are frequently handled informally without proper paperwork.\n\nVacant units: The reviewer will check the vacancy log against the physical reality. Unexplained discrepancies raise flags about occupancy rates and potential rent roll manipulation."},{"heading":"Staff Interviews — Preparing Your Team","body":"Staff interviews are a standard component of the on-site MOR. The reviewer will typically interview the property manager, the leasing agent, and possibly the maintenance supervisor. These interviews assess staff knowledge of HUD requirements — not just whether the files look right.\n\nWhat reviewers ask property managers: How do you process annual recertifications? What is your EIV policy and how do you use it? How do you handle income discrepancies identified by EIV? What is your process for handling reasonable accommodation requests? How do you manage your waiting list? How do you handle VAWA protection requests?\n\nWhat reviewers ask leasing agents: How do you select applicants from the waiting list? How do you determine if an applicant is income-eligible? Do you check EIV for all new move-ins? How do you handle applicants who need a reasonable accommodation in the application process?\n\nPreparing staff: Hold a pre-MOR staff meeting covering the key topics likely to arise. Role-play the interview process. Emphasize that 'I don't know but I'll find out' is a perfectly acceptable answer — much better than guessing incorrectly.\n\nCommon staff interview mistakes: Volunteering negative information, contradicting what the files show, expressing frustration with HUD requirements, or being unable to explain basic processes. All of these create additional scrutiny."},{"heading":"The Exit Conference and Post-Review Process","body":"At the conclusion of the on-site visit, the reviewer typically conducts an exit conference with the property manager and/or owner's representative. This is an opportunity for the reviewer to share preliminary observations and give the property a chance to provide clarifying information or documentation.\n\nWhat happens at the exit conference: The reviewer will describe the potential findings they intend to document, explain the basis for each finding, and give the property representative an opportunity to provide additional documentation or context that might address the concern.\n\nResponding at the exit conference: If the reviewer describes a potential finding and you have documentation that addresses it, produce it immediately. If you need to verify something, say so and provide the documentation within 24 hours.\n\nThe MOR report: After the on-site visit, the reviewer prepares a formal written MOR report documenting all findings, the overall rating, and required corrective actions. This report is typically delivered within 30–60 days of the on-site visit.\n\nPost-MOR follow-up: Once the report is received, the corrective action timeline begins. Assign clear ownership for each corrective action item, document completion as you go, and submit the CAP and completion evidence on time. For your consulting business, offering ongoing CAP management as a retainer service provides recurring revenue while delivering measurable value."}]},{"id":"m81","unit":"u8","number":1,"title":"The Desk Review — Documents Required Before the On-Site Visit","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"What Is the Desk Review and Why It Matters","body":"The desk review is the document submission phase of the MOR that occurs before the reviewer arrives on-site. The owner or management agent submits a required document package — typically one to two weeks before the scheduled visit — which the reviewer analyzes to understand the property's compliance posture.\n\nThe desk review package shapes the reviewer's initial perception of the property. A well-organized, complete, and clearly labeled package signals competent management. A disorganized, incomplete package signals problems and causes the reviewer to arrive with heightened scrutiny.\n\nReviewers use the desk review to: identify discrepancies between reported occupancy and financial data, flag potential EIV noncompliance, assess the financial position of the property, and prioritize which tenant files and areas to examine closely during the on-site visit.\n\nAs a consultant, your most concrete pre-MOR service is assembling the desk review package. This requires knowing exactly what is required, verifying that each document is current and accurate, and organizing the package in a professional, logical manner. A consultant who delivers a flawless desk review package before the reviewer even arrives has already improved the property's outcome."},{"heading":"Occupancy and Tenant Data Documents","body":"Occupancy Report / Rent Roll: A current, complete rent roll showing all units, tenant names, unit sizes, contract rents, tenant rents, utility allowances, HAP amounts, move-in dates, and lease expiration dates. This is the foundational document against which many other items are cross-checked. The rent roll must reconcile with both the HAP billing voucher and the property's financial statements.\n\nTenant Income Certification (TIC) Summary: A summary listing all occupied units, the tenant's annual income, household size, income limit category, and effective certification date.\n\nCertification Due List: A list of all upcoming annual recertification due dates, showing which certifications are current, which are in process, and whether any are past due. Any overdue certifications are immediate findings.\n\nMove-In / Move-Out Log: A log of all move-ins and move-outs in the past 12 months, including dates and unit numbers.\n\nOverhoused/Underhoused Report: Documentation of any tenants who are in units larger or smaller than their family size justifies, and what action has been taken. HUD requires owners to offer appropriately sized units when they become available."},{"heading":"EIV System Documentation for the Desk Review","body":"EIV documentation is one of the most heavily scrutinized elements of the desk review. EIV is mandatory under 24 CFR 5.233, and failure to use it correctly is one of the most common MOR findings.\n\nEIV Binder / Master File: Must include: the current EIV Participation Agreement signed by all authorized users, evidence that all required reports are being run at required intervals, documentation of how income discrepancies are being resolved, and security acknowledgment forms for each EIV user.\n\nExisting Tenant Search Report: Documentation showing that the Existing Tenant Search was run for all applicants within the past 120 days of their move-in. Evidence must be in each new tenant's file.\n\nMultiple Subsidy Report: Printed or saved copies of the Multiple Subsidy Report run within the past 12 months. This report identifies tenants potentially receiving duplicate housing assistance.\n\nIncome Report: Documentation that the Income Report is being run at least annually and that discrepancies are being investigated. All income discrepancies must be resolved within specified timeframes.\n\nFailed Pre-Screening Report: Documentation that the Failed Pre-Screening Report is being checked, identifying applicants who could not be pre-screened by EIV. All EIV access must comply with HUD's privacy and security requirements."},{"heading":"Waiting List and Marketing Documents","body":"Current Waiting List: A complete, dated waiting list showing applicant names, application dates, bedroom sizes requested, any preferences claimed, contact information, and status. The list must be maintained in the order applicants applied (or per approved preference system) and free of unexplained gaps.\n\nAffirmative Fair Housing Marketing Plan (AFHMP): The current AFHMP including all required marketing outreach activities targeting underserved populations, marketing materials, and evidence of AFHMP implementation. The AFHMP must be updated every five years. A lapsed AFHMP is an immediate finding.\n\nWaiting List Opening/Closing Notices: Documentation of the most recent waiting list opening and closing notices, including how and where they were published.\n\nTenant Selection Plan (TSP): The current Tenant Selection Plan including admission preferences, screening criteria, and rejection policies. Under HOTMA (effective January 1, 2025), TSPs must be updated to reflect new requirements. A pre-2025 TSP that has not been updated is a finding.\n\nMarketing Records: Evidence of affirmative marketing activities conducted in the past 12 months, including outreach to minority media, organizations serving persons with disabilities, and other underserved groups."},{"heading":"Policy Documents and Administrative Records","body":"House Rules: The current, HUD-approved house rules applicable to all tenants. House rules must be incorporated into or attached to each lease. Changes require proper notice to tenants (typically 30 days) and approval by HUD or the CA. Outdated or unapproved house rules are a finding.\n\nLease Form: A copy of the current HUD model lease form being used. The lease must comply with all current HUD lease requirements including VAWA language, grievance procedures, and termination provisions.\n\nGrievance Procedure: Written documentation of the property's tenant grievance procedure. HUD requires that tenants have a formal process to contest management decisions. The procedure must be in writing and provided to each tenant.\n\nVAWA Policy and Forms: The current VAWA policy including the Emergency Transfer Plan and current versions of HUD Forms 5380 (Notice of VAWA Rights) and 5382 (VAWA Self-Certification Form). VAWA 2022 requirements must be reflected. Using outdated VAWA forms is a finding.\n\nFair Housing Policy: A written fair housing policy including the owner's commitment to equal opportunity in housing, staff training records, and documentation of reasonable accommodation and modification requests and outcomes."}]},{"id":"m82","unit":"u8","number":2,"title":"Financial Documents — What HUD Requires and Why","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Audited Financial Statements","body":"HUD requires owners of assisted multifamily properties to submit annual audited financial statements through iREMS or REAC's Financial Assessment Subsystem (FASS). During a MOR, the reviewer examines the most recent audited statements.\n\nWhat the reviewer looks at: The audit opinion (clean opinion vs. qualified opinion vs. adverse opinion), significant findings in the management letter, financial ratios indicating project viability (occupancy rates, operating ratio, debt coverage ratio), and consistency between audited figures and other submitted documents.\n\nAudit frequency: Most HUD-assisted properties are required to submit annual audits within 9 months of the end of the fiscal year. For properties with fiscal years ending December 31, the audit is due by September 30. Late audits are a finding.\n\nManagement letter findings: The management letter from the auditor often contains findings about internal controls, compliance issues, or accounting concerns. If the management letter identified issues, the reviewer will want to know what corrective actions were taken. Have documented responses ready.\n\nCommon financial red flags: High operating deficit, Reserve for Replacement below the required minimum, accounts payable significantly overdue, inconsistency between rent roll totals and revenue per the financial statements."},{"heading":"Budget and Financial Planning Documents","body":"Current Year Budget: The approved operating budget for the current fiscal year, broken down by income and expense categories. The budget must be realistic — a budget that projects 100% occupancy when the property runs at 85% raises immediate credibility questions. Reviewers will compare budgeted rent revenue against the current rent roll.\n\nBudget Approval: Evidence that the budget was reviewed and approved by the ownership entity. For properties requiring HUD budget approval under the Regulatory Agreement, evidence of that approval must be included.\n\nPrior Year Budget-to-Actual: A comparison of last year's budget against actual results, with explanations for significant variances. Large unexplained variances — particularly on the expense side — suggest inadequate financial oversight.\n\nCapital Improvement Plan: Documentation of planned capital improvements and how they will be funded. Properties with aging infrastructure that have no capital improvement plan raise concerns about long-term viability."},{"heading":"Reserve for Replacement — Requirements and Documentation","body":"The Reserve for Replacement (RFR) is a dedicated escrow account required by the HUD Regulatory Agreement for the purpose of funding capital repairs and replacements — roofs, HVAC systems, appliances, elevators, and other long-lived assets.\n\nRequired funding: The minimum monthly RFR deposit is specified in the Regulatory Agreement. This minimum deposit must be made every month without exception. Missing or irregular deposits are findings.\n\nRFR balance documentation: Submit the current RFR account statement showing the balance, recent deposits, and any recent withdrawals. The statement must show consistent monthly deposits.\n\nWithdrawal documentation: Any withdrawal from the RFR account for capital repairs must have prior HUD approval. Document every approved withdrawal with the HUD approval letter, the purpose of the withdrawal, and receipts for work performed. Unapproved withdrawals are a serious finding.\n\nRFR Plan / Capital Needs Assessment (CNA): A professional assessment of anticipated capital needs over the next 20 years demonstrating whether the current RFR balance and funding rate are sufficient. A significantly underfunded RFR is a flag for the property's long-term financial viability."},{"heading":"HAP Billing and Voucher Documentation","body":"The HAP (Housing Assistance Payments) billing voucher is the mechanism through which HUD pays rental assistance to the property owner on behalf of assisted tenants. Accurate HAP billing is a fundamental MOR requirement.\n\nCurrent HAP Voucher: The most recent month's HAP billing voucher, showing the unit number, tenant name, contract rent, tenant rent, utility allowance, and HAP amount for each assisted unit. The totals must reconcile with the financial statements.\n\nHAP Voucher Reconciliation: For each unit on the voucher, the HAP amount must exactly match what is calculated on the tenant's current certification. Delayed voucher updates result in either overpayments or underpayments of HAP.\n\nTRACS reconciliation: Some reviewers request a reconciliation of HAP billing against TRACS (Tenant Rental Assistance Certification System). TRACS discrepancies — units on the voucher that don't match TRACS records — are serious compliance concerns.\n\nRetroactive corrections: If HAP billing errors are discovered, they must be corrected retroactively. Overpayments must be repaid; underpayments may be submitted as corrections. Document the discovery, correction, and submission of all retroactive adjustments.\n\nUtility Allowances: The utility allowance schedule being applied must be current, HUD-approved, and correctly reflected on both certifications and the HAP voucher. An outdated utility allowance schedule is a common finding."},{"heading":"Insurance, Taxes, and Regulatory Agreement Compliance","body":"Insurance Coverage: Proof of current insurance coverage meeting Regulatory Agreement and HUD guidelines — property and casualty insurance (with HUD as an additional insured where required), liability insurance, boiler and machinery insurance where applicable, and fidelity bond coverage for employees handling funds. Lapsed or insufficient coverage is a finding.\n\nReal Estate Tax Payment: Evidence that property taxes are current. Tax delinquency is a significant financial red flag. Even tax-exempt properties must document their exemption status.\n\nRegulatory Agreement Compliance: The Regulatory Agreement governs distributions, required owner contributions, and restrictions on property use. The reviewer will assess whether the owner is in compliance with all provisions. Unauthorized distributions to the owner are findings.\n\nMortgage Payment Status: Evidence that the underlying HUD-insured mortgage (if applicable) is current. A mortgage in default is a serious regulatory concern.\n\nProperty Management Contract: The current management contract between the owner and management agent, including the management fee, scope of services, and term. HUD must have approved the management agent, and evidence of current HUD approval is required."}]},{"id":"m83","unit":"u8","number":3,"title":"Organizing and Submitting the Perfect Desk Review Package","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Creating a Desk Review Document Index","body":"A professional desk review package begins with a comprehensive document index — a table of contents listing every document included, the page number where it begins, and the date it was prepared or last updated.\n\nThe index should follow the same structure as Form 9834 review areas: Occupancy Documents, EIV Documentation, Financial Documents, Waiting List/Marketing Documents, and Policy/Administrative Documents.\n\nDate stamping: Every document should clearly show when it was prepared or the period it covers. Print 'Prepared for MOR Review — [Date]' on any document you create specifically for the review.\n\nCover letter: Include a professional cover letter from the management agent addressed to the reviewer, identifying the property (name, address, FHA/contract number), introducing the management team, providing a brief status summary, and expressing commitment to compliance.\n\nDeficiency acknowledgment: If you know that a compliance issue exists, address it proactively in the cover letter accompanied by corrective action documentation. Proactive disclosure is viewed far more favorably than attempting to hide problems.\n\nSubmission format: Confirm with the reviewer whether they prefer physical copies, electronic files, or access to a document sharing platform. An organized electronic folder with clearly named files is increasingly preferred."},{"heading":"Common Desk Review Deficiencies — And How to Prevent Them","body":"Top desk review deficiencies: (1) EIV master file incomplete or showing reports not run at required intervals; (2) Tenant certifications with past-due dates; (3) AFHMP expired or not updated in more than five years; (4) Tenant Selection Plan not updated post-HOTMA (January 1, 2025); (5) RFR account with missing monthly deposits or undocumented withdrawals; (6) Waiting list not current; (7) Current VAWA forms not in use (outdated versions of HUD 5380/5382); (8) HAP voucher amounts not reconciling with current certifications.\n\nPre-submission checklist: Before submitting the desk review package, run through a comprehensive checklist against Form 9834 line items. Assign a staff member to physically check each item. Never submit a desk review package that has not been reviewed by someone other than the person who assembled it.\n\nEIV self-audit: Run all required EIV reports immediately before assembling the desk review package. Print the reports and verify that dates are current. Confirm that all income discrepancies shown on the reports have been documented and resolved.\n\nCertification currency check: Pull a list of all tenants and sort by certification anniversary date. Identify any with past-due or upcoming certifications. Complete any past-due certifications immediately."},{"heading":"Curing Deficiencies Before Submission","body":"The period between receiving the MOR notice and submitting the desk review package is your best opportunity to correct compliance issues before they become formal findings.\n\nWhat can be cured quickly: Missing signatures on certifications (if tenant is still in place), expired AFHMP (update and submit new version with HUD), outdated VAWA forms (replace with current versions in tenant files), EIV reports not recently run (run them now), waiting list not purged recently (conduct documented purge), missing insurance certificate (request from carrier immediately).\n\nWhat requires more time or HUD approval: Incorrect income calculations from prior years (may require retroactive certification corrections and HAP adjustments), unauthorized RFR withdrawals (must be discussed with HUD), Tenant Selection Plan updates (draft, submit to HUD for review).\n\nDocument the cure: Every deficiency you correct before the MOR must be documented. If the reviewer identifies the same issue during the file sample and you have corrective action documentation in hand, the finding may be reduced from a significant deficiency to a minor one.\n\nWhat not to alter: Under no circumstances should original documents be altered, backdated, or falsified to remove deficiencies. This is fraud, and HUD reviewers are trained to detect it. The consequences — including False Claims Act liability and potential criminal referral — are severe."},{"heading":"Electronic vs. Physical Desk Review Packages","body":"Electronic package requirements: When submitting electronically, use PDF format for all documents. Use a consistent naming convention (e.g., 'Section_01_OccupancyReport_2025.pdf'). If using a shared drive or portal, create a clear folder structure matching your document index. Provide the reviewer with direct access and confirm receipt.\n\nElectronic signature considerations: Some documents must bear original signatures. When submitting electronically, scan signed originals rather than submitting digital signature versions, unless the reviewer has confirmed digital signatures are accepted.\n\nPhysical package best practices: Use a binder with numbered tabs matching your index. Use clear tab dividers with typed labels. Include two copies if the reviewer requests them. Ship via traceable carrier with delivery confirmation.\n\nHybrid approach: Many consultants use a hybrid approach — submit an electronic package in advance and bring a physical binder on-site for reference during the review. This allows both the reviewer and the management team to reference documents easily during the exit conference.\n\nTechnology platforms: Some PBCAs use specific portals for desk review submissions. Confirm the required platform with the reviewer when the review is scheduled. Missing a portal-specific upload requirement can delay the review and create a negative impression."},{"heading":"Maintaining a Continuous Desk Review Readiness Posture","body":"The most successful properties maintain a continuous state of desk review readiness — meaning they could assemble a complete, accurate desk review package within one week at any time of year.\n\nThe 'always ready' system: Establish a monthly compliance calendar that tracks EIV report due dates, certification anniversary dates, RFR deposit confirmations, waiting list maintenance dates, and policy review intervals.\n\nQuarterly mock desk reviews: Conduct a quarterly internal desk review using Form 9834 as the checklist. Assign the task to someone other than the person responsible for the documents — this simulates the reviewer's perspective.\n\nRetention policies: Know how long to keep each document type. HUD generally requires tenant file retention for three years after the tenant vacates. Financial records must be retained per the Regulatory Agreement. EIV records have specific retention requirements.\n\nConsulting application: Offer an 'MOR Readiness Assessment' as a standalone consulting product — a fixed-price engagement reviewing current desk review posture, identifying gaps, and providing a prioritized remediation plan. Low-risk for the client; excellent entry point for a longer-term relationship."}]},{"id":"m91","unit":"u9","number":1,"title":"The Complete Tenant File — Structure and Required Documents","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Why the Tenant File Is the Heart of MOR Compliance","body":"The tenant file is the single most important document in the MOR review. Every determination about tenant eligibility, rent calculation, certification accuracy, and fair housing compliance begins and ends with the tenant file. A complete, organized tenant file is your strongest defense against MOR findings.\n\nHUD Handbook 4350.3 REV-1 Change-4, Chapter 9, provides detailed guidance on tenant file requirements. While no specific physical organization is mandated, HUD's expectation is that every file contains all required documents in a form that allows the reviewer to verify compliance.\n\nThe dual purpose of tenant files: Administrative (managing the tenancy) and audit (demonstrating compliance). Build your files to serve both purposes.\n\nFile components by tenancy phase: Application/Move-In (initial contact through occupancy), Active Tenancy (annual and interim certifications, lease renewals, correspondence), and Move-Out (notice of termination, vacate inspection, security deposit disposition).\n\nConsultant role: During a pre-MOR file review, you physically open each file and assess it against a required-documents checklist. Doing this for all files — not just the expected sample — before the review is a core service offering."},{"heading":"Application Package — Required Documents","body":"Required application documents: (1) Written application signed by the applicant, including all adult household members' names, ages, and SSNs; (2) HUD Form 9887 (Release of Information/Privacy Act Notice) signed by all adult household members; (3) HUD Form 9887-A (Applicant/Tenant Consent to Release of Information); (4) Written screening report documenting application of the Tenant Selection Plan criteria; (5) Notice to applicant of approval or rejection — rejection notices must state the reason and include appeal rights; (6) Evidence that the EIV Existing Tenant Search was run before move-in.\n\nSSN requirements: All applicants and household members eligible for assistance must provide Social Security numbers or certify that they do not have one. Documentation of SSN verification (Social Security card, government-issued document) must be in the file.\n\nCriminal background screening: If the TSP includes criminal background screening, documentation of screening results and the disposition (approved/denied) must be in the file. Post-HOTMA, blanket bans on persons with criminal records may conflict with fair housing guidance.\n\nCitizenship/eligible immigration status: HUD Form 214 (Declaration of Citizenship) or equivalent immigration status documentation for each household member."},{"heading":"Move-In Documentation and the Initial Lease Package","body":"HUD-prescribed lease: The executed HUD model lease, signed by all adult household members and the management agent, dated the first day of occupancy. The lease must incorporate by reference current house rules and VAWA provisions. Backdated move-in packages are a common finding and a red flag.\n\nInitial Tenant Income Certification (TIC): The completed and executed TIC (HUD Form 50059 or equivalent TRACS-compatible form) showing the initial income calculation, total tenant payment, HAP amount, and effective date. The TIC must be signed by all tenants and the management agent. The effective date must match the move-in date.\n\nSupporting income verifications: Every income source listed on the TIC must be supported by third-party verification in the file. Verbal verifications are not acceptable for income verification.\n\nUnit inspection form: A completed move-in unit inspection documenting the condition of the unit at move-in, signed by both the tenant and management.\n\nSecurity deposit documentation: If a security deposit was collected, the receipt must be in the file along with documentation of where it is held — typically a separate interest-bearing account as required by the lease and applicable state law."},{"heading":"Ongoing File Maintenance During Active Tenancy","body":"Annual certification documents: Each annual certification generates a new TIC, supporting income verifications, and any updated asset documentation. Post-HOTMA, asset self-certification is permissible for households with total assets under $50,000.\n\nInterim certification documents: Interim certifications are required when a reportable change in household income or composition occurs between annual certifications. Every interim must be fully documented with the triggering event, updated income verifications, and a revised TIC.\n\nCorrespondence: All significant correspondence between the property and the tenant — notices, lease violations, maintenance requests, and responses — should be in the tenant file or a related management file.\n\nReasonable accommodation/modification requests: All requests, the management team's response, supporting documentation, and outcome must be in the file. Fair housing law requires a documented interactive process. A missing or incomplete reasonable accommodation file is both a MOR finding and a fair housing liability.\n\nEIV income discrepancy resolution: Documentation showing that any EIV income discrepancy was investigated and resolved must be in the file or the EIV master binder with a cross-reference."},{"heading":"Move-Out Documentation and File Retention","body":"Termination notice: Documentation of how the tenancy ended — either the tenant's written notice to vacate, or the management agent's notice of lease termination with grounds and required notice period. For management-initiated terminations, the file must show the grievance process was offered.\n\nMove-out inspection: A completed move-out unit inspection form, signed by management, with documentation of whether the tenant was offered the opportunity to attend.\n\nSecurity deposit disposition: A written accounting provided to the tenant within the timeframe required by state law (typically 14–30 days). Any deductions must be itemized and supported by documentation.\n\nFinal accounting: If the tenant owed any back rent or other charges, documentation of the balance calculation and any collection efforts. If a tenant was evicted, documentation of the court proceedings.\n\nFile retention: HUD requires tenant files to be retained for a minimum of three years after the tenant vacates. Some state laws require longer retention. Financial records must be retained per the Regulatory Agreement, typically 3–7 years. Implement a formal records retention and destruction policy."}]},{"id":"m92","unit":"u9","number":2,"title":"Annual and Interim Certifications — Timing, Process, and Compliance","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Annual Recertification — Timing and Scheduling","body":"Annual recertifications must be completed on or before the tenant's certification anniversary date. Late recertifications are one of the most common MOR findings and represent real financial risk because HAP payments may be inappropriate if rent calculations are not current.\n\nThe 120-day rule: HUD requires owners to issue the recertification notice to the tenant no later than 120 days before the certification anniversary date. This rolling window allows time to gather verifications and correct errors before the effective date.\n\nTRACS transmission: Completed certifications must be transmitted to TRACS within 60 days of the effective date. Late TRACS transmissions create discrepancies in HUD's records and are findings.\n\nTracking system: Every property needs a certification tracking system. The critical output is a list of certifications due in the next 120 days, which should be reviewed by the manager at least monthly. Properties that allow certifications to slip are almost always those without a functional tracking system."},{"heading":"Interim Certifications — When They Are Required","body":"Mandatory interim triggers — income increases: When a tenant's income increases, the owner must process an interim certification to capture the increase and adjust the tenant's rent. Under the standard HUD rule, income increases take effect on the first of the month following the reportable change.\n\nMandatory interim triggers — household composition changes: When a new adult is added to the household, their income must be verified and an interim certification processed. Adding an adult household member always requires an update since the new person's income must be verified and added.\n\nOptional interim recertification for income decreases: HUD allows tenants to request an interim recertification when their income decreases significantly. Most properties process these to ensure tenants are not overburdened by rent they can no longer afford.\n\nInterim certification documentation: An interim certification requires a new TIC, updated income verifications for any income sources that changed, and tenant signature. It does not restart the annual certification clock — the next annual certification remains due on the original anniversary date."},{"heading":"Income Verification Hierarchy — The Four Methods","body":"HUD Handbook 4350.3 establishes a strict hierarchy for income verification. Property managers must use the highest-quality verification method available. Using a lower-tier method when a higher-tier method is available is a finding.\n\nTier 1 — EIV system: The highest-priority verification. For income sources that EIV reports (Social Security, SSI, federal wage data), EIV data must be considered and reconciled against tenant-reported income.\n\nTier 2 — Upfront Income Verification (UIV): Third-party verification obtained directly from the source, without tenant involvement in the transmission. Examples: employer verification obtained directly by the property, IRS tax transcript, benefit verification from SSA obtained directly.\n\nTier 3 — Third-party written verification: A signed, dated letter from the income source sent to the property — either directly or through the tenant. A verification form sent to the employer and returned with an authorized signature qualifies.\n\nTier 4 — Documents provided by the tenant: The lowest tier — pay stubs, bank statements, award letters provided by the tenant. These can be used only when higher-tier verification is not available and must be supported by tenant certification. Using Tier 4 when Tier 1–3 is available is a finding."},{"heading":"The Tenant Income Certification Form (TIC / HUD 50059)","body":"The Tenant Income Certification (TIC) — completed on HUD Form 50059 or a TRACS-compatible equivalent — captures household composition, income, assets, and the resulting rent calculation. Every item must be accurate and supported by documentation.\n\nHousehold composition section: Lists every household member by name, relationship, date of birth, and SSN. All persons residing in the unit must be listed. Unlisted household members whose income would not be counted is a serious finding.\n\nIncome section: Lists every income source for every household member with the calculated annual amount. Common errors include: omitting part-time employment income, failing to count recurring overtime or bonuses, and incorrectly treating irregular income as non-recurring.\n\nAsset section: Lists all household assets and the actual or imputed income they generate. Post-HOTMA (January 1, 2025), households with total assets under $50,000 may use a self-certification form rather than third-party verification. Above $50,000, full verification is required.\n\nCalculation section: Shows the calculation from total annual income to TTP and resulting HAP amount. Errors in this calculation directly affect HAP amounts.\n\nSignature section: The TIC must be signed and dated by all adult household members and by an authorized representative of the management agent. Missing signatures are an immediate finding."},{"heading":"Common Certification Errors and How to Prevent Them","body":"Error 1 — Incorrect income calculation: Failing to annualize income correctly. For hourly employees, the calculation must account for actual hours worked, overtime patterns, and seasonal variations. For self-employed tenants, the net income calculation must follow HUD guidance.\n\nError 2 — Missing or expired income verifications: A certification with no supporting verification document in the file is an immediate finding. Verifications must be dated within 120 days of the certification effective date.\n\nError 3 — Incorrect asset calculation: Many managers undercount assets — missing retirement accounts, IRAs, and real property equity. Imputed income from assets exceeding $5,000 must be calculated using the HUD passbook rate.\n\nError 4 — Incorrect income limit application: Using the wrong limit category (e.g., low income vs. very low income) is a fundamental eligibility error.\n\nError 5 — Certification timing errors: A certification effective date that doesn't match the anniversary date, or a certification processed more than 60 days late, are both findings.\n\nPrevention strategy: Implement a two-person quality control review for every certification before it is transmitted to TRACS. The second reviewer uses a checklist to verify income, assets, household composition, signatures, and effective date. This single practice eliminates the majority of certification errors."}]},{"id":"m93","unit":"u9","number":3,"title":"Special Certification Situations","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Live-In Aide Requirements and Documentation","body":"A live-in aide is a person who resides with an elderly person or person with disabilities and is essential to the care and well-being of the person. A tenant may have a live-in aide as a reasonable accommodation if: (1) the tenant has a disability, (2) the aide is essential to their care, and (3) the request is reasonable.\n\nScreening the live-in aide: The management agent may screen the aide for criminal history and other legitimate concerns — but may not require the aide to meet income or financial standards. The aide has no tenancy rights of their own. If the disabled person vacates, the aide must also vacate.\n\nCertification treatment: The live-in aide is listed on the TIC as a household member but their income is not counted in the eligibility determination or rent calculation. The household is entitled to a unit of appropriate size to accommodate the aide.\n\nDocumentation in the file: Must contain the written reasonable accommodation request, the management agent's written response, medical documentation (if provided), move-in documentation for the aide, and documentation that the aide's screening was conducted appropriately."},{"heading":"Student Eligibility Rules Under Section 8","body":"General rule: A student enrolled in an institution of higher education is not eligible for Section 8 assistance unless they meet one of the exemptions.\n\nExemptions: A student is eligible if they are: (1) over age 24; (2) married; (3) have dependent children; (4) a veteran; (5) a person with disabilities who was receiving Section 8 assistance as of November 30, 2005; or (6) individually eligible and their parental income would qualify the student for assistance.\n\nParental income test: For a student who is a dependent under IRS rules and does not meet any of the above exemptions, the parents' income must be included in the eligibility determination. If combined household income exceeds the applicable income limit, the student is not eligible.\n\nPart-time vs. full-time: The student restrictions apply to part-time as well as full-time students. A student who drops below full-time status remains subject to the restrictions.\n\nDocumentation: The file must contain documentation of the student's enrollment status, which exemption applies (if any), and supporting documentation for the exemption claimed (e.g., marriage certificate, DD-214 for veteran status). Annual verification of enrollment status is required."},{"heading":"Mixed-Status Families — Prorated Assistance","body":"A mixed-status family is a household in which some members are U.S. citizens or eligible immigrants and others are neither. HUD rules require prorated assistance for mixed-status families.\n\nThe prorated assistance rule: A mixed-status family receives assistance prorated to the percentage of the household who are eligible. If 3 of 4 household members are eligible, the family receives 75% of the assistance they would receive if all members were eligible.\n\nCalculation: First determine what total assistance would be if all members were eligible. Then multiply by the fraction of eligible members. This calculation is documented on the TIC.\n\nThe ineligible member's income: Income from ineligible family members is counted in the eligibility determination even though those members do not receive assistance. This can make a mixed-status family ineligible if the ineligible member's income pushes total income over the limit.\n\nDocumentation: HUD Form 214 (Declaration of Citizenship/Immigration Status) for each household member, evidence of immigration status review for any non-citizen member, the prorated calculation, and documentation of the tenant's understanding."},{"heading":"Minimum Rent, Hardship Exemptions, and Zero Income","body":"Minimum rent: HUD sets a minimum rent of $25 per month for Section 8 new construction and substantial rehabilitation properties. The minimum rent applies even when the calculated tenant rent would otherwise be zero or near zero.\n\nHardship exemption: Tenants may request a hardship exemption if paying the minimum rent would cause financial hardship. Qualifying circumstances include: loss of employment, death of a family member, medical emergency, or similar extraordinary circumstances. The request must be in writing.\n\nProcessing the hardship request: Upon receiving a hardship exemption request, the owner must suspend the minimum rent for 90 days while evaluating the request. If the owner determines the hardship is genuine and will continue, the exemption is granted.\n\nDocumentation: The file must contain the written hardship exemption request, evidence of the hardship (if provided), the owner's written determination, and documentation that rent collection was properly suspended during evaluation.\n\nZero income households: A household reporting zero income requires signed zero-income certifications from each adult and investigation of how the household is meeting basic living expenses. EIV will often show whether undisclosed income exists."},{"heading":"Unit Transfers, Household Composition Changes, and VAWA Emergency Transfers","body":"Documentation requirements for a transfer: A unit transfer requires a new certification effective on the transfer date, a new lease (or lease amendment) for the new unit, a move-out inspection of the old unit, a move-in inspection of the new unit, a transfer approval letter, and updated TRACS transmission. All documentation must be in the tenant file.\n\nHousehold composition changes — adding members: When a new adult is added to the household, their income must be verified and an interim certification processed. When a child is born or joins the household, a certification update is required.\n\nRemoving household members: When a household member permanently leaves (through death, departure, or divorce), an interim certification is processed. If the remaining household is underhoused, the owner may offer an appropriately sized unit at the next available opportunity.\n\nEmergency transfers under VAWA: Under VAWA 2022, a victim of domestic violence is entitled to an emergency transfer to another unit on the property or to another property in the owner's portfolio. The emergency transfer documentation requirements are detailed and must be handled in accordance with the property's Emergency Transfer Plan."}]},{"id":"m94","unit":"u9","number":4,"title":"HOTMA Changes to Certifications — What Changed January 1, 2025","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"HOTMA Overview — Why 2025 Is a Watershed Year","body":"The Housing Opportunity Through Modernization Act of 2016 (HOTMA) is the most significant reform to HUD multifamily housing programs in decades. Its implementing regulations affecting Section 8 multifamily occupancy standards became fully effective on January 1, 2025 — meaning every MOR conducted from 2025 forward will evaluate HOTMA compliance.\n\nFor your consulting business: Any client whose policies, TSPs, certification processes, or procedures have not been updated to reflect HOTMA is non-compliant today. The window for 'we're still implementing it' explanations has closed. A pre-2025 Tenant Selection Plan or a pre-2025 asset verification process is an immediate finding in a 2025 MOR.\n\nThe core HOTMA changes affecting certifications: (1) Asset self-certification threshold raised to $50,000; (2) Biennial recertification option for certain households; (3) Tenant Selection Plan mandatory update; (4) New income exclusions; (5) Changed treatment of certain asset types.\n\nHOTMA training gap: Many management agents received limited formal training on HOTMA before the January 1, 2025 effective date. Properties that have not been trained on HOTMA are likely non-compliant in multiple areas — a significant opportunity for your consulting practice."},{"heading":"HOTMA Asset Self-Certification — The $50,000 Threshold","body":"Prior to HOTMA, HUD rules required third-party verification of all assets, regardless of their value. HOTMA introduced a self-certification option that significantly reduces this burden for most households.\n\nThe $50,000 threshold: Under HOTMA (effective January 1, 2025), if a household's total assets do not exceed $50,000, the household may provide a signed self-certification of their assets rather than third-party verification. The management agent may accept this self-certification without seeking independent verification from banks or other institutions.\n\nThe self-certification form: HUD has issued a model self-certification form for asset declaration. The form must be signed by all adult household members and must include a certification that total assets are under the $50,000 threshold. The form must be in the tenant file. A homemade form that doesn't meet HUD requirements is a finding.\n\nAbove $50,000: If a household's total assets exceed $50,000, full third-party verification is required — bank statements, account statements, property value assessments. The owner cannot accept self-certification for these households.\n\nIncome from assets must still be counted: Even when self-certifying, the household must estimate actual income from assets. Self-certification eliminates the need for bank statements — it does not eliminate the counting of asset income in the annual income calculation."},{"heading":"HOTMA Biennial Recertification Option","body":"HOTMA introduced an optional biennial (every-other-year) recertification cycle for certain households, reducing administrative burden significantly for properties with stable tenants.\n\nEligibility for biennial recertification: A household may opt for biennial recertification if all adult household members receive income exclusively from fixed sources — Social Security, Supplemental Security Income (SSI), other public assistance with annual cost-of-living adjustments, or any other non-employment income source that does not vary. Households with any employment income are not eligible.\n\nHow biennial recertification works: Qualifying households complete a full recertification every two years. In the intervening year, the tenant's rent is adjusted for any annual COLA to their fixed income sources without requiring a full recertification.\n\nOwner election: The biennial recertification option is available to owners — it is not a tenant right to demand. The owner must elect to offer it and document this election. Cannot be selectively offered in a discriminatory manner.\n\nRisk note: Implement biennial recertification only when you have robust EIV monitoring to catch income changes between certifications — otherwise, incorrect HAP billing could extend for up to 12 additional months."},{"heading":"HOTMA Income Exclusions and Treatment Changes","body":"New income exclusion — lump sum additions to family assets: HOTMA clarified that one-time lump sum additions to family assets (inheritances, insurance settlements, etc.) are excluded from annual income. These amounts are counted as assets and generate imputed income based on the passbook rate — they do not increase annual income directly.\n\nEarned income from minors: HOTMA confirmed that earned income of full-time students under age 18 is excluded from annual income.\n\nSelf-employment income: HOTMA maintained the net income approach for self-employment (gross receipts minus allowable deductions) and clarified that depreciation is NOT an allowable deduction for HUD purposes.\n\nIncome from assets: Even when a household self-certifies that assets are under $50,000, actual income from those assets must still be counted in the annual income calculation. The self-certification eliminates the need for bank statements — it does not eliminate counting asset income.\n\nManagers using pre-HOTMA income calculation procedures are producing incorrect certifications. Conduct full staff training on HOTMA income treatment changes and document completion of that training."},{"heading":"Mandatory Tenant Selection Plan Updates Under HOTMA","body":"Under HOTMA, all properties were required to update their Tenant Selection Plans to reflect new program requirements by January 1, 2025. A TSP that was last updated before 2025 and has not been reviewed against HOTMA requirements is non-compliant today.\n\nWhat changed in TSP requirements: (1) Updated income limit categories consistent with HOTMA; (2) The asset self-certification option (if the owner is implementing it); (3) Updated criminal history screening language consistent with HUD guidance on individualized assessments; (4) Current VAWA 2022 requirements including emergency transfer procedures; (5) Biennial recertification option language if applicable.\n\nHUD review of updated TSPs: HUD or the CA must review and approve updated TSPs. Properties cannot unilaterally implement TSP changes without HUD approval. The approval process must be completed before new policies go into effect.\n\nDistributing the updated TSP: Once approved, the updated TSP must be provided to all applicants on the waiting list (notice of material changes), made available to any applicant upon request, and posted in the management office.\n\nConsulting opportunity: TSP review and update is one of the most in-demand post-HOTMA consulting services. Many management agents know their TSP needs updating but lack the expertise to do it correctly or navigate the HUD approval process."}]},{"id":"m101","unit":"u10","number":1,"title":"Income Calculation — Getting It Right Every Time","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Annual Income — What to Count and What to Exclude","body":"Annual income is all amounts, monetary or not, which are anticipated to be received from a source outside the family during the 12-month period following the effective date of certification. The 'anticipated' nature is critical — you are projecting the next 12 months, not averaging the last 12.\n\nWhat is included: Wages, salaries, tips, overtime, bonuses, and commissions from employment; net income from a business or profession; Social Security, pensions, and annuities; welfare assistance; alimony and child support; recurring gifts; income from assets; and any other regular expected income.\n\nKey exclusions: Casual, sporadic, or irregular gifts; amounts specifically for medical expenses; impairment-related work expenses for disabled persons; income earned by full-time students over a certain threshold; certain foster care payments; and income from assets below $5,000 (subject to passbook rate imputation above $5,000).\n\nThe projection challenge: Because annual income is a projection, property managers must exercise judgment about what is 'anticipated.' An employee who just started a new job should have income calculated at the new rate. An employee who just lost their job should have income adjusted to reflect unemployment benefits or zero. Use the best current information available."},{"heading":"Adjusted Income — Deductions That Reduce Tenant Rent","body":"Adjusted income is annual income minus applicable HUD deductions. It is adjusted income — not annual income — that is used to calculate the tenant's share of rent (Total Tenant Payment). Managers who fail to apply all applicable deductions are overcharging tenants and creating certification errors.\n\nDependent deduction: $480 per year for each dependent (family member who is not the head, co-head, or spouse, and who does not pay rent).\n\nElderly/disabled household deduction: $400 per year for any household in which the head, co-head, or spouse is elderly (62 or older) or disabled. This is a flat deduction per household — one $400 deduction regardless of how many elderly/disabled members.\n\nMedical expense deduction for elderly/disabled households: Out-of-pocket medical expenses exceeding 3% of annual income for elderly or disabled households may be deducted. This includes insurance premiums, unreimbursed medical costs, and prescription costs. Requires documentation and is often missed or miscalculated.\n\nChildcare deduction: Reasonable childcare expenses for children under 13 that enable a family member to work, look for work, or attend school full-time may be deducted. Documentation of childcare expenses (provider receipts) is required."},{"heading":"Calculating Total Tenant Payment and HAP","body":"The TTP is the greater of: (1) 30% of monthly adjusted income; (2) 10% of monthly gross income; (3) the welfare rent (applicable only in certain welfare-to-work situations); or (4) the minimum rent ($25 or property-specific minimum). Select the highest result from these four calculations.\n\nExample: A household with monthly adjusted income of $800 and monthly gross income of $1,000. 30% of $800 = $240. 10% of $1,000 = $100. The TTP is $240 (the higher of the two). The minimum rent is $25, so TTP remains $240.\n\nThe utility allowance: If the unit has tenant-paid utilities, the utility allowance (UA) is subtracted from the TTP. If TTP is $240 and the UA is $100, the net tenant rent is $140. If the UA exceeds the TTP, the tenant pays no rent and may be entitled to a utility reimbursement.\n\nHAP calculation: HAP = Contract Rent minus Net Tenant Rent. If the contract rent is $900 and net tenant rent is $140, HAP = $760. This amount must match the TIC, the HAP billing voucher, and the amount transmitted to TRACS.\n\nGross rent ceiling: The gross rent (contract rent plus utility allowance) must not exceed the gross rent ceiling established for the property's program and unit type."},{"heading":"Self-Employment Income — The Net Income Approach","body":"For self-employed tenants, HUD counts net income from the business — defined as gross receipts less allowable deductions. Allowable deductions are the ordinary and necessary expenses required to conduct the business, per IRS Schedule C guidance, with the key exception that depreciation is NOT an allowable deduction for HUD purposes.\n\nCommon self-employment situations: Tenants who drive for rideshare services, operate day care in their homes, do lawn care, sell handmade goods, or provide cleaning services must all have their net business income calculated correctly.\n\nDocumentation: The preferred documentation is an IRS tax return with Schedule C from the prior year, with adjustments for anticipated changes. For businesses that have not yet filed a return, the management agent may use business records, bank statements, or signed statements from the tenant.\n\nRental income from owned property: If a tenant owns and rents out real property, net rental income (rent received minus operating expenses, not including mortgage principal or depreciation) is counted as annual income. The property itself is also an asset for asset calculation purposes."},{"heading":"Income Inclusions and Exclusions — The Most Common Mistakes","body":"Overtime and bonus income: If a tenant regularly receives overtime pay or performance bonuses, those amounts are anticipated income and must be counted. A tenant cannot exclude overtime simply by saying 'it's not guaranteed.' Review pay stubs and employer verification for the past 12 months to establish the overtime pattern.\n\nAlimony and child support: Included as annual income to the extent actually received. Child support received on behalf of minors is included in family income.\n\nTips and gratuities: Tips received in cash are included in annual income. EIV wage data will often reflect IRS-reported wages, which may include reported tips. Significant discrepancies between reported wages and EIV data for service workers should prompt investigation.\n\nSocial Security vs. SSI: Both are included. Use the gross Social Security amount before Medicare deduction. Many managers incorrectly use the net after-Medicare-deduction amount.\n\nInheritance and insurance proceeds received as a lump sum: Under HOTMA, these are treated as assets rather than income. The lump sum increases the household's assets — it does not directly increase annual income.\n\nFoster care payments: Most foster care payments are excluded from income if paid specifically for a foster child. Verify the exclusion applies based on the specific payment structure."}]},{"id":"m102","unit":"u10","number":2,"title":"Assets — Definition, Calculation, and HOTMA Changes","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"What Counts as a Household Asset","body":"An asset is any item of value owned by a household member from which income may be generated, even if income is currently not being earned.\n\nBank accounts: All checking and savings accounts, money market accounts, and certificates of deposit belonging to any household member. Joint accounts with non-household members are counted based on the household's percentage share.\n\nInvestment accounts: Stocks, bonds, mutual funds, Treasury securities. Retirement accounts (IRA, 401k, 403b, pension) are included based on the cash value, net of any withdrawal penalty.\n\nReal property (other than primary residence): Under HOTMA, equity in real property other than the household's primary residence is counted as an asset. The equity value is the current fair market value less the outstanding mortgage balance.\n\nLife insurance: Cash value (not face value) of whole life or universal life insurance policies. Term insurance has no cash value and is not counted.\n\nPersonal property held as an investment: Gems, jewelry (over what would normally be used), artwork, antiques held as investments.\n\nExcluded items: Necessary personal property (clothing, furniture, car used for transportation), business assets of an active business, and interests in Indian trust lands."},{"heading":"The $5,000 Rule and Passbook Rate Imputation","body":"When a household's total assets exceed $5,000, HUD requires a comparison between actual income from assets and imputed income calculated using the HUD passbook rate. The greater of the two amounts is counted as income from assets.\n\nThe passbook rate: HUD publishes an annual passbook savings rate approximating the return on low-risk savings accounts (typically around 0.06% annually). Used as a proxy for the return that could theoretically be earned on assets if held in a basic savings account.\n\nThe calculation: Multiply total asset value by the passbook rate to get imputed income. Compare to actual income generated by the assets. Count whichever is higher.\n\nExample: A household has $20,000 in a savings account earning $150/year in interest and an IRA worth $10,000 with no distributions. Total assets = $30,000. Actual income = $150. Imputed income = $30,000 × 0.06% = $18. Since $150 > $18, actual income ($150) is counted.\n\nLow-yield assets: A household with $30,000 in cash under the mattress has actual income of $0. Imputed income at 0.06% = $18. The imputed income ($18) is counted because actual income ($0) is lower.\n\nThe $50,000 HOTMA threshold vs. the $5,000 rule: These are separate rules. The $50,000 threshold determines whether self-certification is permitted. The $5,000 threshold triggers the passbook rate imputation. Both rules can apply simultaneously to the same household."},{"heading":"Verifying Assets — Before and After HOTMA","body":"Pre-HOTMA: All assets required third-party verification regardless of value — bank statements, account statements, property value assessments.\n\nPost-HOTMA (effective January 1, 2025): Households with total assets of $50,000 or less may provide a signed self-certification on the HUD-approved form. No bank statements required. For households above $50,000, third-party verification remains required.\n\nSelf-certification and income from assets: The manager must ask the tenant on the self-certification form to estimate actual income from assets (interest earned, dividends received). This information is used in the passbook rate calculation. Self-certification eliminates the need for bank statements — it does not eliminate the counting of asset income.\n\nUpdating certifications at transition: For tenants certified before January 1, 2025 with full asset verification, the new self-certification method applies at their next recertification. You do not need to retroactively apply the new method to existing certifications.\n\nSuspicious self-certifications: If a tenant self-certifies assets under $50,000 but other information suggests higher asset levels, the manager has the right to request verification. Document the reason to avoid fair housing concerns about selective application."},{"heading":"Disposal of Assets Below Fair Market Value","body":"When a household member disposes of an asset for less than fair market value in the two years preceding the certification, HUD requires that the difference between the fair market value and the amount received be counted as if it were still an asset.\n\nPurpose: This rule prevents tenants from artificially reducing their asset levels to maintain eligibility or lower their rent.\n\nThe calculation: If a household member sold a property worth $80,000 for $60,000 eighteen months ago, the $20,000 difference must be included as an asset in the current certification.\n\nExceptions: Assets disposed of as part of a legal settlement or divorce decree, or pursuant to bankruptcy proceedings, are typically excluded. Also excluded are situations where the disposal was made for a legitimate purpose unrelated to gaining housing benefits.\n\nDocumentation: Document the fair market value at time of disposal, the amount received, the calculation of the 'deemed' asset, and the reason for the below-market transfer (if any exception applies).\n\nCommon situations: Selling a property to a child at below-market price, gifting large sums to family members, withdrawing retirement funds and giving them away, or selling personal property at well below assessed value."},{"heading":"Real Property as an Asset — Post-HOTMA Treatment","body":"Primary residence exclusion: The equity in a tenant's primary residence is excluded from assets. Under HOTMA, equity in real property other than the primary residence is a countable asset.\n\nRetained prior residence: If a tenant retains ownership of a prior primary residence, HOTMA provides a grace period before the equity must be counted as an asset. After the grace period, the equity is a countable asset. Document the property's status at each recertification.\n\nInvestment property: Any real property owned by a household member that is not their primary residence is a countable asset. The asset value is the equity (current fair market value minus outstanding mortgage).\n\nNet rental income: If the investment property generates rent, the net rental income (gross rent minus operating expenses, not including mortgage principal or depreciation) is counted as annual income.\n\nProperty value determination: Use the most recent property tax assessment, a comparable market analysis, or an appraisal. Use a consistent, documented method at each recertification."}]},{"id":"m103","unit":"u10","number":3,"title":"EIV — Mandatory Use, Required Reports, and Security Compliance","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"EIV Overview — What It Is and Why It Is Mandatory","body":"The Enterprise Income Verification (EIV) system is a HUD web-based system that compiles income data from the Social Security Administration and Department of Health and Human Services wage records. It provides property managers with an independent source of income information to compare against tenant-reported income to identify discrepancies.\n\nMandatory use: EIV use is mandatory under 24 CFR 5.233 for all properties participating in covered HUD multifamily housing programs. This is not optional. A property that is not using EIV, or that is using it inconsistently, is in regulatory violation. EIV noncompliance is one of the most heavily weighted MOR findings.\n\nWhat EIV shows: The EIV Income Report displays income reported by federal agencies for each household member with a valid SSN — including Social Security benefits, SSI payments, federal pension income, and wage income reported to the IRS.\n\nWhat EIV does not show: EIV does not capture all income. It does not typically show current-year wages for recent job changes, income from cash employment, self-employment income, or rental income. EIV is a supplement to — not a replacement for — standard income verification.\n\nThe EIV master binder: Every property must maintain an EIV master binder documenting: the Participation Agreement, training completion certificates for all authorized users, reports run with dates, and discrepancy resolution documentation."},{"heading":"The Five Required EIV Reports — Timing and Use","body":"1. Income Report: The cornerstone EIV report. Must be run at each annual recertification for every household and before processing any new move-in. When an income discrepancy is identified, the owner must follow the EIV income discrepancy resolution process.\n\n2. Existing Tenant Search: Must be run for every applicant before move-in. This report searches the HUD database to determine whether the applicant is currently receiving Section 8 or other HUD housing assistance at another location. If the applicant is receiving duplicate assistance, they are ineligible until the prior assistance is terminated.\n\n3. Multiple Subsidy Report: Must be run at least annually for all tenants. This report identifies tenants who may be receiving housing assistance at multiple HUD-assisted properties simultaneously. Each identified situation must be investigated and resolved.\n\n4. Discrepancy Report: Must be run at least annually and reviewed at each annual recertification. This report identifies tenants for whom HUD has flagged income discrepancies between tenant-reported income and EIV data. All discrepancies must be investigated per the resolution timeline.\n\n5. Failed Pre-Screening Report: Must be run for all household members whose SSNs could not be pre-screened by EIV — typically those without SSNs or with SSN data issues."},{"heading":"EIV Income Discrepancy Resolution — The Process","body":"Step 1 — Identify the discrepancy: Compare the income on the current certification against EIV data. A significant discrepancy exists when EIV shows income substantially higher or lower than certified — generally $200 or more per month requires investigation.\n\nStep 2 — Request tenant explanation: Provide the tenant written notice of the discrepancy and request an explanation and supporting documentation. The tenant typically has 10 business days to respond. Document the date notice was sent.\n\nStep 3 — Evaluate the tenant's response: Review the tenant's explanation and documentation. In many cases, the discrepancy is due to a prior job that ended, a Social Security COLA that was correctly adjusted, or a data reporting lag in the EIV system.\n\nStep 4 — Obtain third-party verification: If the tenant's explanation requires verification, obtain independent third-party verification. If the explanation is implausible or the tenant fails to respond, use the EIV data as the basis for corrective action.\n\nStep 5 — Process interim certification if needed: If the investigation confirms that the tenant has been underreporting income, process an interim certification reflecting the corrected income and calculate the resulting rent increase.\n\nDocumentation timeline: HUD requires EIV income discrepancies to be resolved generally within 60 days of discovery. Document every step of the process with dates."},{"heading":"EIV Security Requirements and Authorized User Management","body":"Authorized user registration: Only specifically authorized individuals may access EIV. Authorization requires: completion of HUD's EIV Computer-Based Training (CBT), signing the EIV Participation Agreement, and enrollment as an authorized user. Unauthorized access — even by someone generally authorized but not properly registered — is a violation.\n\nTraining requirements: Each authorized user must complete HUD's online EIV training before receiving access. Training completion certificates must be retained in the EIV master binder. New employees must complete training before accessing the system — using a former employee's credentials is a violation.\n\nData security: EIV reports may not be printed and left unsecured. EIV data may not be transmitted via unencrypted email. EIV data may only be used for its authorized purpose — tenant income verification.\n\nSystem access termination: When an authorized EIV user leaves the organization or changes roles, their EIV access must be immediately terminated. Failure to terminate access for departing employees is a common finding and a serious security vulnerability.\n\nAnnual security review: Conduct an annual review of all authorized EIV users to confirm: all current users are still employed and authorized, all have current training certifications, the Participation Agreement is current, and no former employees retain access. Document this annual review in the EIV master binder."},{"heading":"Building an EIV Compliance System","body":"The EIV compliance calendar: Build EIV report due dates into your certification tracking calendar. For each household, the Income Report must be run at annual recertification. The Existing Tenant Search must be run before each new move-in. The Multiple Subsidy Report must be run annually. The Discrepancy Report must be run annually. Never let these dates slip.\n\nStandard operating procedure (SOP): Every property should have a written EIV SOP that describes: who is authorized to access EIV, which reports must be run at which intervals, how discrepancies are to be documented and resolved, where EIV documentation is maintained, and how security requirements are enforced. The SOP itself is a MOR document.\n\nThe EIV master binder structure: Organize with labeled sections for: (1) Participation Agreement; (2) User authorization and training certificates; (3) Existing Tenant Search reports by move-in date; (4) Annual Income Report run dates and discrepancy resolution documentation; (5) Multiple Subsidy Report documentation; (6) Discrepancy Report documentation; (7) Failed Pre-Screening Report documentation; (8) Security incident log.\n\nConsulting EIV assessments: Offering a standalone EIV compliance assessment — reviewing the EIV master binder, user registrations, and report documentation — is an excellent entry-point consulting service. Most properties have at least some EIV gaps, and fixing them before the MOR delivers concrete, measurable value."}]},{"id":"m111","unit":"u11","number":1,"title":"Waiting List Management — Rules, AFHMP, and Best Practices","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"HUD Waiting List Requirements","body":"The waiting list is the gateway to housing assistance for applicants, and one of the most scrutinized MOR elements. HUD requires waiting lists to be maintained in a non-discriminatory, transparent manner consistent with the property's approved Tenant Selection Plan.\n\nBasic list requirements: The waiting list must document each applicant's name, date and time of application, unit sizes needed, preferences claimed and documentation provided, contact information, and current status (active, contacted, skipped, removed). Applications must be date- and time-stamped.\n\nPreferences: If the property has HUD-approved preferences (e.g., for veterans, displaced persons, persons with disabilities, or persons with local residency), applicants claiming preferences must receive priority processing. Preferences must be in the TSP and applied consistently. Preferences not in the TSP cannot be applied.\n\nSkip and removal policies: The TSP must specify the conditions under which an applicant is skipped (temporarily bypassed but retained) versus removed. Common removal grounds: failure to respond to two contact attempts, income exceeding limits, declining an offered unit without good cause. Document every skip and removal with date and reason."},{"heading":"Waiting List Openings, Closings, and Purges","body":"Opening the waiting list: Must provide broad public notice reaching all community segments including minority populations and persons with disabilities. Requires publication in newspapers of general circulation, marketing to minority media sources, and outreach to organizations serving populations identified in the AFHMP as underserved. Online-only notice is generally insufficient.\n\nThe notice content: Must specify unit sizes available, income limits, application period, how to apply, the nondiscrimination statement, and how persons with disabilities may request accommodations in the application process.\n\nClosing the waiting list: Must be announced publicly with the same broad reach as the opening notice. The notice must advise applicants already on the list that their position is preserved.\n\nPurging the list: The purge process must follow a documented protocol: written notice to each applicant subject to purge, a reasonable response period (typically 30 days), removal only upon failure to respond, and documentation of each removal. A purge that disproportionately removes one demographic group may be discriminatory even if the process was facially neutral.\n\nFrequency: There is no HUD-mandated purge frequency, but as best practice, active lists should be reviewed and purged annually."},{"heading":"The Affirmative Fair Housing Marketing Plan (AFHMP)","body":"The AFHMP is a required document under 24 CFR Part 200 for HUD-assisted properties. It documents the property's strategy for marketing to groups historically underrepresented in the tenant population relative to the surrounding community.\n\nRequired AFHMP content: Description of the property and its programs; demographic analysis of the market area comparing current tenants to community population; identification of groups underrepresented in the tenant population; description of specific marketing activities targeting each underrepresented group; and the property's equal opportunity statement.\n\nAFHMP update frequency: HUD requires the AFHMP to be updated every five years or whenever there is a material change in the property's marketing strategy. An expired AFHMP — one that has not been updated in more than five years — is an immediate MOR finding.\n\nImplementing the AFHMP: During the MOR, the reviewer will examine not only the AFHMP document but also evidence that marketing activities were actually conducted (advertising invoices, outreach letters, minority media contacts). An AFHMP with no implementation evidence is a finding.\n\nHUD approval: Updated AFHMPs must be submitted to and approved by HUD or the CA. The owner may not unilaterally implement a new AFHMP without approval."},{"heading":"Tenant Selection — From Waiting List to Lease","body":"Contacting applicants: Contact the top-ranked applicant (accounting for any preferences) and invite them to apply. Document the contact attempt with date, method, and result. If the first contact attempt is unsuccessful, make at least one additional attempt before skipping.\n\nThe application and screening process: Issue the application, collect required documentation, run the EIV Existing Tenant Search, conduct screening per TSP criteria, and make the eligibility determination. Every step must be documented.\n\nThe rejection letter: If an applicant is rejected, the rejection letter must state: the specific reason for rejection, the right to request an informal hearing, and the deadline for requesting the hearing. Generic rejection letters are a fair housing risk and a MOR finding.\n\nReasonable accommodation in the application process: Applicants with disabilities have the right to request reasonable accommodations in the application process — assistance completing the application, extended response times, or an alternative format. These must be offered, documented, and accommodated unless doing so creates undue hardship.\n\nSelection documentation: Maintain a written record of every applicant in the selection pool — date contacted, result, and disposition. This demonstrates the selection process was conducted consistently per the TSP."},{"heading":"Waiting List Technology and Record-Keeping","body":"Electronic waiting lists: Must retain a complete audit trail of every change to an applicant's status — who made the change, when, and why. If the software doesn't have this audit trail capability, it is inadequate for compliance purposes.\n\nAccessibility of the waiting list application process: The application process must be accessible to persons with disabilities — providing applications in alternative formats upon request, allowing in-person application for those who cannot apply online, and designating a staff member to assist applicants who need help.\n\nFair housing testing: Some fair housing organizations conduct systematic testing of waiting list processes by sending testers who apply for housing. Consistent, documented procedures are the only defense.\n\nThe connection between the waiting list and the AFHMP: Waiting list demographic data is the feedback mechanism for the AFHMP. If the waiting list does not reflect the diversity described in the AFHMP as a target, marketing activities may need to be adjusted.\n\nRecord retention: Waiting list records must be retained for a period sufficient to demonstrate compliance with fair housing requirements — generally three to seven years depending on applicable law. Retain rejected applications as well as approved ones."}]},{"id":"m112","unit":"u11","number":2,"title":"Tenant Selection Plan — HOTMA Requirements and Best Practices","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"What the TSP Must Contain","body":"The Tenant Selection Plan is the property's governing document for how it selects tenants from the waiting list. Every policy, preference, screening criterion, and procedure relating to applicant selection must be in the TSP. If it's not in the TSP, it should not be applied.\n\nRequired TSP elements: (1) Description of the waiting list management process; (2) Income targeting requirements; (3) Bedroom size assignment policies; (4) Tenant selection criteria including credit history, rental history, and criminal history screening standards; (5) The reasonable accommodation process for applicants with disabilities; (6) VAWA protections; (7) The informal hearing/appeal process for rejected applicants; (8) Nondiscrimination statement.\n\nHOTMA-mandated updates (mandatory as of January 1, 2025): The TSP must reflect updated income limit categories consistent with HOTMA, the asset self-certification option if the owner is implementing it, updated criminal history screening language consistent with HUD guidance on individualized assessments, and current VAWA 2022 requirements.\n\nHUD approval: The TSP must be submitted to and approved by HUD or the CA before it takes effect. Maintain documentation of the approval date and the approved version.\n\nDistribution: The approved TSP must be provided to every applicant at the time of application and made available to any tenant upon request."},{"heading":"Criminal History Screening — HUD Guidance and Fair Housing","body":"The disparate impact risk: Because arrest and incarceration rates differ significantly by race, national origin, and other protected classes, a blanket 'no criminal record' policy can have a disparate impact — disproportionately excluding protected class members even without discriminatory intent. Disparate impact is prohibited under the Fair Housing Act.\n\nThe individualized assessment: HUD guidance encourages individualized assessment of criminal history — considering: nature and severity of the offense, time elapsed since the offense, evidence of rehabilitation, and relevance of the offense to housing. A blanket ban on persons with any felony conviction likely creates fair housing liability.\n\nAbsolute exclusions: HUD regulations require exclusion of applicants convicted of methamphetamine production on federally assisted property (mandatory exclusion). HUD also permits exclusion of registered sex offenders required to register for life.\n\nTSP screening criteria must be: specific (describing types and timeframes of disqualifying criminal history), applied consistently to all applicants, compliant with HUD guidance on individualized assessment, reviewed against applicable state law, and clearly documented so that rejection decisions can be explained on a non-discriminatory basis."},{"heading":"Income Targeting Requirements","body":"HUD programs require that a specified percentage of units be occupied by families whose incomes do not exceed certain income limits. Section 8 programs typically require that 40% of new admissions each year be to families at or below 30% AMI (Extremely Low Income).\n\nIncome limit categories: HUD publishes annual income limits for each metropolitan area and non-metropolitan county. For Section 8 housing: Extremely Low Income (30% AMI), Very Low Income (50% AMI), and Low Income (80% AMI). The applicable limits depend on household size.\n\nDocumentation: Maintain a log of all new admissions for the year showing the household's income as a percentage of AMI. At year-end, calculate the percentage of admissions that were Extremely Low Income families.\n\nIncome limits update: HUD updates income limits annually, usually in the spring. The new limits must be applied to all certifications effective on or after the update date. Using outdated income limits is a finding. Subscribe to HUD notifications to receive alerts when new limits are published.\n\nIncome targeting in the TSP: The income targeting requirement should be explicitly described in the TSP, including the applicable percentage. Reviewers check the TSP against actual admission records to assess targeting compliance."},{"heading":"Screening Criteria — Credit and Rental History","body":"Credit history screening: The TSP may specify disqualifying types of negative credit history (e.g., evictions for non-payment within the past three years, open judgments for unpaid rent, active bankruptcies). Criteria must be specific enough to be applied consistently.\n\nRental history: The TSP may require references from prior landlords and specify disqualifying negative rental history (prior lease termination for cause, documented lease violations). Criteria must be specific and consistently applied.\n\nThe Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA): If the property uses consumer credit reports, FCRA requirements apply — obtaining the applicant's written consent before pulling the report, providing adverse action notices when a credit report contributes to a rejection decision, and following proper dispute resolution procedures.\n\nSource of income discrimination: Many states and localities prohibit discrimination against applicants who receive housing vouchers or other public assistance. The TSP screening criteria must not screen out applicants based on source of income where such protections exist.\n\nDomestic violence history: Under VAWA, a person's status as a victim of domestic violence, dating violence, sexual assault, or stalking may not be used as a reason to deny admission. The TSP must explicitly state that victim status is not a basis for rejection."},{"heading":"The Informal Hearing Process for Rejected Applicants","body":"Every rejected applicant has the right to an informal hearing to contest the rejection decision. This right is a HUD requirement. The informal hearing process must be described in the TSP and conducted whenever a rejected applicant requests one.\n\nThe rejection notice: The rejection notice must state the specific reason for rejection, the right to request an informal hearing, the deadline for requesting the hearing (typically 14 days from receipt), how to request it, and who will conduct it.\n\nConducting the hearing: The hearing must be conducted by an impartial party — typically someone who was not involved in the original rejection decision. For small properties, the owner may need to designate an outside party.\n\nThe hearing record: The hearing officer must maintain a written record including the evidence presented, the applicant's arguments, and the decision. The decision must be in writing, stating the factual and legal basis.\n\nVAWA hearing rights: Under VAWA, victims who are rejected based on activity related to their victimization have specific protections in the hearing process. The hearing officer must understand and apply these protections.\n\nDocumentation: Retain documentation of every rejection — the rejection letter, date of mailing, request for hearing (if any), the hearing record, and the decision — for at least three years."}]},{"id":"m113","unit":"u11","number":3,"title":"Fair Housing, Section 504, and Reasonable Accommodations","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"The Seven Federal Fair Housing Protected Classes","body":"The Fair Housing Act prohibits discrimination in housing on the basis of seven federally protected characteristics:\n\n(1) Race; (2) Color; (3) National Origin; (4) Religion; (5) Sex (including gender identity and sexual orientation under current HUD interpretation); (6) Disability; and (7) Familial Status — families with children under 18, pregnant women, and persons in the process of obtaining custody of a child.\n\nAdditional protected classes: Many states and localities add protected classes — age, marital status, source of income, military/veteran status, and ancestry. Always check state and local law for the jurisdiction of any property you are advising.\n\nTypes of discrimination: The FHA prohibits both intentional discrimination (disparate treatment) and facially neutral policies with discriminatory effect (disparate impact).\n\nDisparate treatment examples: Steering applicants of one race to particular buildings, applying stricter screening standards to applicants of a particular national origin, refusing to rent to families with children.\n\nDisparate impact examples: A screening policy that effectively excludes a protected class at a higher rate, a marketing strategy that fails to reach minority communities, occupancy standards that effectively exclude larger families."},{"heading":"Reasonable Accommodations for Tenants with Disabilities","body":"A reasonable accommodation is a change in rules, policies, practices, or services that enables a person with a disability to have equal opportunity to use and enjoy the housing.\n\nExamples: Allowing a service animal in a 'no pets' building, providing a reserved parking space closer to the unit, accepting rent payment at a different time due to disability payment timing, or providing written communications in an accessible format.\n\nThe interactive process: When a tenant requests a reasonable accommodation, the owner must engage in a good-faith dialogue to understand the need and explore how it can be met. The owner may request documentation of the disability and the need, but may not demand disclosure of a specific diagnosis.\n\nWhat makes an accommodation 'reasonable': An accommodation is reasonable if it does not impose an undue financial and administrative burden or fundamentally alter the nature of the housing program. Most accommodation requests are reasonable and should be granted.\n\nDenying a request: An accommodation may be denied only if granting it would impose an undue hardship — the burden is on the owner to demonstrate the hardship. Document the interactive process, the owner's analysis, and the decision. A denial without documentation is a fair housing violation."},{"heading":"Reasonable Modifications for Tenants with Disabilities","body":"A reasonable modification is a physical change to a unit or common area that enables a person with a disability to use the housing. Examples: installing grab bars in a bathroom, widening a doorway, installing a roll-in shower, adding a ramp to a unit entrance, or lowering a countertop.\n\nWho pays: In conventional housing, the tenant pays for modifications (with the right to restore the unit upon vacating). For HUD-assisted properties under Section 504, the owner may be required to pay for modifications in some circumstances.\n\nSection 8 modification rules: The owner must permit the modification upon request. The owner may require that modifications be done professionally and that appropriate permits be obtained. However, the owner may not require restoration if restoring the modification would harm the usefulness of the housing for subsequent disabled tenants (e.g., grab bars that future disabled tenants might need).\n\nDocumentation requirements: The modification request, the interactive process, the owner's approval or denial, and any conditions attached must be documented in the tenant file.\n\nCommon mistakes: Conditioning approval on proof that the tenant can afford the modification, requiring restoration of modifications that benefit future disabled tenants, or refusing modification requests without engaging in the interactive process."},{"heading":"Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act","body":"Section 504 (29 U.S.C. § 794) prohibits discrimination against persons with disabilities in programs or activities receiving federal financial assistance. For HUD-assisted properties, Section 504 creates obligations beyond the Fair Housing Act — including specific physical accessibility requirements.\n\nPhysical accessibility requirements: Properties with 5 or more units that have undergone substantial rehabilitation with federal funds must make a minimum percentage of units accessible — typically 5% for mobility impairments and 2% for visual/hearing impairments. Newly constructed federally assisted properties have even stricter requirements.\n\nAccessibility program requirements: Section 504 requires that the property's programs and services — not just physical units — be accessible. This includes the application process, management office, laundry facilities, recreational areas, and any other amenity offered.\n\n504 Coordinator: For entities with 15 or more employees, Section 504 requires designation of a 504 Coordinator responsible for managing compliance. Must be identified to applicants and tenants.\n\nGrievance procedure: Entities covered by Section 504 must maintain a grievance procedure for 504 complaints, provided to applicants and tenants."},{"heading":"Fair Housing Training, Documentation, and Complaint Response","body":"Staff training requirements: All staff who interact with applicants or tenants — including leasing agents, property managers, maintenance staff, and security personnel — must receive fair housing training. Training must cover: the seven federal protected classes, disparate treatment and disparate impact, reasonable accommodation procedures, VAWA, and how to respond to complaints. Training must be documented.\n\nTraining frequency: Initial training upon hiring and annual refresher training. Provide additional training when HUD issues new guidance or a fair housing complaint is received.\n\nFair housing posters: HUD requires fair housing posters prominently displayed in the management office and wherever rental applications are provided. Must be the current version.\n\nResponding to complaints: When a fair housing complaint is received — whether directly from a tenant or through HUD or a fair housing organization — respond in writing, investigate promptly, and document every step. Never dismiss or minimize a fair housing complaint.\n\nHUD complaint process: If a complaint is filed with HUD's Office of Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity (FHEO), cooperate fully with HUD investigations. Obstruction is both illegal and counterproductive.\n\nBuilding a culture of compliance: The most effective strategy is creating a culture where every staff member understands the rules, takes them seriously, and treats every applicant and tenant with equal dignity and respect."}]},{"id":"m121","unit":"u12","number":1,"title":"VAWA 2022 — Current Requirements for HUD-Assisted Housing","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"VAWA Overview — Who Is Protected and What Is Prohibited","body":"The Violence Against Women Act was most recently reauthorized in 2022 (VAWA 2022), expanding protections and adding new requirements for HUD-assisted housing. Compliance with VAWA 2022 is a MOR requirement — using outdated VAWA forms or having an outdated VAWA policy is an immediate finding.\n\nWho VAWA protects: Victims of domestic violence, dating violence, sexual assault, and stalking. VAWA 2022 explicitly extended protections to LGBTQ+ individuals — protections apply regardless of sex or gender identity.\n\nProtected activities: Being a victim of covered violence may not be used as a basis for: denying an application for housing, terminating a tenancy, charging fees or penalties related to covered violent incidents, or evicting a victim.\n\nThe perpetrator exception: VAWA does not protect the perpetrator of the violence. The owner may evict the perpetrator while allowing the victim to remain.\n\nVAWA does not override other grounds for action: If a victim engages in lease-violating behavior unrelated to their status as a victim (e.g., nonpayment of rent, property damage, criminal activity), the owner may still pursue lease enforcement. VAWA protects victim status — not general lease violations."},{"heading":"HUD Form 5380 — VAWA Notice of Rights","body":"HUD Form 5380 (Notice of Occupancy Rights Under the Violence Against Women Act) must be provided to every applicant and tenant in specified circumstances. Using the current version (updated for VAWA 2022) is mandatory. Using an outdated form is an immediate MOR finding.\n\nWhen Form 5380 must be provided: (1) To every applicant at the time of application; (2) To every tenant at the time the lease is signed or renewed; (3) To every tenant when a notice to vacate is issued by the owner; (4) Within 14 calendar days of a tenant's request.\n\nContent of Form 5380: Notifies the recipient of their VAWA rights including: the right not to be denied housing or evicted solely because of victim status, the right to request an emergency transfer, the right to request confidentiality of their status, and information about how to document status using Form 5382.\n\nConfidentiality: The VAWA status of any individual must be kept strictly confidential. May not be shared with any other person — including the alleged abuser — without the victim's written consent.\n\nDocumentation in the tenant file: Every tenant file must contain a signed acknowledgment that Form 5380 was provided, or a note documenting that the form was provided and the date."},{"heading":"HUD Form 5382 — Self-Certification of VAWA Status","body":"HUD Form 5382 (Certification of Domestic Violence, Dating Violence, Sexual Assault, or Stalking, and Alternate Documentation) provides a mechanism for a tenant or applicant to self-certify their VAWA-covered victim status. VAWA 2022 updated this form; only the current version may be used.\n\nWhen Form 5382 is relevant: When the management agent receives information suggesting that a tenant is a VAWA-covered victim — either because the tenant reports it or because incidents have occurred on the property — provide Form 5382 and allow them to assert VAWA protections.\n\nTime to complete: The tenant has 14 business days from receipt to submit the completed certification or alternate documentation. During this period, the management agent may not take adverse action based on the incident.\n\nAlternate documentation: Form 5382 identifies alternate forms of documentation that may be submitted: a police report, court order, documentation from a victim service provider, or a statement from an attorney.\n\nConfidentiality: Form 5382 documents must be stored separately from the tenant's general file — in a locked, restricted-access location — to prevent inadvertent disclosure. Owner's obligations upon receipt: retain documentation confidentially, take no adverse action against the victim based on the covered incident, and consider whether an emergency transfer is warranted."},{"heading":"The Emergency Transfer Plan","body":"VAWA requires HUD-assisted property owners to have a written Emergency Transfer Plan (ETP) and that victims who fear for their safety may request an emergency transfer to another available unit on the property or to another property in the owner's portfolio.\n\nETP required content: The Emergency Transfer Plan must describe: the criteria for eligibility, the process for requesting a transfer, how transfer requests are prioritized against the waiting list, the timeframe for processing transfer requests, documentation requirements, and confidentiality protections.\n\nHUD Form 5381: HUD has issued a model Emergency Transfer Plan (HUD Form 5381) that properties may adopt or adapt. Using a plan that does not meet HUD's requirements — or having no plan at all — is a MOR finding. Using an outdated version that doesn't reflect VAWA 2022 is also a finding.\n\nEligibility: A tenant is eligible for an emergency transfer if they are a VAWA-covered victim and either: request the transfer based on a reasonable belief that the perpetrator will harm them in their current unit, or have been threatened or harassed by the perpetrator while in the current unit.\n\nTransfer availability: Owners are required to facilitate transfers only if a safe unit is available. If no unit is available on-site, the owner should assist the victim in identifying other options and connecting with VAWA support services."},{"heading":"VAWA Implementation — Staff Training and Ongoing Compliance","body":"Staff training on VAWA: All staff must be trained on VAWA requirements — which forms to provide and when, how to handle disclosure of victim status, confidentiality requirements, the emergency transfer process, and how to respond to the perpetrator if they contact the property office seeking information about the victim. Training must be documented.\n\nUpdating VAWA policies: After each VAWA reauthorization, policies must be reviewed and updated. VAWA 2022 included significant changes. Using forms or policies from the 2013 or 2015 reauthorization after the 2022 update is non-compliant.\n\nThird-party VAWA resources: The Emergency Transfer Plan should include a list of local VAWA resources — domestic violence shelters, legal aid organizations, and victim service providers — with current contact information.\n\nHandling the perpetrator: When the management agent knows that a perpetrator of covered violence resides on the property, tools available include: lease bifurcation (terminating the perpetrator's portion of the lease while allowing the victim to remain), lease termination for the perpetrator based on criminal activity, and trespass notices.\n\nMOR documentation checklist: Every tenant file must have evidence that Form 5380 was provided. The management office must have a current ETP (Form 5381 or equivalent). VAWA training records must be in personnel files."}]},{"id":"m122","unit":"u12","number":2,"title":"Leases, HAP Contracts, and Tenant Protections","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"The HUD Model Lease — Required Provisions","body":"HUD-assisted properties must use the HUD-prescribed model lease or a lease that contains all HUD-required provisions. Required provisions include: a description of the unit and tenancy term, the amount of rent and how it is calculated, the owner's and tenant's obligations, grounds for lease termination with required notice periods, the grievance procedure, required HUD notice language, VAWA provisions, and incorporation by reference of the house rules.\n\nLease term: Most HUD-assisted leases are for an initial term of one year. After the initial term, the lease continues month-to-month unless either party gives proper notice.\n\nLease execution: Every adult household member must sign the lease. The management agent must also sign. Unsigned leases are findings.\n\nNo side agreements: The lease represents the entire agreement between the owner and the tenant regarding occupancy. Side agreements not reflected in the lease are impermissible.\n\nAnnual lease review: Review executed leases annually to confirm: the current tenant is the lease signatory, the unit description is correct, the rent amount matches the current certification, and all required provisions are present."},{"heading":"The HAP Contract — Owner Obligations","body":"The HAP contract is the agreement between HUD and the property owner that governs the payment of rental assistance. Key owner obligations include: maintain the project in decent, safe, and sanitary condition; comply with HUD Handbook 4350.3 in determining tenant eligibility and rent; comply with all applicable fair housing laws; maintain required insurance; permit HUD management reviews; transmit certified tenant data to TRACS; and maintain required Reserve for Replacement funding.\n\nHAP contract term and renewal: HAP contracts have defined terms. Begin the renewal process at least 12 months before expiration. A lapsed HAP contract means no assistance payments.\n\nHAP contract amendments: Changes to the number of assisted units, rent adjustments, and ownership transfers may require formal amendment. Unauthorized changes to HAP-related terms are contract violations.\n\nRent adjustments: Contract rents are adjusted annually using HUD-published Annual Adjustment Factors (AAF) or through comparability studies. Charging tenants above approved contract rents is a serious violation.\n\nOwnership and management agent changes: The sale of a property with an active HAP contract requires HUD approval. Changes in the management agent must also be approved. Unauthorized ownership or management transfers are HAP contract violations."},{"heading":"Lease Terminations — Process and Documentation","body":"Acceptable grounds for HUD-assisted lease termination: (1) Serious or repeated violations of the lease; (2) Violation of applicable federal, state, or local law; (3) Criminal activity or drug-related activity; (4) Other good cause — which must be genuine, documented, and reasonable.\n\nNotice requirements: Written notice must specify: the grounds for termination, the date the tenancy will end (meeting minimum notice period), the right to respond, and the grievance procedure. For most violations, minimum notice is 30 days.\n\nThe grievance procedure: Before filing for eviction, HUD-assisted owners must give the tenant the opportunity to request an informal hearing under the property's grievance procedure. Tenants who request a hearing must receive one before eviction proceedings can be initiated.\n\nVAWA protections in terminations: Victim status cannot be grounds for termination. If a termination is being considered for a household in which a VAWA situation exists, VAWA protections must be carefully evaluated before proceeding.\n\nDocumentation for court: Document every lease violation, every notice sent, every grievance hearing, and every communication with the tenant. Well-documented lease termination files protect the owner in eviction court."},{"heading":"House Rules — Adoption, Modification, and Enforcement","body":"HUD approval of house rules: Any house rules applied to tenants must have been reviewed and approved by HUD or the CA. Self-adopted or informally created rules that were never formally approved are unenforceable and create MOR findings.\n\nRequired notice for changes: Before house rules can be changed, tenants must receive written notice — typically 30 days — of the proposed change. After the comment period, proposed changes must be submitted to HUD for approval before taking effect.\n\nConsistency in enforcement: House rules must be enforced consistently across all tenants. Selective enforcement — enforcing rules against certain tenants or demographic groups more strictly — is a fair housing violation. Document rule enforcement actions consistently and with specificity.\n\nCommon rule issues: House rules frequently generate disputes around: noise policies, guest policies (policies restricting overnight guests can affect familial status rights), smoking policies, parking rules, and pet policies.\n\nPet policies and assistance animals: Service animals and emotional support animals are not pets — they are accommodations for persons with disabilities. A blanket 'no pets' rule cannot be used to refuse an assistance animal. The request must go through the reasonable accommodation process."},{"heading":"Tenant Grievance Procedures","body":"HUD requires that every assisted property maintain a formal grievance procedure giving tenants the right to contest management decisions. The grievance procedure must be in writing, provided to every tenant, and actually followed.\n\nWhen the grievance procedure applies: A tenant may request a grievance hearing to contest: a lease termination notice, a rent increase, a denial of a requested accommodation, a refusal to make requested repairs, or any other management decision the tenant believes violates their rights.\n\nThe hearing process: Upon receiving a written request, the owner must: acknowledge receipt, schedule the hearing within a reasonable time (typically 5–10 business days), designate an impartial hearing officer, and provide written notice of hearing date, time, and location.\n\nTenant rights at the hearing: The right to bring a representative (including an attorney or advocate), present evidence and witnesses, review the owner's evidence, and receive a written decision with the factual and legal basis.\n\nDocumentation: The grievance procedure file for each hearing must include: the hearing request, the notice of hearing, the hearing record, and the written decision. A pattern of findings against tenants without adequate process is a fair housing red flag."}]},{"id":"m123","unit":"u12","number":3,"title":"Financial Management — Budgets, RFR, Audits, and HAP Billing","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Operating Budget Management","body":"The MOR assesses both the quality of financial management practices and the financial health of the property — a financially stressed property cannot maintain decent, safe, and sanitary housing.\n\nThe annual operating budget: Must be realistic, based on actual historical data and reasonable projections, and submitted for approval per the requirements of the Regulatory Agreement.\n\nBudget management throughout the year: Monitor actual performance against budget monthly. When actual results diverge significantly — either income shortfalls or expense overruns — identify the cause and develop a response plan. A management agent who cannot explain budget variances demonstrates poor financial oversight.\n\nUtility expense management: Utilities are often the largest controllable expense category. Properties with rising utility costs should have energy management programs in place, document utility conservation measures, and track consumption data over time.\n\nVendor contracting: Contracts with vendors for major services (HVAC maintenance, landscaping, pest control) should be competitively bid and properly authorized. Regulatory Agreements may require competitive bidding above certain thresholds. Document the bidding process and vendor selection rationale."},{"heading":"Reserve for Replacement — Funding, Withdrawals, and Planning","body":"The Reserve for Replacement (RFR) is a dedicated escrow account required by the Regulatory Agreement for major capital repairs and replacements — roofs, HVAC systems, elevators, appliances, parking lots, and other long-lived assets.\n\nMinimum deposit requirements: The Regulatory Agreement specifies the minimum monthly deposit. This amount must be deposited every month without exception. If the property cannot afford the minimum deposit, the owner must negotiate with HUD — not simply skip deposits.\n\nRFR account: Must be maintained in a separate interest-bearing account. May not be commingled with operating funds.\n\nWithdrawal approval process: Any withdrawal requires prior HUD approval. The owner must submit a withdrawal request specifying: the purpose, estimated cost, scope of work, and confirmation that the RFR balance will remain above the required minimum. After completion, submit documentation (receipts, contractor invoices) to HUD. Unapproved withdrawals are serious findings.\n\nCapital needs assessment (CNA): A professional assessment of the property's capital needs over a 20-year horizon. A current CNA demonstrating adequate RFR funding gives the MOR reviewer confidence in the property's financial sustainability."},{"heading":"Audits — Requirements, Findings, and Responses","body":"Annual audited financial statements prepared by an independent CPA are required for all HUD-assisted multifamily housing properties. Properties receiving $750,000 or more in federal funds in a year are also subject to OMB Single Audit requirements, which include specific compliance testing for federal program requirements.\n\nAudit timing: Audits must be submitted to HUD within 9 months of the end of the fiscal year. For December 31 year-ends, the audit is due by September 30. Late submission is a finding.\n\nThe audit opinion: The audit should result in an unmodified ('clean') opinion. Qualified opinions, adverse opinions, or disclaimers of opinion are serious flags.\n\nResponding to management letter findings: When the auditor issues management letter findings, the owner must provide a written response and corrective action plan. During the MOR, the reviewer will ask about prior audit findings and whether they were corrected. A management letter finding not addressed by the subsequent audit is a pattern of noncompliance.\n\nREAC financial data submission: Audited financial statements must be submitted to HUD through REAC's Financial Assessment Subsystem (FASS). Failure to submit through FASS — separate from delivering a copy to the reviewer — is a compliance failure."},{"heading":"HAP Billing and TRACS — Accuracy and Timeliness","body":"Monthly voucher submission: The HAP voucher must be submitted monthly per the schedule established in the HAP contract. Late submissions may result in delayed payment and cash flow problems.\n\nVoucher accuracy: Every unit on the voucher must match the current tenant certification. The contract rent, utility allowance, tenant rent, and HAP amount for each unit must be correct. Even a single-dollar error in a unit's calculation is a finding if it creates a discrepancy between the voucher and the certification.\n\nTRACS reconciliation: The Tenant Rental Assistance Certification System (TRACS) is HUD's database that receives certified tenant data electronically. TRACS must be reconciled with the HAP voucher. Discrepancies trigger error reports that must be corrected promptly.\n\nRetroactive corrections: When HAP billing errors are discovered, the owner must submit retroactive corrections. Overpayments must be repaid. Maintain documentation of all corrections — date discovered, amount, basis, and correction submission.\n\nUtility reimbursements: When the utility allowance exceeds the tenant's TTP, the tenant is entitled to a utility reimbursement. The owner is responsible for paying the reimbursement and claiming it in the HAP billing. Failure to pay utility reimbursements is a finding."},{"heading":"Distributions, Identity of Interest, and Regulatory Agreement Compliance","body":"Surplus cash and distributions: An owner of a HUD-assisted property may only take distributions from surplus cash — the amount by which income exceeds all expenses, debt service, required RFR deposits, and a minimum reserve. Distributions from other than surplus cash are Regulatory Agreement violations.\n\nCalculating surplus cash: Calculated semi-annually (at June 30 and December 31) using the HUD-prescribed calculation. Only if available cash exceeds the liabilities threshold may the owner take a distribution.\n\nIdentity of interest (IOI) disclosures: An IOI exists when the owner has a financial relationship with a vendor, contractor, or other party doing business with the property. IOI relationships must be disclosed to HUD and may require approval. Examples: an owner who also owns the property management company, or an owner whose family member provides maintenance services.\n\nManagement fees: Only the management fee specified in the approved management contract may be charged. Additional fees — asset management fees, supervisory fees — require HUD approval. Unapproved fees are findings.\n\nFinancial whistleblower risk: The False Claims Act allows individuals to bring civil actions against owners who fraudulently obtain federal funds. Ensuring that HAP billing, distributions, and IOI transactions are above reproach is protection against significant financial liability."}]},{"id":"m131","unit":"u13","number":1,"title":"Your MOR Consulting Services — What to Offer and How to Package Them","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"The MOR Consulting Market — Why It Exists and Why Now","body":"The demand for MOR consulting is driven by the gap between what HUD requires and what most property managers have been formally trained to deliver. Most property managers in HUD-assisted housing learned on the job — accumulating informal knowledge, misconceptions, and outdated practices that create a persistent compliance gap.\n\nWhy the market exists: HUD has steadily increased its enforcement intensity. HOTMA, effective January 1, 2025, added a significant compliance burden that most management agents are not fully prepared for. EIV requirements have grown more stringent. VAWA 2022 added new obligations. Every regulatory update creates new demand for expert guidance.\n\nWhy now: The post-HOTMA environment is an exceptional entry point for a new consulting practice. Properties whose certifications, TSPs, and EIV processes have not been updated for HOTMA are out of compliance today. A single phone call in which you can articulate three specific HOTMA deficiencies that are common in 2025 MOR findings establishes your credibility immediately.\n\nYour target market: (1) Owners and management agents of HUD-assisted multifamily properties wanting to maintain or improve their MOR ratings; (2) Owners who have received poor ratings and are under corrective action or PIPs; (3) New management agents taking over troubled properties; (4) Property owners facing their first HUD review; (5) Lenders and investors assessing the compliance posture of properties they are considering acquiring."},{"heading":"Core Service Offerings — The MOR Prep Suite","body":"Service 1 — MOR Readiness Assessment (one-time engagement): A comprehensive evaluation of the property's current compliance posture using Form 9834 as the framework. Includes: tenant file sample review, EIV master binder review, waiting list and TSP review, financial document review, and staff knowledge assessment. Deliverable: written report with prioritized findings and recommended corrective actions. Typical fee: $3,000–$6,000 depending on property size.\n\nService 2 — MOR Prep Package (pre-MOR intensive): Everything in the Readiness Assessment plus: hands-on correction of identified deficiencies, assembly and review of the desk review package, staff training and interview prep, and attendance at the exit conference (optional). Typical fee: $5,000–$12,000.\n\nService 3 — HOTMA Compliance Assessment: A focused assessment of whether the property's certifications, TSP, EIV processes, and documentation practices are compliant with HOTMA requirements effective January 1, 2025. Typical fee: $2,500–$5,000.\n\nService 4 — Staff Training: Half-day or full-day training sessions on EIV compliance, HOTMA changes, fair housing, or tenant file management. Delivered on-site or virtually. Typical fee: $800–$1,500 per half-day session.\n\nService 5 — Ongoing Compliance Partnership (retainer): Monthly or quarterly engagement to maintain MOR readiness — running through the compliance calendar, reviewing certifications, and providing advice on emerging issues. Typical fee: $500–$2,000 per month."},{"heading":"Corrective Action Plan Consulting — A High-Value Niche","body":"Properties receiving Below Average or Unsatisfactory ratings are in distress — highly motivated to pay for expert help. CAP consulting is among the highest-value and most consistently in-demand MOR consulting services.\n\nWhy CAP consulting is high-value: Properties under corrective action face real consequences — management agent replacement, annual MOR scrutiny, and potential enforcement action. The stakes create urgency, and urgency creates fee tolerance.\n\nThe CAP consulting process: Begin with a thorough review of the MOR report. Map each finding to the relevant regulatory requirement, identify the root cause (not just the symptom), develop a specific corrective action that addresses the root cause, assign responsibility, set a realistic timeline, and track implementation.\n\nOngoing monitoring: After submitting the CAP, monitoring implementation is a separate billable phase. Many clients need a consultant to verify that corrective actions are actually being implemented.\n\nDeliverables: At the end of a CAP engagement, the client should have: a completed, well-documented CAP submitted to HUD; evidence of implementation for every corrective action item; updated policies and procedures reflecting the corrective actions; and training records showing staff have been trained on new procedures.\n\nPositioning: When approaching a potential client who has just received a poor MOR rating, your opening message is: 'I can help you convert this finding into an opportunity to demonstrate to HUD that your management has fundamentally changed.'"},{"heading":"Pricing Strategy and Engagement Structures","body":"Value-based pricing rationale: Your fees should reflect the value you deliver — not just your time. A client who avoids a Below Average rating (and thus an annual MOR) saves: the cost of additional scrutiny, management disruption, staff time, and reputational damage with HUD. That value is worth $5,000–$15,000 or more depending on property size.\n\nProject-based vs. hourly billing: Project-based fees (fixed-price with a defined scope) are generally preferable for both you and your client. Fixed fees make budgeting predictable for the client and incentivize you to work efficiently. Reserve hourly billing for undefined-scope engagements like CAP response work.\n\nIndicative fee ranges by property size: Small (under 50 units): MOR Readiness Assessment $2,500–$4,000; MOR Prep Package $4,000–$7,000. Mid-size (50–200 units): MOR Readiness Assessment $4,000–$7,000; MOR Prep Package $7,000–$15,000. Large (200+ units): MOR Readiness Assessment $6,000–$10,000; MOR Prep Package $12,000–$25,000.\n\nRetainer economics: Monthly retainer engagements provide predictable recurring revenue. A portfolio of 10 retainer clients at an average of $1,000/month generates $120,000 in annual recurring revenue before project work. Target building 5–10 retainer relationships in your first two years.\n\nScope management: Define project scope carefully in your engagement letter and document any scope changes. Scope creep — additional work not included in the original engagement — is the most common cause of fee disputes in consulting engagements."},{"heading":"Legal and Business Structure for Your Consulting Practice","body":"Business entity: Form an LLC or S-Corp for your consulting practice. An LLC provides liability protection, separates personal finances from business finances, and offers pass-through taxation. Consult with a business attorney and CPA to determine the optimal structure.\n\nProfessional liability insurance: Errors and Omissions (E&O) insurance is essential for a compliance consultant. If a client attributes an adverse MOR outcome to incorrect advice you provided, E&O insurance is your protection. Expect to pay $1,500–$3,000 annually. Do not engage clients without it.\n\nEngagement letter: Every client engagement should begin with a signed engagement letter that defines: scope of services, fee and payment terms, start and end dates, limitations on your liability, confidentiality obligations, and the process for resolving disputes.\n\nConfidentiality: As a consultant, you will access sensitive information — tenant files, financial records, EIV data. Your engagement letter should include explicit confidentiality obligations. Never share client information with other clients or third parties without written authorization.\n\nProfessional development: HUD regulations change regularly. Subscribe to HUD's multifamily mailing lists, attend HUD-sponsored webinars, join professional organizations (NAHMA, NAACOS, state housing associations), and complete continuing education. Staying current is what differentiates a premium consultant."}]},{"id":"m132","unit":"u13","number":2,"title":"The MOR Prep Workflow — Delivering Results","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"The Pre-Engagement Discovery Process","body":"Initial intake questions: Ask every potential client: When is your next MOR expected? When was your most recent MOR and what was the rating? Do you have a copy of the most recent MOR report? How many assisted units? Who is the Contract Administrator or HUD Field Office? What property management software do you use? Have there been ownership or management changes in the past two years?\n\nReviewing the prior MOR report: The prior MOR report is the most valuable discovery document. It tells you exactly where the property has been deficient in the past, which is statistically the most likely place to find current deficiencies.\n\nRequesting a pre-engagement file sample: For prospective clients, consider requesting access to 3–5 tenant files for a complimentary pre-engagement review. If you can describe specific deficiencies in their own files, you have established your value proposition more effectively than any sales pitch.\n\nUnderstanding the management team: During discovery, assess: Is the property manager experienced in HUD-assisted housing? Do they seem knowledgeable about EIV and certification requirements? Are they open to change? Staff who are resistant to corrective guidance are a risk factor for the engagement.\n\nSetting realistic expectations: Set honest expectations about the likely scope of issues, the timeline for remediation, and the probable MOR outcome. Over-promising and under-delivering destroys your reputation. Under-promising and over-delivering builds it."},{"heading":"The File Review Protocol","body":"Sample size: Your pre-MOR file review should cover at minimum 20% of occupied units or 10 files, whichever is greater. For a thorough pre-assessment, review all tenant files or a statistically significant sample.\n\nFile review checklist: For each file, systematically check: complete application package (signed HUD 9887 and 9887-A, screening documentation, EIV Existing Tenant Search, citizenship documentation); initial TIC with supporting income verifications; current TIC with verifications and signatures; annual recertification timing compliance; HOTMA asset self-certification or third-party verification; lease signed by all adults; Form 5380 acknowledgment; EIV discrepancy documentation if applicable; reasonable accommodation documentation if applicable.\n\nRating each file: Use a consistent rating system — Green (fully compliant), Yellow (minor deficiency, easily correctable), Red (significant deficiency requiring immediate action). Aggregate the ratings to give the client a quantitative picture.\n\nRoot cause analysis: Don't just document deficiencies — identify root causes. A pattern of missing income verifications suggests either a training gap or a process gap. Correcting root causes prevents recurrence; correcting individual file errors just fixes this year's finding.\n\nDocumenting your review: Maintain detailed notes organized by file and by deficiency type. These notes are the basis for your client report and your corrective action recommendations."},{"heading":"Staff Training as a Compliance Tool","body":"Correcting files is necessary but not sufficient. Unless the staff who produced the non-compliant files understand why they were wrong and how to do it correctly going forward, the same deficiencies will appear at the next MOR.\n\nTraining curriculum for MOR prep: Income calculation and verification (with HOTMA updates); asset verification and self-certification; certification timing and scheduling; EIV required use and documentation; fair housing and reasonable accommodation; VAWA 2022 requirements; tenant file organization and record retention.\n\nTraining format: On-site training is generally most effective for the hands-on elements (walking through sample files, demonstrating EIV procedures). Shorter reinforcement training can be delivered virtually. Provide written reference materials — checklists, quick reference guides, and templates.\n\nKnowledge testing: Administer a brief knowledge test before and after training. The pre-test establishes baseline knowledge levels. The post-test demonstrates training effectiveness and provides documentation of training completion.\n\nTraining documentation: Maintain a training attendance record with: date, topics covered, trainer name, and signatures of all attendees. This record is both a MOR document (demonstrating staff were trained) and a business record."},{"heading":"Mock MOR — Your Most Valuable Pre-Assessment Tool","body":"A mock MOR is a simulated MOR review conducted before the actual review, using Form 9834 as the framework, including simulated staff interviews and document review. It is your highest-value pre-MOR service because it gives the client the most accurate preview of what the real review will produce.\n\nPlanning the mock MOR: Schedule the mock MOR at least four to six weeks before the expected actual review, to allow time to address findings. Use Form 9834 as your scoresheet. Arrange to conduct staff interviews with the same staff who will be interviewed in the actual review.\n\nConducting the mock: Follow the same sequence a real reviewer would — begin with the desk review documents, proceed to tenant file sampling, conduct unit walkthroughs, conduct staff interviews, and hold an exit conference with the management team.\n\nThe mock exit conference: Walk the management team through every finding you identified — just as the real reviewer will. Present findings with the same tone and specificity as a real MOR. Have the management team practice responding.\n\nFindings report: After the mock, prepare a written findings report using the same format as an actual MOR report. Rate each area, identify deficiencies, and provide your overall mock rating. This document becomes the corrective action work plan for the remaining weeks before the actual review."},{"heading":"Post-MOR Corrective Action Management","body":"If the client received a good rating: Congratulate the team, document the outcome, and propose an ongoing retainer to maintain the compliance posture achieved. A Satisfactory or Above Average rating that was preceded by your engagement is a testimonial-worthy outcome.\n\nIf the client received findings: Move immediately into CAP mode. The CAP must be submitted to HUD within 30 days of the MOR report. Use your engagement notes from the mock MOR and the pre-MOR file review to draft the CAP quickly.\n\nCAP implementation tracking: Maintain a tracking spreadsheet with every CAP item, the assigned responsible party, the target completion date, and the evidence of completion. Review this tracker weekly with the client. Submit documentation of completed items proactively to HUD.\n\nEvidence packages: For each corrective action, assemble an evidence package: the original finding, the corrective action taken, the documentation demonstrating completion, and the date completed. Submit to HUD in a well-organized packet.\n\nLessons learned: After the CAP is completed, conduct a lessons-learned session with the client. What systemic issues were found? What process changes were implemented? What training gaps were addressed? This session reinforces improvements made and positions your ongoing consulting relationship as a quality assurance function."}]},{"id":"m133","unit":"u13","number":3,"title":"Growing Your Practice — Clients, Marketing, and Revenue","subtitle":"","sections":[{"heading":"Finding Your First Clients","body":"Leverage existing relationships: Your first clients will most likely come from people who already know you and trust your expertise — former employers, owners or management agents you worked with, property managers who attended training programs you delivered, colleagues in housing advocacy or government roles.\n\nJoin professional associations: Organizations like NAHMA, the National Leased Housing Association (NLHA), and state-level housing associations are primary networking venues for affordable housing professionals. Attend conferences, join committees, and volunteer to speak or present. Thought leadership in professional settings builds credibility rapidly.\n\nApproach property owners directly: Identify Section 8 properties in your target geography from HUD's multifamily housing database (available at HUD's website). Research their MOR history (MOR reports are public records via FOIA). Approach owners of properties with prior findings or upcoming reviews with a targeted, specific value proposition.\n\nGovernment relationships: Building professional relationships with HUD Field Office staff and PBCA account managers is valuable — it keeps you informed about regulatory changes, enforcement trends, and the particular concerns of the reviewing entity in your market."},{"heading":"Marketing Your Practice — Positioning and Messaging","body":"Your core value proposition: Articulate your value in one or two sentences. Example: 'I help affordable housing property managers achieve Satisfactory or better MOR ratings and maintain them year over year, so they can focus on serving their residents rather than managing compliance crises.'\n\nThought leadership content: Write articles for NAHMA News, state housing association newsletters, or LinkedIn about specific MOR compliance topics — HOTMA changes, EIV compliance, VAWA 2022 requirements. This positions you as an expert before the client ever contacts you. A property manager who has read three of your articles on EIV compliance before calling you is already sold on your expertise.\n\nCase studies: After completing engagements (with client permission), document the outcome as a case study. A before/after narrative — 'Property X had received Below Average for two consecutive MORs; after our eight-week engagement, they received Satisfactory and exited the corrective action cycle' — is far more persuasive than any general description of your services.\n\nWebsite and LinkedIn presence: A professional website describing your services, credentials, and approach is essential in 2025. LinkedIn is the primary professional networking platform in real estate and housing — use it to publish content, share articles, and connect with potential clients."},{"heading":"Building a Referral Network","body":"Primary referral sources: (1) HUD-approved housing counseling agencies working with properties in distress; (2) Affordable housing attorneys handling HAP contract issues and enforcement matters; (3) Multifamily lenders conducting due diligence on HUD-assisted properties; (4) Property management associations whose members need consulting services; (5) Other consulting firms in adjacent spaces — NSPIRE consultants, fair housing training firms — who encounter clients needing MOR prep.\n\nReciprocal referrals: Build your referral network by also referring clients to others. If a client needs fair housing training, refer them to a fair housing trainer. If they need an audit, refer them to a CPA experienced in HUD housing. People who receive referrals from you are far more likely to send referrals back.\n\nPBCA relationships: While PBCAs cannot formally endorse consultants, building a professional relationship with PBCA account managers — as colleagues committed to improving housing quality — creates informal referral pathways.\n\nTestimonials: After each successful engagement, ask satisfied clients for a written testimonial or LinkedIn recommendation. A portfolio of genuine testimonials from property managers who achieved good MOR outcomes is one of your most powerful marketing assets."},{"heading":"Scaling Your Practice — Associates, Partnerships, and Technology","body":"Associate consultants: The most direct scaling mechanism is bringing on associates — other experienced HUD-assisted housing professionals who can conduct assessments and training on your behalf. This allows you to handle more simultaneous engagements and serve clients in geographies you cannot reach personally.\n\nPartnership with other compliance firms: Consider partnerships with NSPIRE inspection consultants, fair housing training firms, or HUD housing counseling agencies. These partners serve overlapping client populations and can refer clients who need your specific expertise.\n\nTechnology leverage: Project management tools (Asana, Monday.com) allow you to manage multiple simultaneous client engagements. Document sharing platforms (Google Drive, SharePoint) allow clients to upload files for remote review. Virtual meeting tools allow you to conduct training for clients in any location.\n\nProductized services: As you accumulate experience, convert customized consulting work into standardized deliverables that can be delivered efficiently and consistently. Your MOR readiness assessment checklist, file review protocol, and staff training curriculum are all assets that can be standardized."},{"heading":"The Long Game — Building a Sustainable Compliance Practice","body":"Staying current with regulations: The single most important ongoing investment in your practice is staying current with HUD regulations. HUD publishes notices, handbook updates, PIH notices, Mortgagee Letters, and guidance documents regularly. Subscribe to HUD's multifamily mailing lists, attend HUD webinars, and read NAHMA's regulatory update publications.\n\nDeveloping expertise depth: Over time, develop deep expertise in specific sub-areas — HOTMA implementation, EIV compliance, mixed-finance properties (combining HUD, LIHTC, and other funding sources), Section 202 (elderly housing), or Section 811 (disabled housing). Depth in a specialty area differentiates you from general practitioners.\n\nMeasuring your impact: Track MOR ratings before and after your engagements. Track client retention rates. This data is both a quality management tool and a marketing asset.\n\nThe ethical foundation: Your consulting practice must be built on ethical conduct. Never advise a client to falsify records or misrepresent facts to HUD. Never accept undisclosed compensation from vendors serving your clients. Never exaggerate your credentials or track record. Your reputation is your most valuable asset.\n\nThe mission alignment: The purpose of HUD-assisted housing is to provide safe, decent, and affordable homes to families in need. Your consulting work serves that mission directly — when you help a property achieve MOR compliance, you help ensure that tenants receive the quality of housing that federal law requires."}]}];
export const MOR_CHAPTER_QUIZZES = {"m71":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"What is the primary purpose of a HUD Management and Occupancy Review (MOR)?","opts":["To physically inspect units for NSPIRE compliance","To assess whether a property is managed in compliance with HUD requirements","To determine whether a HAP contract should be renewed","To verify that property taxes are current"],"ans":1,"exp":"The MOR focuses on management practices, policies, and documentation — not physical conditions. Physical inspections are conducted under NSPIRE."},{"q":"Which HUD form is the official instrument used to conduct every MOR?","opts":["HUD Form 50059","HUD Form 9887","HUD Form 9834","HUD Form 214"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD Form 9834 (Management Review for Multifamily Housing Projects) is the standardized scoresheet and checklist used by every MOR reviewer."},{"q":"Which HUD handbook is the primary occupancy handbook governing MOR compliance topics?","opts":["Handbook 4350.1","Handbook 4350.3 REV-1 Change-4","Handbook 7420.8","Handbook 4381.5"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD Handbook 4350.3 REV-1 Change-4 governs tenant eligibility, certifications, rent calculations, and most other occupancy-related MOR topics."},{"q":"Under what federal regulation is EIV use mandatory?","opts":["24 CFR 5.233","24 CFR 200.15","42 U.S.C. 1437f","24 CFR 5.801"],"ans":0,"exp":"24 CFR 5.233 mandates the use of HUD's Enterprise Income Verification system for all covered multifamily housing programs."},{"q":"Since January 1, 2024, what is HUD's policy on the format of MORs?","opts":["Virtual/remote MORs are preferred to reduce cost","MORs must be conducted on-site; remote reviews are no longer permitted","A hybrid format (partial remote, partial on-site) is now standard","Owners may elect either on-site or virtual format"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD ended the COVID-era remote review exception effective January 1, 2024. All MORs must now be conducted on-site."},{"q":"Which entity may conduct a MOR in addition to HUD Field Office staff?","opts":["The local Housing Authority","A HUD-approved Performance Based Contract Administrator (PBCA)","A state housing finance agency","The property's independent auditor"],"ans":1,"exp":"PBCAs are private entities contracted by HUD to administer Section 8 contracts in a given region, which includes conducting MORs."},{"q":"What document gives HUD the contractual authority to conduct a MOR?","opts":["The Regulatory Agreement","The HUD-insured mortgage note","The HAP contract","The property management agreement"],"ans":2,"exp":"The HAP contract includes a provision requiring the owner to permit HUD or its designee to conduct management reviews."},{"q":"How frequently are properties with Satisfactory MOR ratings typically reviewed?","opts":["Annually","Every two to three years","Every five years","Only when a complaint is received"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD uses a risk-based approach. Satisfactorily performing properties are typically reviewed every two to three years."},{"q":"What is the typical review frequency for a property with a Below Average or Unsatisfactory rating?","opts":["Every five years","Every three years","Annually until performance improves","Only if a complaint is filed"],"ans":2,"exp":"Properties with Below Average or Unsatisfactory ratings typically receive annual MORs until their performance improves."},{"q":"What is the primary difference between a MOR and an NSPIRE inspection?","opts":["NSPIRE reviews documents; MOR inspects physical conditions","MOR reviews management practices and documents; NSPIRE inspects physical conditions","Both review the same items using different instruments","MOR is conducted by HUD; NSPIRE is conducted by the owner"],"ans":1,"exp":"The MOR and NSPIRE reviews are complementary but distinct. The MOR assesses management compliance; NSPIRE assesses physical conditions."},{"q":"HOTMA became fully effective for multifamily housing certification requirements on what date?","opts":["January 1, 2020","October 1, 2022","January 1, 2025","January 1, 2026"],"ans":2,"exp":"HOTMA's occupancy-related amendments became fully effective for HUD multifamily housing programs on January 1, 2025."},{"q":"A management agent who refuses to permit a MOR may be found in breach of which document?","opts":["The Regulatory Agreement only","The HAP contract","The state occupancy permit","The property management agreement"],"ans":1,"exp":"The HAP contract requires the owner to permit HUD or its designee to conduct management reviews. Refusal constitutes a contract breach."},{"q":"Which of the following events is most likely to trigger a MOR outside the normal review cycle?","opts":["A REAC score above 80","A recent change in the property's utility provider","A tenant fair housing complaint filed with HUD","A routine lease renewal period"],"ans":2,"exp":"Tenant complaints, fair housing complaints, audit findings, or EIV noncompliance flags can all trigger a MOR outside the standard cycle."},{"q":"The MOR focuses on which type of compliance?","opts":["Physical housing quality","Financial audit compliance only","Management practices, policies, documentation, and tenant eligibility","Tax compliance and insurance coverage only"],"ans":2,"exp":"The MOR comprehensively reviews management practices, policies, tenant files, certifications, waiting list management, financial management, and fair housing."},{"q":"Which statement best describes the relationship between MOR findings and corrective action?","opts":["Only Unsatisfactory ratings require corrective action","Any finding at any rating level requires a corrective action plan","Satisfactory ratings require no corrective action regardless of individual findings","Corrective action is only required for fair housing violations"],"ans":1,"exp":"Every MOR finding — regardless of the overall rating — must be addressed through a written Corrective Action Plan submitted to HUD."}]},"m72":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"How many rating levels does HUD's MOR rating scale have?","opts":["Three","Four","Five","Six"],"ans":2,"exp":"The MOR uses a five-level scale: Superior, Above Average, Satisfactory, Below Average, and Unsatisfactory."},{"q":"A property receives a MOR with exceptional management and no deficiencies identified. What rating is it likely to receive?","opts":["Above Average","Superior","Satisfactory","Below Average"],"ans":1,"exp":"Superior is awarded for exceptional management with no or minimal deficiencies across all review areas."},{"q":"Which MOR rating triggers formal enforcement action most directly?","opts":["Below Average","Unsatisfactory","Satisfactory with findings","Above Average"],"ans":1,"exp":"An Unsatisfactory rating almost always triggers formal enforcement action, which may include management agent replacement or a Performance Improvement Plan."},{"q":"What is the primary difference between a 'pattern' finding and an 'isolated' deficiency in MOR review?","opts":["Patterns require corrective action; isolated deficiencies do not","Patterns suggest systemic failure and are weighted more heavily by reviewers","Isolated deficiencies are always more serious than patterns","There is no distinction — both are treated equally"],"ans":1,"exp":"Reviewers look for patterns because they indicate the problem will recur. Systemic issues across multiple files or areas are treated more seriously than single errors."},{"q":"A Corrective Action Plan (CAP) must typically be submitted to HUD within how many days of receiving the MOR report?","opts":["7 days","14 days","30 days","90 days"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD typically requires submission of the CAP within 30 days of receiving the MOR report."},{"q":"Which finding, by itself, can significantly reduce a property's MOR rating?","opts":["A minor bookkeeping error in one tenant file","A critical deficiency on Form 9834","An expired management contract","A missing utility allowance schedule"],"ans":1,"exp":"Some items on Form 9834 are designated as critical. A single critical deficiency can substantially reduce the overall rating."},{"q":"What is a Performance Improvement Plan (PIP)?","opts":["A financial restructuring plan for troubled properties","A formal agreement between HUD and the owner specifying performance benchmarks and timelines","An NSPIRE score improvement program","A tenant-management relationship improvement document"],"ans":1,"exp":"A PIP is a formal HUD-owner agreement with specific performance benchmarks, monthly/quarterly reporting requirements, and clear escalation triggers."},{"q":"What happens if corrective actions identified in a prior MOR are found to be uncorrected in the current review?","opts":["They are dismissed since the prior MOR period has passed","They are treated as aggravating factors in the current review","They automatically produce an Unsatisfactory rating","The reviewer is prohibited from scoring them again"],"ans":1,"exp":"Carry-forward findings — deficiencies not corrected from a prior MOR — are treated as aggravating factors in the current review."},{"q":"Under what circumstances can HUD require replacement of the management agent?","opts":["Only if the management agent commits fraud","When the property receives a first-time Satisfactory rating","When persistent noncompliance demonstrates the agent cannot achieve compliance","Only when requested by the property owner"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD can require management agent replacement when persistent poor ratings demonstrate the current agent is incapable of achieving compliance."},{"q":"Which MOR rating best describes 'acceptable compliance with some minor deficiencies not indicating systemic problems'?","opts":["Superior","Above Average","Satisfactory","Below Average"],"ans":2,"exp":"Satisfactory is the baseline passing rating — the property meets requirements with acceptable compliance and some minor, non-systemic deficiencies."},{"q":"The MOR overall rating is best described as:","opts":["A simple percentage of acceptable items","A reflection of deficiency nature, severity, and pattern across all review areas","The average of individual section scores","Determined solely by the number of critical findings"],"ans":1,"exp":"The overall rating reflects the nature, severity, and pattern of deficiencies — not a simple average or count."},{"q":"An owner whose management agent receives a poor MOR rating argues they bear no responsibility. This argument is:","opts":["Correct — the management agent bears all liability","Incorrect — the owner has a non-delegable duty to maintain compliance","Correct if the management contract assigns liability to the agent","Incorrect only if the owner is also the management agent"],"ans":1,"exp":"Owner liability for MOR compliance is non-delegable. Even if a management agent caused the problems, the owner also has regulatory liability."},{"q":"When reviewing a prior MOR report as a consultant, what is the most strategically important information to extract?","opts":["The name of the reviewer who conducted the MOR","Recurring findings across multiple MOR cycles","The exact date the MOR was conducted","The number of units inspected"],"ans":1,"exp":"Recurring findings across multiple years almost certainly represent ongoing problems. These are the highest-priority areas for your pre-assessment."},{"q":"After implementing corrective actions, what must the owner submit to HUD?","opts":["Only a verbal confirmation at the next meeting","Documentation demonstrating that each corrective action was implemented","A new management contract","An updated HAP voucher"],"ans":1,"exp":"After implementing corrective actions, the owner must submit documentation to HUD demonstrating completion. HUD formally confirms acceptance."},{"q":"A property's MOR ratings over three years: Unsatisfactory, Below Average, Satisfactory. How would HUD view this trajectory?","opts":["The property must go directly to Above Average before trends are considered","Negatively — any history of poor ratings is permanent","Favorably — it shows genuine improvement over time","Neutrally — only the most recent rating matters"],"ans":2,"exp":"A positive trajectory from Unsatisfactory to Below Average to Satisfactory demonstrates genuine improvement, which HUD views favorably."}]},"m73":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"What is the typical advance notice period for a scheduled MOR?","opts":["2–4 days","One week","Two to four weeks","Six months"],"ans":2,"exp":"Reviewers typically contact the property two to four weeks before the review to schedule the visit and request desk review documents."},{"q":"What is the standard HUD tenant file sampling percentage during a MOR?","opts":["5% of occupied units","10% of occupied units","20% of occupied units","50% of occupied units"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD typically reviews 20% of occupied units, with a minimum of 10 files and a maximum of 50 files for very large properties."},{"q":"Who selects the specific tenant files to be reviewed during a MOR?","opts":["The property manager","The management agent's compliance officer","The HUD reviewer","The property owner"],"ans":2,"exp":"The reviewer selects the file sample — it is not the management agent's choice. This prevents management agents from only showing their best files."},{"q":"What is the primary purpose of unit walkthroughs during a MOR (as distinct from NSPIRE)?","opts":["To score unit conditions using NSPIRE criteria","To verify occupancy, check for lease violations, and assess maintenance responsiveness","To measure unit square footage for HAP billing","To assess whether utility allowances are correctly calculated"],"ans":1,"exp":"MOR unit visits verify that units are occupied by the people listed in tenant files and assess general maintenance responsiveness — not NSPIRE scoring."},{"q":"What should a property manager say during a staff interview when asked a question they are unsure about?","opts":["Make a reasonable guess to appear knowledgeable","Say 'I don't know but I'll find out' and follow up","Decline to answer any questions","Refer all questions to the owner's attorney"],"ans":1,"exp":"'I don't know but I'll find out' is far preferable to guessing incorrectly. Reviewers appreciate honest, professional responses."},{"q":"What is the exit conference?","opts":["A formal proceeding recorded by a court reporter","An opportunity for the reviewer to share preliminary findings and for the property to provide clarifying information","The reviewer's final written report delivered to the owner","A disciplinary meeting between HUD and the management agent"],"ans":1,"exp":"The exit conference is conducted at the end of the on-site visit and gives the property an opportunity to provide additional documentation or context for potential findings."},{"q":"If a reviewer mentions a potential finding at the exit conference and you have documentation that addresses it, what should you do?","opts":["Wait for the written report before responding","Produce the documentation immediately or commit to providing it within 24 hours","Dispute the finding verbally without producing documentation","Ask the reviewer to drop the finding without documentation"],"ans":1,"exp":"The exit conference is an important opportunity to provide clarifying documentation. Produce it immediately if available, or commit to providing it within 24 hours."},{"q":"Which file type do reviewers often pay extra attention to during the tenant file sample?","opts":["Files of elderly tenants","Files of recent move-ins within the past 12 months","Files of tenants who have been in place the longest","Files with the highest HAP amounts"],"ans":1,"exp":"Reviewers often focus on recent move-ins because initial eligibility determinations are high-stakes and errors there affect the entire tenancy."},{"q":"When should a standard file organization be implemented to prepare for a MOR?","opts":["Only immediately before the MOR","As part of ongoing management practices, not just during MOR prep","Only for files in the reviewer's sample","Only for new move-ins after the MOR notice is received"],"ans":1,"exp":"File organization should be a standard ongoing practice. Implementing it only during MOR prep is detectable and produces incomplete results."},{"q":"What do reviewers assess during staff interviews that cannot be determined from documents alone?","opts":["The total number of tenant files","Staff knowledge of HUD requirements and their ability to articulate management practices","Whether the property has sufficient reserve funds","The accuracy of utility allowance calculations"],"ans":1,"exp":"Staff interviews assess whether staff actually understand HUD requirements — not just whether the files look right."},{"q":"Unit transfer documentation is frequently incomplete in MOR reviews because:","opts":["Transfers don't legally require documentation","Transfers are frequently handled informally without proper paperwork","HUD only requires documentation for transfers between different properties","Transfer documentation is only required for Section 8 units"],"ans":1,"exp":"Unit transfers are frequently handled informally. Reviewers specifically check transfer documentation because they know it is often incomplete."},{"q":"How long after the on-site visit does a reviewer typically take to deliver the written MOR report?","opts":["24–48 hours","One week","30–60 days","90 days"],"ans":2,"exp":"The written MOR report is typically delivered within 30–60 days of the on-site visit."},{"q":"What is a best practice for preparing leasing staff for a MOR?","opts":["Instruct them to answer all questions without consulting the manager","Brief them on what leasing-related questions may be asked and how to respond","Direct all questions from the reviewer to the property manager only","Have leasing staff take the day off during the review"],"ans":1,"exp":"All staff who will interact with the reviewer should be briefed, including leasing staff, who may be asked about applicant selection and EIV procedures."},{"q":"What is the primary risk of a management agent volunteering negative information during a staff interview?","opts":["It improves the reviewer's opinion of the staff's honesty","It creates additional scrutiny in areas the reviewer may not have originally planned to examine","It has no effect on the MOR outcome","It automatically produces a Below Average finding"],"ans":1,"exp":"Volunteering negative information creates scrutiny in areas that may have otherwise received less attention. Answer questions honestly but don't elaborate beyond what is asked."},{"q":"A property receives its MOR report and disagrees with a factual finding. What option is available?","opts":["No recourse exists once the report is issued","The owner may request a correction for factual errors in the MOR report","The owner must accept all findings without question","The owner may only challenge findings in federal court"],"ans":1,"exp":"If factual errors exist in the MOR report, the owner has the right to request a correction through the reviewing HUD Field Office or PBCA."}]},"m81":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"When must the desk review package typically be submitted to the reviewer?","opts":["On the day of the on-site visit","One to two weeks before the on-site visit","The day the MOR notice is received","Within 24 hours of the on-site visit"],"ans":1,"exp":"Desk review documents are typically submitted one to two weeks before the on-site visit so the reviewer can analyze them in advance."},{"q":"Which document is described as 'the foundational document against which many other items are cross-checked'?","opts":["The AFHMP","The Occupancy Report / Rent Roll","The EIV Participation Agreement","The Audited Financial Statements"],"ans":1,"exp":"The rent roll is the foundational document — it must reconcile with the HAP billing voucher, financial statements, and tenant certifications."},{"q":"A disorganized, incomplete desk review package signals to a reviewer that:","opts":["The property is small and understaffed","The property may have significant management problems worth investigating closely","The management agent prefers to discuss documents on-site","The property's NSPIRE score may be at risk"],"ans":1,"exp":"A disorganized package causes the reviewer to arrive with heightened scrutiny. First impressions in the MOR process begin with the desk review."},{"q":"The EIV Binder/Master File must include which of the following?","opts":["Copies of all tenant leases","The current EIV Participation Agreement and evidence that required reports are run at required intervals","The property's operating budget","The AFHMP and marketing materials"],"ans":1,"exp":"The EIV master file must contain the Participation Agreement, user training certificates, report run documentation, and discrepancy resolution documentation."},{"q":"How often must the Existing Tenant Search report be run?","opts":["Annually for all tenants","At every annual recertification","For every applicant, within 120 days before move-in","Only when requested by HUD"],"ans":2,"exp":"The Existing Tenant Search must be run for every applicant within 120 days before their move-in to check for duplicate Section 8 assistance."},{"q":"How frequently must the AFHMP be updated at minimum?","opts":["Annually","Every two years","Every five years","Only when the waiting list is opened"],"ans":2,"exp":"The AFHMP must be updated every five years, or whenever there is a material change in marketing strategy. An expired AFHMP is an immediate MOR finding."},{"q":"Which of the following is a required policy document in the desk review package?","opts":["The owner's personal financial statement","Current VAWA forms (HUD 5380 and 5382) reflecting VAWA 2022","The state housing agency's funding allocation letter","The contractor's liability insurance certificate"],"ans":1,"exp":"Current VAWA forms (HUD 5380 Notice and HUD 5382 Certification) must reflect VAWA 2022 requirements. Using outdated forms is a finding."},{"q":"What does a Certification Due List document?","opts":["When audits are due to HUD","All upcoming annual recertification dates showing status (current, in process, past due)","When AFHMP updates are required","The due dates for HAP contract renewals"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Certification Due List shows all upcoming certification anniversaries, which certifications are current, in process, or past due."},{"q":"What does the Overhoused/Underhoused Report document?","opts":["Whether the property's units meet HUD physical occupancy standards","Tenants in units larger or smaller than their family size justifies and actions taken","Properties that have exceeded their HAP contract unit count","Units that are above or below the gross rent ceiling"],"ans":1,"exp":"This report documents tenants in inappropriately sized units. HUD requires owners to offer appropriately sized units when they become available."},{"q":"A cover letter in the desk review package should include:","opts":["The names of all tenants whose files will be reviewed","The property name/address, FHA/contract number, a status summary, and an expression of compliance commitment","Detailed responses to prior MOR findings only","A request that the reviewer not examine specific areas of concern"],"ans":1,"exp":"The cover letter introduces the property, management team, and summarizes current status. It sets a professional, cooperative tone."},{"q":"When should you proactively disclose a known compliance issue in the desk review package?","opts":["Never — wait to see if the reviewer finds it","Only for financial issues, not tenant file issues","Always, accompanied by corrective action documentation","Only if the issue is more than 12 months old"],"ans":2,"exp":"Proactive disclosure of known issues, accompanied by corrective action documentation, is viewed far more favorably than attempting to conceal problems."},{"q":"How often must the Multiple Subsidy Report be run?","opts":["Monthly","Quarterly","At least annually","Every three years"],"ans":2,"exp":"The Multiple Subsidy Report must be run at least annually to identify tenants potentially receiving duplicate housing assistance."},{"q":"The Waiting List in the desk review must include:","opts":["Only the names of applicants currently in the selection process","Applicant names, application dates, bedroom sizes requested, preferences claimed, contact info, and status","Only applicants who have been active in the past 90 days","The property manager's assessment of each applicant's likelihood of tenancy"],"ans":1,"exp":"A complete waiting list is required showing all required data elements — date, size, preferences, contact information, and current status."},{"q":"What is the primary purpose of the desk review phase of the MOR?","opts":["To give the reviewer time to schedule the on-site visit","To allow the reviewer to analyze documents in advance, identify discrepancies, and prioritize areas for on-site review","To give the management agent time to prepare files for the visit","To provide HUD with annual financial reporting data"],"ans":1,"exp":"The desk review allows the reviewer to assess compliance posture before the on-site visit, so they can focus scrutiny on the highest-risk areas."},{"q":"If a desk review reveals a high percentage of income mismatches or missing certifications, what is the likely result?","opts":["The reviewer will reduce the file sample size to limit findings","The reviewer will expand the file sample beyond the standard 20%","The reviewer will defer the on-site visit pending correction","No change — the file sample size is always fixed at 20%"],"ans":1,"exp":"Desk review findings suggesting widespread certification problems will cause the reviewer to expand the file sample to get a more representative view of compliance."}]},"m82":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"Within how many months of the fiscal year-end must audited financial statements typically be submitted to HUD?","opts":["3 months","6 months","9 months","12 months"],"ans":2,"exp":"Audited financial statements must typically be submitted within 9 months of the fiscal year end — September 30 for a December 31 year-end."},{"q":"What is the name of the HUD system through which audited financial statements must be submitted?","opts":["TRACS","EIV","REAC Financial Assessment Subsystem (FASS)","PIC"],"ans":2,"exp":"Financial statements must be submitted through REAC's Financial Assessment Subsystem (FASS) / iREMS."},{"q":"What is the purpose of the Reserve for Replacement (RFR)?","opts":["To fund operating deficits when rental income falls short","To pay management fees in months where cash flow is tight","To accumulate funds for major capital repairs and replacements","To provide emergency tenant assistance for rent arrears"],"ans":2,"exp":"The RFR is a dedicated account for funding major capital repairs — roofs, HVAC systems, appliances, elevators — not for operating expenses."},{"q":"What does a qualified, adverse, or disclaimed audit opinion signal?","opts":["The auditor specializes in affordable housing","A serious problem with the accuracy of financial records or compliance","The audit was conducted by a specialized HUD-approved firm","A routine notation with no significance"],"ans":1,"exp":"A clean (unmodified) opinion is expected. Qualified or adverse opinions signal significant financial statement issues that warrant scrutiny."},{"q":"Any withdrawal from the Reserve for Replacement account requires:","opts":["Board approval only","Prior HUD approval with supporting documentation","Notice to tenants only","Management agent discretion with retroactive notification to HUD"],"ans":1,"exp":"All RFR withdrawals require prior HUD approval. Unapproved withdrawals are a serious MOR finding."},{"q":"How is surplus cash calculated for purposes of permitted owner distributions?","opts":["Total revenue minus total operating expenses","Available cash minus current liabilities and required reserve balances, per the HUD-prescribed calculation","Net operating income minus debt service","Management fee income minus expenses"],"ans":1,"exp":"Surplus cash is calculated semi-annually by comparing available cash against current liabilities and required balance thresholds per the HUD formula."},{"q":"What information does the HAP billing voucher show for each assisted unit?","opts":["Tenant's employment status and income level","Contract rent, utility allowance, tenant rent, and HAP amount","Tenant's citizenship status and household composition","Unit's physical condition score"],"ans":1,"exp":"The HAP voucher shows contract rent, utility allowance, tenant rent, and HAP amount for each assisted unit — and must reconcile with current certifications."},{"q":"What is a 'management letter' in the context of an annual audit?","opts":["The management agent's annual report to the owner","The auditor's findings about internal control weaknesses and compliance issues","HUD's annual correspondence about the property's performance","The property manager's correspondence log"],"ans":1,"exp":"The management letter is issued by the auditor and contains findings about internal controls, accounting concerns, or compliance issues identified during the audit."},{"q":"Which documents should be available to a MOR reviewer to demonstrate sound financial planning?","opts":["Only the audited statements","Current year budget and prior year budget-to-actual comparison with variance explanations","Prior year budget only","Current year utility bills"],"ans":1,"exp":"The current year budget and prior year budget-to-actual comparison with variance explanations demonstrate sound financial oversight."},{"q":"A property's utility allowance schedule has not been updated in three years. This is:","opts":["Acceptable — utility allowances are set for the life of the HAP contract","A finding — utility allowances must be current and HUD-approved","Not a MOR issue — it only affects the physical inspection","Only a concern if the property is above the gross rent ceiling"],"ans":1,"exp":"An outdated utility allowance schedule that has not been reviewed and approved by HUD is a common and easily preventable MOR finding."},{"q":"What is an 'identity of interest' (IOI) and why is it significant?","opts":["A tenant's claim to a specific unit based on prior occupancy","A financial relationship between the owner and a vendor that must be disclosed to HUD","The HAP contract provision identifying the property as HUD-assisted","The management agent's certification of staff identity"],"ans":1,"exp":"IOI exists when the owner has a financial relationship with a vendor or contractor. IOI relationships must be disclosed to HUD and may require approval."},{"q":"Insurance coverage for HUD-assisted properties typically must include HUD as:","opts":["The primary beneficiary","An additional named insured where required by the Regulatory Agreement","The sole policyholder","Only a contingent beneficiary"],"ans":1,"exp":"Regulatory Agreements typically require HUD to be named as an additional insured on property insurance policies."},{"q":"A Capital Needs Assessment (CNA) is best described as:","opts":["The annual operating budget","A professional assessment of the property's capital needs over a 20-year horizon","The monthly maintenance log of completed repairs","The auditor's evaluation of capital expenditures"],"ans":1,"exp":"A CNA is a professional assessment projecting capital needs over 20 years and evaluating whether the RFR funding rate is adequate to meet those needs."},{"q":"An owner fails to make the required monthly RFR deposit for four consecutive months. This is:","opts":["Not a problem if the RFR balance remains above the minimum","An immediate MOR finding","Acceptable if documented in the operating budget","Only a concern if it results in deferred maintenance"],"ans":1,"exp":"Missing RFR deposits are an immediate finding regardless of the current balance. The deposit schedule must be maintained consistently."},{"q":"Real estate tax delinquency at a HUD-assisted property is significant in a MOR because:","opts":["It is the management agent's personal liability","It is a financial red flag suggesting the property cannot meet its obligations","It only affects the property's NSPIRE score","It is a tenant protection issue, not a management compliance issue"],"ans":1,"exp":"Tax delinquency signals financial stress and potential inability to maintain the property. It is a significant concern in the MOR financial management review area."}]},"m83":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"What should a professional desk review package begin with?","opts":["The most recent MOR report","A comprehensive document index (table of contents)","The property's current HAP voucher","The owner's financial statement"],"ans":1,"exp":"A document index signals systematic, thorough management and allows the reviewer to quickly locate any requested document."},{"q":"When submitting an electronic desk review package, what file format is standard?","opts":["Word document (.docx)","Excel spreadsheet (.xlsx)","PDF format","HTML files"],"ans":2,"exp":"PDF format is standard for electronic desk review packages. Use consistent naming conventions and a clear folder structure."},{"q":"What does a 'continuous desk review readiness posture' mean in practice?","opts":["Having the desk review package ready six months before any MOR","Maintaining compliance such that a complete, accurate desk review package can be assembled within one week at any time","Keeping the most recent MOR report on file at all times","Requiring monthly audits of all financial records"],"ans":1,"exp":"Continuous readiness means maintaining compliance daily — not just preparing for a known MOR — so that a desk review package is always within days of assembly."},{"q":"When correcting a known deficiency before submitting the desk review package, what must be documented?","opts":["The estimated cost of the correction","What was wrong, when it was corrected, and who made the correction","Only the final corrected version of the document","The name of the employee who created the original deficiency"],"ans":1,"exp":"All pre-MOR corrections must be documented — what was wrong, when corrected, and who corrected it. This documentation may mitigate the severity of a finding."},{"q":"Under no circumstances should a consultant or management agent alter, backdate, or falsify original documents because:","opts":["It is against company policy","It is fraud that HUD reviewers are trained to detect, with consequences including False Claims Act liability","It is unfair to other properties that don't falsify documents","It creates additional paperwork for HUD staff"],"ans":1,"exp":"Falsifying documents is fraud. HUD reviewers are trained to detect it, and the consequences — including False Claims Act liability — are severe."},{"q":"How often should a mock desk review be conducted?","opts":["Only in the year a MOR is expected","Every two years","Quarterly, regardless of when the next MOR is expected","Monthly for troubled properties only"],"ans":2,"exp":"Quarterly mock desk reviews using Form 9834 maintain a continuous readiness posture and catch issues long before they become MOR findings."},{"q":"A 'hybrid' submission approach for desk review packages means:","opts":["Submitting some documents electronically and some physically based on sensitivity","Submitting an electronic package in advance and bringing a physical binder for on-site reference","Having both the owner and the management agent submit separate packages","Submitting a draft first, followed by a final version"],"ans":1,"exp":"A hybrid approach — electronic submission in advance plus a physical reference binder on-site — is practical and professional."},{"q":"How long must tenant files be retained by HUD rule?","opts":["One year after the tenant vacates","Three years minimum after the tenant vacates","Seven years from initial move-in","Ten years regardless of tenancy status"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD generally requires tenant file retention for a minimum of three years after the tenant vacates. State law may require longer retention."},{"q":"An 'MOR Readiness Assessment' as a consulting service product should include:","opts":["Only an EIV compliance review","A comprehensive evaluation using Form 9834, including tenant file sample, EIV review, waiting list review, and written findings report","Only financial document review","Staff performance reviews"],"ans":1,"exp":"An MOR Readiness Assessment uses Form 9834 as the framework to comprehensively evaluate every review area, producing a prioritized remediation report."},{"q":"Why is a pre-2025 Tenant Selection Plan a concern in a 2025 MOR?","opts":["TSPs were not required before 2025","HOTMA required TSPs to be updated by January 1, 2025, so a pre-2025 TSP that hasn't been updated is non-compliant","TSPs change annually based on HUD income limits","Only TSPs created before 2020 are a concern"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA required all TSPs to be updated to reflect new program requirements by January 1, 2025. A pre-2025 TSP that hasn't been updated is an immediate finding."},{"q":"Signing the EIV Participation Agreement is:","opts":["Optional for small properties under 50 units","Required only for management companies, not individual property managers","Required for all authorized EIV users as part of obtaining system access","A one-time requirement that never needs to be renewed"],"ans":2,"exp":"All authorized EIV users must sign the Participation Agreement as part of obtaining and maintaining access. This document must be in the EIV master binder."},{"q":"If a reviewer requests documents in a specific portal format and the management agent misses the upload requirement, what is the likely result?","opts":["The reviewer will call to ask for the missing document","A delayed review and a negative first impression for the management team","The MOR will be rescheduled automatically","An automatic Below Average rating"],"ans":1,"exp":"Missing a portal-specific upload delays the review and creates a poor impression. Always confirm the required submission platform with the reviewer when scheduling."},{"q":"What is the business value of an 'MOR Readiness Assessment' to a client?","opts":["Emergency-only value for properties that just failed a MOR","A proactive investment that saves the cost of findings, corrective action cycles, and potential rating decline","A product offered only to large portfolio owners","A compliance formality with limited practical value"],"ans":1,"exp":"The readiness assessment creates direct ROI by identifying and correcting issues before they become findings — avoiding the cost of corrective action cycles."},{"q":"What is the key output of a quarterly mock desk review?","opts":["A list of tenants who need recertification","A prioritized compliance gap list to be addressed before the next actual review","A financial variance report for the owner","An NSPIRE pre-inspection report"],"ans":1,"exp":"The quarterly mock desk review produces a prioritized gap list — specific issues to correct before the next actual MOR review."},{"q":"Why should a pre-submission desk review package review be conducted by someone other than the assembler?","opts":["HUD requires a second signer on all desk review packages","A second set of eyes catches items that familiarity blinds the assembler to","The reviewer is required to confirm the package before submission","It is required under HOTMA for all properties"],"ans":1,"exp":"A second reviewer catches errors the original assembler misses due to familiarity. This simple quality control step reduces the risk of missing deficiencies."}]},"m91":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"What HUD handbook chapter provides detailed guidance on tenant file requirements?","opts":["Chapter 3","Chapter 9 of Handbook 4350.3 REV-1 Change-4","Chapter 5 of Handbook 4350.1","Chapter 12 of Handbook 7420.8"],"ans":1,"exp":"Chapter 9 of HUD Handbook 4350.3 REV-1 Change-4 provides the primary guidance on tenant file requirements."},{"q":"The HUD form that authorizes HUD and the owner to obtain income verification from third parties is:","opts":["HUD Form 9834","HUD Form 9887","HUD Form 50059","HUD Form 5382"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD Form 9887 (Release of Information/Privacy Act Notice) authorizes HUD and the owner to obtain income verification and must be signed by all adult household members."},{"q":"What is the companion form to HUD Form 9887?","opts":["HUD Form 9887-A","HUD Form 9834-A","HUD Form 50058","HUD Form 5380"],"ans":0,"exp":"HUD Form 9887-A (Applicant/Tenant Consent to Release of Information) accompanies Form 9887 and authorizes third-party verifications."},{"q":"When should a move-in unit inspection form be signed?","opts":["Within 30 days of move-in","On or before the move-in date","At the first annual recertification","At the time of lease renewal"],"ans":1,"exp":"The move-in inspection must be completed and signed on or before the move-in date to document unit condition at tenancy commencement."},{"q":"What must a rejection notice for an applicant include?","opts":["Only the owner's name and property address","The specific reason for rejection, the right to request an informal hearing, and the appeal deadline","A list of all applicants currently ahead on the waiting list","The name of the next eligible applicant"],"ans":1,"exp":"A rejection notice must state the specific reason, the right to an informal hearing, and the deadline for requesting that hearing."},{"q":"How long must tenant files be retained after a tenant vacates?","opts":["One year","Two years","Three years minimum","Seven years"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD requires a minimum of three years of retention after the tenant vacates. State law may require longer."},{"q":"A move-in package is backdated after the tenant has already taken occupancy. This is:","opts":["Acceptable if the documentation is accurate","A common and accepted industry practice","A MOR finding and potentially fraudulent","Only a problem if the tenant complains"],"ans":2,"exp":"Backdated move-in packages are a common finding and a red flag. All move-in documentation must be dated the actual move-in date."},{"q":"The EIV Existing Tenant Search must be run when?","opts":["Annually for all current tenants","Before each new move-in","Only when an applicant fails credit screening","Quarterly for properties with turnover"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Existing Tenant Search must be run before each new move-in to verify the applicant is not already receiving Section 8 elsewhere."},{"q":"If a household member is a live-in aide, their income is:","opts":["Counted at 50% toward annual income","Fully counted the same as any household member","Excluded from annual income and eligibility determination","Counted only if they work outside the home"],"ans":2,"exp":"Live-in aide income is not counted in the household's income for eligibility or rent calculation. The aide has no independent tenancy rights."},{"q":"Which of the following is a 'dual purpose' for tenant files?","opts":["Administrative management of the tenancy and audit demonstration of compliance","Fair housing marketing and tenant eligibility screening","HAP billing and TRACS transmission","Staff performance evaluation and regulatory reporting"],"ans":0,"exp":"Tenant files serve both an administrative purpose (managing the tenancy) and an audit purpose (demonstrating compliance to reviewers)."},{"q":"All significant correspondence between the property and the tenant should be:","opts":["Maintained by the tenant only","Kept in the tenant file or a related management file","Discarded after 90 days","Submitted to HUD annually"],"ans":1,"exp":"All significant correspondence — notices, lease violations, maintenance requests, accommodation requests — should be in the tenant file to document the management relationship."},{"q":"SSN documentation must be in the file for:","opts":["Only the head of household","All adult household members who are eligible for assistance","Only household members who are employed","The head of household and co-head only"],"ans":1,"exp":"SSN documentation must be in the file for all household members who are eligible for assistance, not just the head of household."},{"q":"What does the criminal background screening documentation in a tenant file demonstrate?","opts":["That the management agent is more thorough than required","That screening was conducted consistently per the TSP criteria and the disposition is documented","That all tenants have passed a federal background check","That the property complies with VAWA criminal history provisions"],"ans":1,"exp":"Criminal background screening documentation demonstrates consistent application of TSP criteria and the basis for approval or rejection decisions."},{"q":"A security deposit must be held in:","opts":["The property's operating account for convenience","The owner's personal checking account","A separate account as required by the lease and applicable state law","An account controlled by HUD"],"ans":2,"exp":"Security deposits must be held in a separate account (typically interest-bearing) per lease requirements and state law. Commingling with operating funds is impermissible."},{"q":"A tenant's reasonable accommodation request must be documented in:","opts":["The property's general policy notebook only","The tenant file, including the request, interactive process, supporting documentation, and outcome","HUD's national accommodation tracking system","The property's maintenance log"],"ans":1,"exp":"Every reasonable accommodation request, the interactive process, supporting documentation, and the outcome must be in the tenant file."}]},"m92":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"When must an annual recertification be completed?","opts":["Within 30 days after the certification anniversary date","On or before the tenant's certification anniversary date","Anytime within the calendar year of the anniversary","Within 60 days before or after the anniversary"],"ans":1,"exp":"Annual recertifications must be completed on or before the anniversary date. Late certifications are one of the most common MOR findings."},{"q":"How many days before the certification anniversary must the owner issue the recertification notice?","opts":["30 days","60 days","90 days","120 days"],"ans":3,"exp":"HUD requires the recertification notice to be issued no later than 120 days before the certification anniversary date."},{"q":"Which tier of verification is the highest-priority in HUD's income verification hierarchy?","opts":["Tenant-provided documents (pay stubs)","Third-party written verification","Upfront Income Verification (UIV)","EIV system data"],"ans":3,"exp":"EIV system data is the highest-priority (Tier 1) verification method. When EIV data is available, it must be considered and reconciled against tenant-reported income."},{"q":"What is the deadline for transmitting a completed certification to TRACS?","opts":["Within 15 days of effective date","Within 30 days of effective date","Within 60 days of effective date","Within 90 days of effective date"],"ans":2,"exp":"Certifications must be transmitted to TRACS within 60 days of the effective date."},{"q":"An interim certification is mandatory when a household member:","opts":["Turns 65 years of age","Gets married to someone outside the household","Has a reportable income increase between annual certifications","Renews their driver's license"],"ans":2,"exp":"Income increases trigger mandatory interim certifications. The owner must capture the increase and adjust rent accordingly."},{"q":"Does an interim certification restart the annual certification clock?","opts":["Yes — the annual certification is now due one year from the interim","No — the next annual certification remains due on the original anniversary date","Only if the interim is processed more than 6 months before the anniversary","Yes, but only for households with fixed incomes"],"ans":1,"exp":"An interim certification does not restart the annual certification clock. The next annual is due on the original anniversary date regardless."},{"q":"An employer verification letter used to support an income calculation must be dated within how many days of the certification effective date?","opts":["30 days","60 days","90 days","120 days"],"ans":3,"exp":"Income verifications must be dated within 120 days of the certification effective date to be considered current."},{"q":"Using tenant-provided documents (Tier 4) as the primary verification when third-party verification is available is:","opts":["Acceptable if the tenant provides originals","A finding","Acceptable for self-employed tenants only","Required under HOTMA as a simplification measure"],"ans":1,"exp":"Tier 4 documentation may only be used when higher-tier verification is not available. Using it when Tier 1-3 is available is a finding."},{"q":"What is the Total Tenant Payment (TTP)?","opts":["The gross rent charged to all tenants regardless of income","The greater of 30% of monthly adjusted income, 10% of monthly gross income, welfare rent, or minimum rent","The HAP amount paid by HUD to the owner","The utility allowance divided by the contract rent"],"ans":1,"exp":"TTP is the greater of four calculations: 30% of monthly adjusted income, 10% of monthly gross income, welfare rent, or minimum rent."},{"q":"The HAP amount is calculated as:","opts":["Contract rent minus utility allowance","Contract rent minus net tenant rent (TTP minus utility allowance)","Total tenant payment plus the utility allowance","Gross rent minus the income limit percentage"],"ans":1,"exp":"HAP = Contract Rent minus Net Tenant Rent. Net Tenant Rent = TTP minus Utility Allowance. If UA exceeds TTP, the tenant pays no rent and may receive a utility reimbursement."},{"q":"Regular overtime pay that a tenant has consistently received for 18 months should be:","opts":["Excluded since it is not guaranteed","Counted as anticipated income based on established pattern","Treated as non-recurring income and excluded","Averaged over three years before including"],"ans":1,"exp":"Regular overtime that is a consistent pattern of employment is anticipated income and must be included in the income calculation."},{"q":"The two-person quality control review is a best practice for certifications because:","opts":["HUD requires it for all certifications over $500 HAP","It catches errors the original preparer missed due to familiarity before TRACS transmission","It reduces the management agent's liability for HOTMA noncompliance","It allows both staff members to sign the TIC"],"ans":1,"exp":"A second reviewer uses a checklist to verify income, assets, signatures, and effective date — eliminating most certification errors before they reach TRACS."},{"q":"What is the primary cause of certification timing errors in tenant files?","opts":["Tenants refusing to provide income documentation","A failure in the tracking system that allows anniversary dates to pass unnoticed","HUD changing anniversary date rules annually","Software errors in the TRACS submission system"],"ans":1,"exp":"Properties that allow certifications to slip are almost always those without a functional tracking system that alerts staff 120, 90, and 60 days before each anniversary."},{"q":"When is a tenant entitled to a utility reimbursement?","opts":["When their income decreases","When the utility allowance exceeds their Total Tenant Payment","When they install energy-efficient appliances","When they pay utilities directly to the property"],"ans":1,"exp":"When the utility allowance exceeds the TTP, the tenant pays no rent and may be entitled to a utility reimbursement — which the owner must pay and claim in HAP billing."},{"q":"The gross Social Security benefit used for income calculation should be:","opts":["The net amount after Medicare deduction (what the tenant actually receives)","The gross amount before Medicare deduction","The average of the last three years of benefit amounts","The amount shown on the tenant's most recent bank statement"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD uses the gross Social Security amount before Medicare deduction. Many managers incorrectly use the net after-Medicare-deduction amount."}]},"m93":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"A live-in aide's income is treated how for certification purposes?","opts":["Counted in full as regular household income","Counted at 50% since the aide is not the primary tenant","Excluded from income and eligibility determination","Counted only for asset imputation purposes"],"ans":2,"exp":"Live-in aide income is excluded from the household's income for eligibility and rent calculation. The aide has no independent tenancy rights."},{"q":"Under what condition can a live-in aide be screened by the management agent?","opts":["Never — aides cannot be screened","For criminal history and legitimate management concerns, but not for income or financial standards","Only if the tenant requests it","Only using the same criteria as regular applicants"],"ans":1,"exp":"The management agent may screen a live-in aide for criminal history and other legitimate concerns but may not require the aide to meet income or financial standards."},{"q":"Under the student eligibility rules, which student would be eligible for Section 8 assistance?","opts":["A 19-year-old single student enrolled full-time at a community college","A 22-year-old student who is married with two children","A 20-year-old student whose parents have very high income","A part-time student who is 17 years old"],"ans":1,"exp":"A married student meets the exemption. Single students under age 24 without dependent children generally do not qualify for Section 8 assistance."},{"q":"The student eligibility restrictions apply to:","opts":["Full-time students only","Part-time students only","Both part-time and full-time students","Only students at accredited four-year universities"],"ans":2,"exp":"Student eligibility restrictions apply to both part-time and full-time students enrolled in an institution of higher education."},{"q":"What is a 'mixed-status family' under HUD housing rules?","opts":["A family with both adults and children","A household where some members are eligible citizens/immigrants and others are not","A family receiving both Section 8 and LIHTC benefits","A household where income comes from multiple sources"],"ans":1,"exp":"A mixed-status family has some household members who are U.S. citizens or eligible immigrants and others who are neither. HUD requires prorated assistance."},{"q":"In a household of 4 where 3 members are eligible for assistance, what is the prorated assistance percentage?","opts":["25%","50%","75%","100%"],"ans":2,"exp":"Assistance is prorated to the percentage of eligible members. 3 of 4 eligible = 75% of what the household would receive if all were eligible."},{"q":"The income of ineligible household members in a mixed-status family is:","opts":["Completely excluded from eligibility determination","Counted in the eligibility determination even though those members don't receive assistance","Counted only if it exceeds the income limit","Counted only for asset imputation"],"ans":1,"exp":"Income from ineligible family members is counted in the eligibility determination even though those members do not receive assistance. This can make the mixed-status family ineligible."},{"q":"What is the minimum rent amount for Section 8 new construction and substantial rehabilitation properties?","opts":["$0","$25 per month","$50 per month","$100 per month"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD sets a minimum rent of $25 per month. This minimum applies even when the calculated tenant rent would otherwise be zero."},{"q":"A tenant requests a hardship exemption from the minimum rent. What must the owner do?","opts":["Immediately grant the exemption permanently","Suspend the minimum rent for 90 days while evaluating the request","Deny the request since minimum rent is always required","Refer the tenant to the local Housing Authority"],"ans":1,"exp":"Upon receiving a hardship exemption request, the owner must suspend the minimum rent for 90 days while evaluating the request."},{"q":"A zero income household certification requires:","opts":["No special documentation since zero income is straightforward","Signed zero-income certifications from each adult and investigation of how the household meets basic living expenses","Only EIV verification","HUD's prior written approval"],"ans":1,"exp":"Zero income households require signed zero-income certifications from each adult and investigation of how the household is meeting basic living expenses. EIV will often show whether undisclosed income exists."},{"q":"What documentation is required when a unit transfer occurs?","opts":["Only a new lease","New certification, new lease, move-out inspection, move-in inspection, transfer approval letter, and updated TRACS transmission","Only updated TRACS transmission","No documentation needed — a verbal agreement with the tenant is sufficient"],"ans":1,"exp":"Unit transfers require a new certification, new lease (or lease amendment), move-out and move-in inspections, a transfer approval letter, and updated TRACS transmission."},{"q":"When a household composition change adds a new adult member, the management agent must:","opts":["Wait until the next annual recertification to update the file","Verify the new member's income and process an interim certification","Obtain HUD approval before allowing the new member to move in","Simply add the person's name to the existing lease"],"ans":1,"exp":"Adding a new adult to the household requires verifying their income and processing an interim certification to reflect the updated household composition."},{"q":"Under VAWA, a victim of domestic violence who needs to move to a safer unit is entitled to:","opts":["An emergency transfer if a safe unit is available on the property or in the owner's portfolio","An immediate guarantee of relocation anywhere in the country","Priority placement on any HUD waiting list in the country","A rent-free period while alternative housing is found"],"ans":0,"exp":"Under VAWA 2022, a victim is entitled to an emergency transfer to another available unit on the property or in the owner's portfolio, handled per the Emergency Transfer Plan."},{"q":"The parental income test for student eligibility applies to a student who is:","opts":["Any student regardless of age or family status","A dependent student not meeting any of the listed exemptions","A student over age 24","A student receiving any form of financial aid"],"ans":1,"exp":"The parental income test applies to students who are dependents under IRS rules and do not meet any of the exemptions (age 24+, married, veteran, etc.)."},{"q":"Which of the following represents a valid hardship exemption trigger for the minimum rent?","opts":["Tenant voluntarily reducing work hours","Loss of employment creating genuine financial hardship","Tenant's preference to pay less rent","Disagreement with the rent calculation"],"ans":1,"exp":"Qualifying hardship circumstances include loss of employment, death of a family member, medical emergency, or similar extraordinary circumstances. Voluntary income reduction or preference does not qualify."}]},"m94":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"HOTMA's occupancy-related amendments became fully effective on what date?","opts":["January 1, 2020","October 1, 2023","January 1, 2025","July 1, 2025"],"ans":2,"exp":"HOTMA's implementing regulations affecting Section 8 multifamily occupancy standards became fully effective on January 1, 2025."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, households with total assets at or below what threshold may provide a self-certification instead of third-party verification?","opts":["$5,000","$10,000","$25,000","$50,000"],"ans":3,"exp":"Under HOTMA (effective January 1, 2025), households with total assets not exceeding $50,000 may provide a signed self-certification rather than third-party verification."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, what households are eligible for biennial (every-other-year) recertification?","opts":["All households regardless of income source","Households where all adults receive income exclusively from fixed sources (Social Security, SSI, etc.)","Households with no assets","Elderly households only"],"ans":1,"exp":"Biennial recertification is available to households where all adult members receive income exclusively from fixed sources. Households with any employment income are not eligible."},{"q":"The biennial recertification option is:","opts":["A tenant right — tenants may demand biennial recertification if they meet the criteria","An owner election — owners must elect to offer it and document this election","Automatically applied to all eligible households without any action needed","Required by HOTMA for all eligible households"],"ans":1,"exp":"The biennial recertification option is available to owners — it is not a tenant right. The owner must elect to offer it and document this election."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, a lump sum inheritance received by a tenant should be treated as:","opts":["Annual income in the year received","An asset that may generate imputed income","Non-reportable since inheritances are personal gifts","Annual income spread over five years"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA clarified that one-time lump sum additions to family assets (inheritances, insurance settlements) are excluded from annual income and treated as assets that may generate imputed income."},{"q":"When a household self-certifies assets under $50,000, must they still report income earned from those assets?","opts":["No — self-certification replaces all asset documentation requirements","Yes — actual income from assets must still be estimated and counted in the annual income calculation","Only if assets exceed $5,000","Only if the income exceeds $500 per year"],"ans":1,"exp":"Self-certification eliminates the need for bank statements — it does not eliminate the counting of asset income. The household must still estimate actual income from assets."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, depreciation is:","opts":["An allowable deduction for self-employment income for HUD purposes","NOT an allowable deduction for HUD purposes, despite being deductible for IRS purposes","Allowed up to the amount of the federal tax depreciation deduction","Allowed for residential rental income only"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA maintained the rule that depreciation is NOT an allowable deduction for HUD income calculation purposes, even though it is allowed for IRS Schedule C purposes."},{"q":"A TSP last updated in 2022 (before HOTMA) and not reviewed since is:","opts":["Still valid since HOTMA changes are still being phased in","Non-compliant as of January 1, 2025 — TSPs were required to be updated by that date","Valid for two more years before requiring update","Only non-compliant if a MOR reviewer specifically requests a 2025 update"],"ans":1,"exp":"All properties were required to update their TSPs to reflect HOTMA by January 1, 2025. A pre-2025 TSP that hasn't been reviewed against HOTMA requirements is non-compliant today."},{"q":"Before a revised TSP can be distributed and used, it must be:","opts":["Posted on the property's website","Reviewed and approved by HUD or the CA","Signed by all current tenants","Approved by a majority vote of current tenants"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD or the CA must review and approve updated TSPs. Properties cannot unilaterally implement TSP changes without HUD approval."},{"q":"Which of the following is a HOTMA-required update to the Tenant Selection Plan?","opts":["Adding a section on online application submission","Updating criminal history screening language consistent with HUD guidance on individualized assessments","Removing all income limit references","Adding tenant satisfaction surveys"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA required TSPs to reflect updated criminal history screening language consistent with HUD guidance on individualized assessments, among other changes."},{"q":"The HOTMA biennial recertification option requires that in the 'off year' (the year without a full recertification):","opts":["No action is taken and rent remains unchanged","The tenant's rent is adjusted for any annual COLA to their fixed income sources","A partial recertification is completed","The management agent must still obtain income verifications"],"ans":1,"exp":"In the intervening year, the tenant's rent is adjusted for any annual COLA to their fixed income sources without requiring a full recertification."},{"q":"A management agent continues to require bank statements from all tenants regardless of asset level after January 1, 2025. This is:","opts":["Best practice — more documentation is always better","Not a compliance issue since the agent can choose stricter standards","Potentially creating an unnecessary administrative burden and must be applied consistently to avoid fair housing concerns","Required under HOTMA for all households"],"ans":2,"exp":"While requiring bank statements doesn't violate HOTMA's minimum standard, requiring them only from some households could create fair housing concerns. The HOTMA self-certification option reduces burden for eligible households."},{"q":"What is the primary consulting opportunity created by the HOTMA transition?","opts":["Properties are already compliant and don't need help","Many properties haven't updated their certifications, TSPs, and EIV processes for HOTMA — creating high demand for compliance assessment services","HOTMA simplified compliance so consulting demand has decreased","Only newly constructed properties are affected by HOTMA"],"ans":1,"exp":"Many management agents received limited formal training on HOTMA before January 1, 2025. Properties that haven't been trained are likely non-compliant in multiple areas — a significant consulting opportunity."},{"q":"Full-time students under age 18 — their earned income is:","opts":["Counted in full as household income","Excluded from annual income under HOTMA","Counted only if it exceeds $480 per year","Counted as 50% of actual amount"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA confirmed that earned income of full-time students under age 18 is excluded from annual income."},{"q":"Once a revised TSP is approved, it must be distributed to:","opts":["Only new applicants going forward","All applicants on the waiting list (notice of material changes), and made available to any applicant upon request","Only tenants currently in residence","HUD only — tenants are not entitled to copies"],"ans":1,"exp":"The updated TSP must be provided to all waiting list applicants as notice of material changes, made available to any applicant upon request, and posted in the management office."}]},"m101":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"Annual income for HUD certification purposes is best described as:","opts":["Last year's actual income from all sources","All amounts anticipated to be received from outside the family in the next 12 months","The household's adjusted gross income per the IRS","The average of the past three years of household income"],"ans":1,"exp":"Annual income is a projection of anticipated income over the next 12 months — not a historical average."},{"q":"The dependent deduction in HUD's adjusted income calculation is:","opts":["$240 per dependent per year","$480 per dependent per year","$1,000 per dependent per year","$400 per dependent per year"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD allows a $480 annual deduction for each dependent household member who is not the head, co-head, or spouse."},{"q":"The elderly/disabled household deduction is:","opts":["$480 per elderly/disabled member","$400 per household where head, co-head, or spouse is elderly or disabled","$1,200 per household annually","$240 per elderly/disabled member"],"ans":1,"exp":"The elderly/disabled deduction is $400 per household (not per member) where the head, co-head, or spouse is age 62+ or disabled."},{"q":"Out-of-pocket medical expenses exceeding what percentage of annual income may be deducted for elderly/disabled households?","opts":["1%","3%","5%","10%"],"ans":1,"exp":"Out-of-pocket medical expenses exceeding 3% of annual income may be deducted for elderly or disabled households."},{"q":"Childcare expenses may be deducted if they enable a family member to:","opts":["Attend medical appointments","Work, look for work, or attend school full-time","Care for elderly relatives","Participate in community activities"],"ans":1,"exp":"Childcare expenses for children under 13 are deductible if they enable a family member to work, look for work, or attend school full-time."},{"q":"Social Security benefits used in an income calculation should be:","opts":["The net amount after Medicare deduction","The gross amount before Medicare deduction","The amount deposited to the tenant's bank account","The amount shown on Form 1099-SSA"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD uses the gross Social Security benefit before the Medicare deduction. Many managers incorrectly use the net after-Medicare amount."},{"q":"A tenant consistently receives overtime pay averaging $200/month over the past 18 months. How should this be treated?","opts":["Excluded since overtime is not guaranteed","Included as anticipated income since it is a consistent pattern","Included at 50% since it may not continue","Only included if the employer confirms it in writing"],"ans":1,"exp":"Regular, consistent overtime is anticipated income and must be counted in the annual income calculation."},{"q":"For a self-employed tenant, HUD counts:","opts":["Gross receipts without any deductions","Net income — gross receipts minus allowable deductions, excluding depreciation","Net income per the IRS Schedule C including all deductions","Only income reported on IRS Form W-2"],"ans":1,"exp":"For self-employed tenants, HUD counts net income (gross receipts minus allowable deductions), with the key exception that depreciation is NOT an allowable deduction."},{"q":"Child support received on behalf of minor children is:","opts":["Excluded since it is for the children, not the parent","Included in family annual income","Included only if it exceeds $1,000 per year","Included only if paid by court order"],"ans":1,"exp":"Child support received on behalf of minor children is included in family annual income."},{"q":"A tenant earns tips at a restaurant job but only reports a small amount. EIV wage data shows significantly higher earnings. The manager should:","opts":["Accept the tenant's reported figure since tips are informal","Investigate the discrepancy — significant EIV/reported income differences require resolution","Exclude tip income since it is cash and unverifiable","Only use the EIV figure without investigation"],"ans":1,"exp":"Significant discrepancies between reported income and EIV data require investigation. EIV wage data for service workers often reflects IRS-reported wages including reported tips."},{"q":"Foster care payments are generally:","opts":["Fully included in annual income","Excluded from income if paid specifically for a foster child, per applicable HUD guidance","Included at 50% of the payment amount","Included only if they exceed the minimum rent threshold"],"ans":1,"exp":"Most foster care payments are excluded from income if specifically paid for a foster child. Verify the exclusion based on the specific payment structure."},{"q":"A tenant who just started a new job should have annual income projected at:","opts":["The average of the prior year's wages","The annualized rate based on the new job's pay","Zero until 90 days of employment are completed","The same as the prior certification"],"ans":1,"exp":"Annual income is a projection of anticipated income. A tenant who just started a new job should have income projected at the new job's annualized rate."},{"q":"What income is counted for a tenant who owns and rents out real property?","opts":["Gross rent received without any deductions","Net rental income — rent received minus operating expenses, not including mortgage principal or depreciation","Only income in excess of the applicable income limit","None — rental income from personal property is excluded"],"ans":1,"exp":"Net rental income (gross rent minus operating expenses, excluding mortgage principal and depreciation) is counted as annual income."},{"q":"Which of the following is NOT an allowable adjusted income deduction?","opts":["$480 dependent deduction","$400 elderly/disabled household deduction","Mortgage payments on a primary residence","Out-of-pocket medical expenses exceeding 3% AMI for elderly households"],"ans":2,"exp":"Mortgage payments are not a HUD adjusted income deduction. The allowable deductions are: dependent ($480), elderly/disabled ($400), medical expenses (3% threshold for eligible households), and childcare."},{"q":"A lump-sum inheritance received by a tenant under HOTMA is treated as:","opts":["Annual income in the year received, creating an immediate rent increase","An asset — increasing household assets and potentially generating imputed income","Non-reportable since inheritances are personal matters","Annual income spread equally over five years"],"ans":1,"exp":"Under HOTMA, lump-sum additions to family assets (inheritances, insurance settlements) are excluded from annual income and treated as assets."}]},"m102":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"When do total assets exceed $5,000, what additional calculation is required?","opts":["Run a credit check on all adult household members","Compare actual income from assets against imputed income at the passbook rate and count the higher amount","Submit the asset information to EIV for verification","Obtain a professional appraisal of all asset values"],"ans":1,"exp":"When total assets exceed $5,000, compare actual income from assets against imputed income (assets × passbook rate) and count whichever is greater."},{"q":"The passbook rate is used to:","opts":["Determine the minimum savings required for move-in","Calculate imputed income from assets when actual income is lower","Establish the interest rate on tenant security deposits","Calculate the gross rent ceiling for a unit"],"ans":1,"exp":"The passbook rate calculates imputed income — the return that could theoretically be earned on assets held in a basic savings account."},{"q":"A household has $30,000 in assets earning $150/year in actual income. The passbook rate is 0.06%. What income from assets is counted?","opts":["$0 since assets are below $50,000","$18 (imputed)","$150 (actual)","$168 (actual plus imputed)"],"ans":2,"exp":"Imputed income = $30,000 × 0.06% = $18. Actual income = $150. Since $150 > $18, actual income ($150) is counted."},{"q":"A household has $30,000 in cash earning no interest. What income from assets is counted?","opts":["$0 since no actual income is generated","$18 (imputed at 0.06% passbook rate)","$150 (standard minimum asset income)","$30,000 (full asset value)"],"ans":1,"exp":"Actual income = $0. Imputed income = $30,000 × 0.06% = $18. Since $18 > $0, the imputed income ($18) is counted."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, households with assets of $50,000 or less may provide:","opts":["No asset documentation at all","A signed self-certification on the HUD-approved form instead of third-party verification","Only a verbal confirmation to the property manager","A simple note signed by the tenant"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA allows households with assets at or below $50,000 to use the HUD-approved self-certification form rather than third-party bank statements."},{"q":"The $50,000 HOTMA self-certification threshold and the $5,000 passbook rate rule are:","opts":["The same rule with different thresholds for different property types","Two separate, simultaneous rules that both apply","The HOTMA rule replaces the old $5,000 rule entirely","Only the $50,000 rule applies after January 1, 2025"],"ans":1,"exp":"These are two separate rules. The $50,000 threshold determines whether self-certification is permitted. The $5,000 threshold triggers the passbook rate comparison. Both can apply to the same household simultaneously."},{"q":"What types of accounts must be counted as household assets?","opts":["Only accounts with balances over $1,000","Checking accounts, savings accounts, money market accounts, and certificates of deposit for all household members","Only accounts in the head of household's name","Only accounts at federally-insured institutions"],"ans":1,"exp":"All bank accounts for all household members must be counted — checking, savings, money market, and CDs."},{"q":"A tenant sold their house to an adult child for $40,000 below fair market value 18 months ago. What must the management agent count?","opts":["Nothing — the transaction was personal and is not relevant to certification","The $40,000 difference as if it were still an asset, for up to two years from the date of disposal","Only the sale proceeds actually received by the tenant","The full fair market value of the property"],"ans":1,"exp":"When assets are disposed of below fair market value within the past two years, the difference between FMV and amount received must be counted as if it were still an asset."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, equity in real property other than the primary residence is:","opts":["Excluded since it is not a liquid asset","Counted as a household asset","Counted only if the property generates rental income","Excluded for properties valued under $100,000"],"ans":1,"exp":"Under HOTMA, equity in real property other than the primary residence is a countable household asset."},{"q":"Retirement accounts (IRA, 401k) are included in assets based on:","opts":["The future projected value at retirement","The current cash value net of any withdrawal penalty","The original contributions only","The employer contribution only"],"ans":1,"exp":"Retirement accounts are valued at the current cash value, net of any early withdrawal penalty — what the household could actually access today."},{"q":"Which is a correct asset for HUD certification purposes?","opts":["A personal vehicle used for daily transportation","Cash value of a whole life insurance policy","Face value of term life insurance","Household furniture and appliances"],"ans":1,"exp":"The cash value (not face value) of whole life or universal life insurance is counted. Term insurance has no cash value. Personal vehicles and household goods are excluded."},{"q":"A household self-certifies assets below $50,000. The manager notices other information suggesting higher assets. The manager may:","opts":["Not investigate — the self-certification is legally final","Request verification of assets, documenting the specific reason to avoid fair housing concerns","Automatically deny housing to the household","Report the household to HUD without further investigation"],"ans":1,"exp":"If other information suggests higher asset levels, the manager has the right to request verification. The reason must be documented to avoid discriminatory application."},{"q":"Joint accounts with non-household members are counted at:","opts":["The full value regardless of who owns it","The household's percentage share of the account","50% of the total value always","Zero since the non-household member owns a portion"],"ans":1,"exp":"Joint accounts with non-household members are counted based on the household's percentage share of the account."},{"q":"Why does self-certification under HOTMA still require the household to report income from assets?","opts":["It doesn't — self-certification eliminates all asset income reporting","Self-certification eliminates the need for bank statements but not the requirement to count income earned from assets","It is a transitional requirement that will be phased out","HUD requires it only for households with assets over $25,000"],"ans":1,"exp":"Self-certification eliminates the need for third-party bank statements. It does not eliminate the counting of income actually earned from those assets in the annual income calculation."},{"q":"Necessary personal property such as clothing, furniture, and a car used for transportation:","opts":["Must be counted as assets at their current market value","Are excluded from household assets","Are included if their total value exceeds $5,000","Are included only if they could be sold for more than their depreciated value"],"ans":1,"exp":"Necessary personal property — clothing, furniture, a car used for transportation — is excluded from household assets."}]},"m103":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"EIV use for covered multifamily housing programs is:","opts":["Strongly recommended but not legally required","Mandatory under 24 CFR 5.233","Required only for properties with 50 or more units","Required only for properties with HAP contracts executed after 2010"],"ans":1,"exp":"EIV use is mandatory under 24 CFR 5.233 for all covered HUD multifamily programs. This is a regulatory requirement, not guidance."},{"q":"What does the EIV Income Report show?","opts":["The property's financial income and expenses","Federal agency income data for each household member with a valid SSN","The full employment history of all applicants","Bank account balances for all household members"],"ans":1,"exp":"The EIV Income Report displays income reported by federal agencies — Social Security, SSI, pension income, and IRS wage data — for household members with valid SSNs."},{"q":"The Existing Tenant Search must be run before move-in to check for:","opts":["Prior criminal history at a HUD property","Duplicate Section 8 assistance at another location","Outstanding maintenance requests from a prior property","Prior evictions from any property"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Existing Tenant Search searches HUD's database to determine if the applicant is already receiving Section 8 or other HUD assistance at another property."},{"q":"How often must the Multiple Subsidy Report be run?","opts":["Monthly","Quarterly","At least annually","Every two years"],"ans":2,"exp":"The Multiple Subsidy Report must be run at least annually to identify tenants potentially receiving duplicate housing assistance at multiple HUD properties."},{"q":"EIV is a supplement to — not a replacement for — standard income verification because:","opts":["EIV is not always accurate and should be ignored","EIV does not capture all income — it may not reflect current-year wages, self-employment, cash income, or rental income","EIV data is outdated by three years","EIV requires consent from the tenant before being used"],"ans":1,"exp":"EIV does not capture all income types. It is a supplement to standard verification methods — an additional check, not the complete verification."},{"q":"Generally, EIV income discrepancies must be resolved within:","opts":["7 business days","30 days","60 days","6 months"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD requires EIV income discrepancies to be resolved generally within 60 days of discovery. Document every step with dates."},{"q":"When an authorized EIV user leaves the organization, their EIV access must be:","opts":["Terminated within 90 days","Immediately terminated upon departure","Transferred to another authorized user","Maintained for 30 days for transition purposes"],"ans":1,"exp":"EIV access must be immediately terminated when an authorized user leaves or changes roles. Using a former employee's credentials is a violation."},{"q":"The EIV Participation Agreement must be signed by:","opts":["The property owner only","All authorized EIV users as part of obtaining access","The property manager once per year regardless of users","The HUD Field Office representative annually"],"ans":1,"exp":"All authorized EIV users must sign the EIV Participation Agreement as part of obtaining access. The signed agreements must be in the EIV master binder."},{"q":"Before accessing EIV, each user must complete:","opts":["A HUD field office orientation","HUD's EIV Computer-Based Training (CBT)","A background investigation by HUD","A two-day on-site training at HUD headquarters"],"ans":1,"exp":"Each authorized user must complete HUD's online EIV Computer-Based Training (CBT) before receiving access. Training completion certificates must be in the EIV master binder."},{"q":"What is the purpose of the Failed Pre-Screening Report?","opts":["To identify tenants who failed credit screening","To identify household members whose SSNs could not be pre-screened by EIV","To document failed income verifications","To flag properties with frequent certification errors"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Failed Pre-Screening Report identifies household members whose SSNs could not be pre-screened by EIV — typically those without SSNs or with SSN data issues."},{"q":"EIV data printed from the system may not be:","opts":["Retained for more than 30 days","Left unsecured or transmitted via unencrypted email","Shared with the property owner without HUD approval","Included in the EIV master binder"],"ans":1,"exp":"EIV data must be handled with strict security: not left unsecured and not transmitted via unencrypted email. It may only be used for authorized income verification purposes."},{"q":"An annual review of authorized EIV users should confirm all of the following EXCEPT:","opts":["All current users are still employed and authorized","All users have current training certifications","The Participation Agreement is current","The total dollar amount of EIV-identified discrepancies for the year"],"ans":3,"exp":"The annual security review confirms active users, current training, and current Participation Agreement. Tracking dollar amounts is not part of the security review."},{"q":"If the Income Report shows a significant discrepancy, the first step in the resolution process is:","opts":["Immediately increase the tenant's rent to match EIV data","Provide the tenant written notice and request an explanation with supporting documentation","File a report with HUD's Inspector General","Close out the EIV discrepancy without investigation"],"ans":1,"exp":"The first step is notifying the tenant in writing and requesting an explanation and documentation. The tenant typically has 10 business days to respond."},{"q":"A property with no EIV usage and no EIV master binder in a 2025 MOR will likely receive:","opts":["A notation but no formal finding since EIV is complex","One of the most heavily-weighted MOR findings given EIV's mandatory status under 24 CFR 5.233","An invitation to attend HUD training only","No finding since the MOR focuses on tenant files, not EIV"],"ans":1,"exp":"EIV noncompliance is one of the most heavily weighted MOR findings given its mandatory regulatory status. A complete absence of EIV usage is among the most serious compliance failures."},{"q":"An EIV SOP (Standard Operating Procedure) at the property should describe:","opts":["Only the EIV login credentials for authorized users","Who is authorized, which reports to run and when, how discrepancies are documented and resolved, where records are kept, and how security requirements are enforced","The technical specifications of the EIV system","The list of income sources EIV covers by federal agency"],"ans":1,"exp":"The EIV SOP is an operational guide covering authorized users, report schedules, discrepancy resolution, record storage, and security enforcement."}]},"m111":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"What must be stamped on each waiting list application?","opts":["The applicant's SSN","Date and time of application","The income limit category","The reviewing officer's initials"],"ans":1,"exp":"Applications must be date- and time-stamped to establish the order in which applicants will be served (subject to any approved preferences)."},{"q":"HUD-approved preferences on a waiting list must be:","opts":["Developed annually by the management agent","In the approved Tenant Selection Plan and applied consistently","Applied only to new applications, not to existing waitlist members","Set unilaterally by the owner without HUD review"],"ans":1,"exp":"Preferences must be in the approved TSP and applied consistently. Preferences not in the TSP cannot be applied."},{"q":"A waiting list opening notice must be published in:","opts":["The local newspaper only","One source reaching the general public","Broad public channels reaching all community segments including minority populations and persons with disabilities","The management office only"],"ans":2,"exp":"Waiting list openings require broad public notice reaching all community segments — not just a single general circulation newspaper."},{"q":"What must happen before a waiting list can be purged?","opts":["HUD must pre-approve the purge","A documented 30-day written notice must be sent to each applicant subject to purge","The owner must obtain consent from each applicant","A public announcement must be placed in the newspaper"],"ans":1,"exp":"A purge protocol must include written notice to each applicant, a reasonable response period (typically 30 days), removal only upon failure to respond, and documentation."},{"q":"An AFHMP that has not been updated in six years is:","opts":["Acceptable since AFHMPs don't expire","An immediate MOR finding since AFHMPs must be updated every five years","Only a concern if the waiting list lacks diversity","Acceptable for small properties under 25 units"],"ans":1,"exp":"The AFHMP must be updated every five years. An expired AFHMP is an immediate MOR finding."},{"q":"The AFHMP requires documentation of:","opts":["Tenant satisfaction ratings","Marketing activities targeting underrepresented groups, with evidence of implementation","The property's physical condition score","Income limits applied in the prior year"],"ans":1,"exp":"The reviewer examines both the AFHMP document and evidence that marketing activities were actually conducted — advertising invoices, outreach letters, and minority media contacts."},{"q":"When a waiting list is closed, applicants already on the list:","opts":["Lose their position and must reapply when the list reopens","Must be notified that their position is preserved","Are automatically offered the next available unit","Must resubmit income verification documents"],"ans":1,"exp":"When closing the waiting list, applicants already on it must be notified that their position is preserved."},{"q":"A skip on the waiting list occurs when:","opts":["An applicant is permanently removed","An applicant is temporarily bypassed but remains on the list","An applicant accepts a unit but later changes their mind","The management agent makes a clerical error in applicant ordering"],"ans":1,"exp":"A skip means an applicant is temporarily bypassed but retained on the list — for example, when a unit of the needed size isn't currently available."},{"q":"How many income limit categories does HUD publish for Section 8 programs?","opts":["Two: low and very low income","Three: extremely low (30% AMI), very low (50% AMI), and low (80% AMI)","Four including moderate income","Five based on household size only"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD publishes three income limit categories: Extremely Low Income (30% AMI), Very Low Income (50% AMI), and Low Income (80% AMI)."},{"q":"Section 8 programs typically require that what percentage of new admissions each year be to Extremely Low Income families?","opts":["10%","20%","40%","75%"],"ans":2,"exp":"Section 8 programs typically require that 40% of new admissions per year be to families at or below 30% AMI (Extremely Low Income)."},{"q":"What is an overhoused tenant?","opts":["A tenant paying too much rent relative to income","A tenant occupying a unit larger than their family size justifies","A tenant with assets exceeding the income limit","A tenant who has been on the waiting list too long"],"ans":1,"exp":"An overhoused tenant occupies a unit that is larger than their household size requires. Owners must offer appropriately sized units when they become available."},{"q":"Electronic waiting list software must have:","opts":["A mobile app for applicants","A complete audit trail of every change with who made it, when, and why","Integration with TRACS","HUD-specific certification"],"ans":1,"exp":"Electronic waiting list software must have an audit trail documenting every status change — if the software lacks this capability, it is inadequate for compliance purposes."},{"q":"The AFHMP connection to the waiting list means that:","opts":["The waiting list ranking is set by the AFHMP","Waiting list demographic data provides feedback on whether AFHMP marketing is reaching target groups","The AFHMP sets income limits for waiting list applicants","Applicants from the AFHMP targeted groups bypass the waiting list"],"ans":1,"exp":"Waiting list demographics are the feedback mechanism for the AFHMP. If the list doesn't reflect targeted diversity, marketing activities may need to be adjusted."},{"q":"How must the application process be accessible per HUD requirements?","opts":["Only if a federal ADA complaint has been filed","For persons with disabilities: alternative formats, in-person options for those who can't apply online, and staff assistance","Only in writing via mail","Through technology only, since all applications must be submitted online"],"ans":1,"exp":"The application process must be accessible to persons with disabilities — alternative formats, in-person options, and staff assistance must be available upon request."},{"q":"Records of rejected applicants must be retained for:","opts":["90 days only","One year","At least three to seven years, depending on applicable law","Only until the waiting list is reopened"],"ans":2,"exp":"Rejected application records must be retained for a period sufficient to demonstrate fair housing compliance — generally three to seven years depending on applicable law."}]},"m112":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"A screening criterion not written in the TSP:","opts":["May be applied at the management agent's discretion","Cannot be applied — if it's not in the TSP, it should not be used","May be applied if the owner approves it verbally","May be applied for protected class members only"],"ans":1,"exp":"If a criterion is not in the TSP, it should not be applied to applicants. Unapproved criteria are both a MOR finding and a fair housing risk."},{"q":"Under HUD's guidance, criminal history screening should use:","opts":["Blanket bans on all persons with any criminal record","Individualized assessment considering nature, severity, time elapsed, and evidence of rehabilitation","Credit score thresholds as a proxy for criminal risk","Only the last five years of criminal history regardless of offense type"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD guidance encourages individualized assessment of criminal history. Blanket bans on any criminal record likely create disparate impact fair housing liability."},{"q":"Which of the following is a mandatory exclusion from Section 8 housing under HUD regulations?","opts":["Any person with a prior felony conviction","Any person who has ever been evicted","Persons convicted of methamphetamine production on federally assisted property","Persons with two or more minor criminal violations"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD regulations mandate exclusion of persons convicted of methamphetamine production on federally assisted property and registered sex offenders required to register for life."},{"q":"The FCRA applies when:","opts":["Any income verification is conducted","The property uses consumer credit reports in the screening process","The property uses EIV to verify income","The property conducts criminal background checks without a consumer reporting agency"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Fair Credit Reporting Act applies when properties use consumer credit reports. It requires written consent, adverse action notices, and dispute resolution procedures."},{"q":"Under VAWA, an applicant's history as a victim of domestic violence may not be used to:","opts":["Verify their income for eligibility purposes","Deny their application for housing","Determine their preference category on the waiting list","Assess their suitability for a particular unit size"],"ans":1,"exp":"Under VAWA, victim status cannot be used to deny housing. The property must assess the applicant using the same criteria applied to all applicants."},{"q":"The 40% ELI (Extremely Low Income) admissions requirement applies to:","opts":["All occupied units at all times","New admissions in any given calendar year","All recertifications","Only newly constructed properties"],"ans":1,"exp":"The 40% ELI requirement applies to new admissions in a calendar year — 40% of households newly admitted in any year must be at or below 30% AMI."},{"q":"What must a rejection notice include under HUD requirements?","opts":["A waiting list ranking for when the applicant can reapply","The specific reason for rejection, the right to an informal hearing, and the deadline for requesting it","The names of other properties with available units","A general statement that the applicant did not meet all criteria"],"ans":1,"exp":"Rejection notices must be specific about the reason, inform the applicant of their right to a hearing, and state the deadline for requesting one."},{"q":"An 'informal hearing' for a rejected applicant must be conducted by:","opts":["The same staff member who made the rejection decision","An impartial party not involved in the original rejection decision","A HUD Field Office representative","The property owner personally"],"ans":1,"exp":"The hearing must be conducted by an impartial party — typically someone not involved in the original rejection decision."},{"q":"A TSP screening criterion that disproportionately excludes applicants of a protected class may violate the Fair Housing Act through:","opts":["Disparate treatment — intentional discrimination","Disparate impact — facially neutral policy with discriminatory effect","Neither — screening criteria are always exempt from fair housing review","Both disparate treatment and disparate impact simultaneously"],"ans":1,"exp":"A facially neutral screening criterion that disproportionately screens out a protected class can constitute disparate impact discrimination under the Fair Housing Act."},{"q":"Source of income discrimination protection means:","opts":["Owners must accept all forms of government assistance in all states","Many states and localities prohibit using source of income (including housing vouchers) as a basis for rejection","HUD prohibits asking about income sources during applications","All owners must accept Section 8 vouchers regardless of their HAP contract"],"ans":1,"exp":"Many states and localities prohibit discrimination based on source of income, which includes refusing applicants with housing vouchers. Check local law for each property."},{"q":"How long must documentation of a rejected application be retained?","opts":["30 days","90 days","At least three years","One year"],"ans":2,"exp":"Documentation of rejections — the rejection letter, hearing records, and decisions — must be retained for at least three years."},{"q":"The TSP must be approved by HUD before being implemented because:","opts":["HUD collects TSPs for national housing research purposes","The owner cannot unilaterally change eligibility criteria in a federally-assisted program","The management agent is not authorized to make policy decisions","Tenants have a right to vote on TSP criteria"],"ans":1,"exp":"Properties cannot unilaterally implement TSP changes. HUD or the CA must review and approve updated TSPs before they take effect."},{"q":"Which HOTMA update is required in the TSP effective January 1, 2025?","opts":["Increasing minimum income requirements for applicants","Updating criminal history screening language consistent with HUD guidance on individualized assessments","Removing all preferences from the waiting list","Requiring biometric identification for applicants"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA required TSPs to be updated to reflect new program requirements, including updated criminal history screening language consistent with HUD guidance."},{"q":"The informal hearing officer's written decision must include:","opts":["The owner's final determination signed by the management company CEO","The factual and legal basis for the decision","Only the outcome (approved or rejected)","A citation to the specific HUD handbook provision violated"],"ans":1,"exp":"The written decision must state the factual and legal basis — not just the outcome. This creates a reviewable record."},{"q":"An applicant who is rejected may request an informal hearing within:","opts":["72 hours","7 days","The deadline specified in the rejection notice, typically 14 days from receipt","60 days from the rejection date"],"ans":2,"exp":"The hearing request deadline is specified in the rejection notice — typically 14 days from receipt of the rejection letter."}]},"m113":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"How many protected classes does the federal Fair Housing Act recognize?","opts":["Three","Five","Seven","Ten"],"ans":2,"exp":"The Fair Housing Act recognizes seven protected classes: race, color, national origin, religion, sex, disability, and familial status."},{"q":"Under current HUD interpretation, the sex protected class includes:","opts":["Biological sex only","Gender identity and sexual orientation","Sex as defined by birth certificate only","Sex and age combined"],"ans":1,"exp":"Under current HUD interpretation, the sex protected class includes gender identity and sexual orientation, consistent with VAWA 2022 and HUD fair housing guidance."},{"q":"Familial status as a protected class protects:","opts":["Only married couples with children","Families with children under 18, pregnant women, and persons obtaining custody of children","Only families with more than three children","All family types regardless of composition"],"ans":1,"exp":"Familial status protects families with children under 18, pregnant women, and persons in the process of obtaining custody of a child."},{"q":"A facially neutral policy that disproportionately affects a protected class without a justifying business necessity is an example of:","opts":["Disparate treatment","Disparate impact","Steering","Redlining"],"ans":1,"exp":"Disparate impact occurs when a facially neutral policy has a discriminatory effect on a protected class, even without discriminatory intent."},{"q":"A reasonable accommodation request may be denied only if:","opts":["The tenant has not lived in the unit for at least one year","Granting it would impose undue financial and administrative burden or fundamentally alter the housing program","The requested accommodation is novel or unusual","More than three accommodation requests have been made in a year"],"ans":1,"exp":"An accommodation may be denied only if it imposes undue hardship. The burden is on the owner to demonstrate the hardship. Most requests are reasonable and should be granted."},{"q":"During the reasonable accommodation interactive process, the management agent may:","opts":["Demand disclosure of the specific diagnosis","Request documentation of the disability and the functional need, without demanding a specific diagnosis","Deny the request until the tenant provides three medical opinions","Require the tenant to pay a fee for processing the accommodation"],"ans":1,"exp":"The management agent may request documentation of the disability and the functional need — but may not demand disclosure of a specific diagnosis."},{"q":"Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act applies to:","opts":["All rental housing regardless of funding source","Programs or activities receiving federal financial assistance","Only federally owned public housing","Only properties built after 1990"],"ans":1,"exp":"Section 504 prohibits discrimination against persons with disabilities in programs or activities receiving federal financial assistance, including HUD-assisted properties."},{"q":"Section 504 physical accessibility requirements for substantially rehabilitated federally-assisted properties include:","opts":["100% of units must be accessible","5% mobility accessible and 2% sensory accessible units","10% of units accessible for any disability type","At least one accessible unit per building"],"ans":1,"exp":"Section 504 requires that 5% of units in substantially rehabilitated federally-assisted properties be accessible for mobility impairments and 2% for visual/hearing impairments."},{"q":"A Section 504 Coordinator must be designated for entities with how many or more employees?","opts":["5 employees","10 employees","15 employees","25 employees"],"ans":2,"exp":"Section 504 requires designation of a 504 Coordinator for entities with 15 or more employees. The coordinator must be identified to applicants and tenants."},{"q":"A reasonable modification is:","opts":["A change in rules or policies to accommodate a disabled person","A physical change to a unit or common area that enables a disabled person to use the housing","A financial adjustment to rent for disabled tenants","A change in lease terms for disability-related reasons"],"ans":1,"exp":"A reasonable modification is a physical change to a unit or common area — grab bars, ramps, wider doorways — that enables a person with a disability to use the housing."},{"q":"In a HUD-assisted property, who typically pays for a reasonable modification?","opts":["HUD directly","The management agent from operating funds","Generally the tenant, though Section 504 may require the owner to pay in some circumstances","The tenant's insurance company"],"ans":2,"exp":"In conventional housing, tenants pay for modifications. For HUD-assisted properties, Section 504 may require the owner to pay for modifications in some circumstances."},{"q":"Fair housing training must be provided to:","opts":["Only property managers and leasing agents","All staff who interact with applicants or tenants, including maintenance and security","Only corporate management of the management company","Only staff hired in the past 12 months"],"ans":1,"exp":"All staff who interact with applicants or tenants — leasing agents, managers, maintenance, and security — must receive fair housing training."},{"q":"When a fair housing complaint is received, the correct response is to:","opts":["Refer the complaint to the owner's attorney and take no other action","Respond in writing, investigate promptly, and document every step","Dismiss the complaint if it appears unfounded","Contact HUD to inform them the complaint is baseless"],"ans":1,"exp":"Respond in writing, investigate promptly, and document every step. Never dismiss or minimize a fair housing complaint."},{"q":"Current HUD fair housing posters must be displayed:","opts":["Only in the management office","In the management office and wherever rental applications are provided","Throughout all common areas of the property","On the outside of every unit door"],"ans":1,"exp":"Fair housing posters must be prominently displayed in the management office and wherever rental applications are provided."},{"q":"A 'no pets' policy cannot be used to refuse a service animal or emotional support animal because:","opts":["HUD requires all properties to allow all animals","Assistance animals are not pets — they are accommodations for persons with disabilities and must go through the reasonable accommodation process","The Fair Housing Act categorically requires all animals to be permitted","Only service dogs, not emotional support animals, are protected"],"ans":1,"exp":"Service animals and emotional support animals are accommodations for persons with disabilities, not pets. Requests for assistance animals must be processed through the reasonable accommodation interactive process."}]},"m121":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"VAWA 2022 explicitly extended protections to which group not previously covered by name?","opts":["Persons over age 65","LGBTQ+ individuals","Non-citizen residents","Persons with disabilities"],"ans":1,"exp":"VAWA 2022 explicitly extended protections to LGBTQ+ individuals, clarifying that VAWA protections apply regardless of sex or gender identity."},{"q":"Under VAWA, being a victim of covered violence may not be used as a basis for:","opts":["Filing a police report","Denying housing, terminating a tenancy, or evicting the victim","Requesting reasonable accommodations","Requesting a unit transfer"],"ans":1,"exp":"VAWA prohibits using victim status as the basis for denying housing, terminating tenancy, charging fees related to the incident, or evicting the victim."},{"q":"The perpetrator of domestic violence is protected under VAWA:","opts":["Yes, if they are the primary leaseholder","Yes, equally with the victim","No — VAWA does not protect the perpetrator","Only if the perpetrator is also a protected class member under the Fair Housing Act"],"ans":2,"exp":"VAWA does not protect the perpetrator of the violence. The owner may evict the perpetrator while allowing the victim to remain."},{"q":"HUD Form 5380 must be provided to a tenant within 14 calendar days of:","opts":["Any lease renewal","Any maintenance request","A tenant's request for the form","Move-out notice by the management agent"],"ans":2,"exp":"Form 5380 must be provided at application, lease signing/renewal, notice to vacate by the owner, and within 14 calendar days of a tenant's request."},{"q":"A tenant submits a completed HUD Form 5382 asserting VAWA victim status. What must the management agent do with this document?","opts":["File it in the general tenant file for easy access","Store it separately from the general tenant file in a locked, restricted-access location","Forward it to HUD for documentation purposes","Share it with maintenance staff for safety awareness"],"ans":1,"exp":"Form 5382 documents must be stored separately from the general tenant file in a locked, restricted-access location to prevent inadvertent disclosure."},{"q":"After a tenant submits Form 5382, the management agent has how many business days to take adverse action against the tenant based on the covered incident?","opts":["The agent may not take adverse action during the 14-day evaluation period","7 business days","30 days","Adverse action may be taken immediately upon receipt"],"ans":0,"exp":"The management agent may not take adverse action based on the covered incident during the 14 business days the tenant has to submit documentation."},{"q":"The Emergency Transfer Plan must include:","opts":["The names of all current VAWA-protected tenants on the property","Eligibility criteria, the request process, transfer prioritization, timeframes, and confidentiality protections","Only the management agent's contact information for emergency use","The list of VAWA-related crimes reportable to police"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Emergency Transfer Plan must describe eligibility criteria, the request process, prioritization, timeframes for processing, documentation requirements, and confidentiality protections."},{"q":"What is the current HUD model Emergency Transfer Plan form?","opts":["HUD Form 5380","HUD Form 5382","HUD Form 5381","HUD Form 9887"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD Form 5381 is the model Emergency Transfer Plan that properties may adopt or adapt. Using it ensures all required elements are present."},{"q":"A victim is eligible for an emergency transfer if:","opts":["Any household member has ever been convicted of a violent crime","They have lived at the property for at least 12 months","They have a reasonable belief the perpetrator will harm them in their current unit, or have been threatened or harassed there","Their income qualifies for an emergency housing voucher"],"ans":2,"exp":"VAWA emergency transfer eligibility requires that the victim has a reasonable belief they will be harmed in their current unit or has been threatened or harassed there by the perpetrator."},{"q":"VAWA victim status information must be kept:","opts":["Confidential — not shared with any other person without the victim's written consent","Available to all management staff for safety purposes","Available to maintenance staff for scheduling purposes","Reported to HUD Field Office within 14 days"],"ans":0,"exp":"VAWA status information must be kept strictly confidential. It may not be shared with anyone — including the alleged abuser — without the victim's written consent."},{"q":"Lease bifurcation is a tool that allows the owner to:","opts":["Split a single lease into annual and month-to-month terms","Terminate the perpetrator's portion of a joint lease while allowing the victim to remain","Modify rent amounts for VAWA-protected households","Add a victim's new support person to an existing lease without a new certification"],"ans":1,"exp":"Lease bifurcation allows the owner to remove the perpetrator from the lease while allowing the victim household member to remain as the leaseholder."},{"q":"VAWA protections do NOT protect a victim from:","opts":["Being questioned by police about reported incidents","Eviction for lease-violating behavior unrelated to their victim status (e.g., nonpayment of rent)","Being asked to document their status using Form 5382","Being offered an emergency transfer"],"ans":1,"exp":"VAWA protects victim status — not general lease violations. A victim may still be subject to lease enforcement action for unrelated violations."},{"q":"What constitutes alternate documentation to HUD Form 5382 for establishing VAWA status?","opts":["A notarized statement from the tenant alone","Police report, court order, documentation from a victim service provider, or statement from an attorney","Only court-issued orders of protection","Any written statement from any third party"],"ans":1,"exp":"Alternate documentation includes police reports, court orders, documentation from victim service providers, or attorney statements. Each is acceptable in lieu of Form 5382."},{"q":"When a new version of VAWA forms is issued (e.g., after VAWA 2022 reauthorization), properties must:","opts":["Continue using the prior version until new forms are formally distributed","Immediately adopt the current version — using outdated forms is a MOR finding","Ask HUD for a waiver to continue using older forms","Update only if a MOR reviewer specifically requests current forms"],"ans":1,"exp":"Properties must use current VAWA forms. Using forms from prior reauthorizations (2013 or 2015 versions) after the 2022 update is a MOR finding."},{"q":"Staff who work at the front desk and interact with tenants must be trained on VAWA because:","opts":["They are legally required to serve as VAWA advocates","They may receive tenant disclosures of victim status and must know how to handle them confidentially","Their training is required by the management company's insurance","Only if the property has more than 100 units"],"ans":1,"exp":"Front desk and all tenant-facing staff must be trained because they may receive disclosures of victim status, and mishandling these disclosures — even inadvertently — creates VAWA and fair housing liability."}]},"m122":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"Every adult household member must sign the HUD model lease. If an adult member does not sign, this is:","opts":["Acceptable if they are listed as a dependent","A MOR finding — unsigned leases are an immediate compliance issue","Only an issue at lease renewal","Acceptable if the management agent signs a waiver"],"ans":1,"exp":"Every adult household member must sign the lease. Unsigned leases are findings."},{"q":"A 'side agreement' between an owner and tenant that is not reflected in the lease is:","opts":["Permissible if the owner approves it in writing","Impermissible — the lease represents the entire agreement","Allowed for utility arrangements only","Required for live-in aide provisions"],"ans":1,"exp":"No side agreements outside the lease are permitted. The lease must reflect the complete agreement between owner and tenant."},{"q":"Acceptable grounds for lease termination in HUD-assisted housing include:","opts":["Any reason the owner considers valid","Serious or repeated lease violations, criminal activity, or other good cause","Termination without cause on 60 days' notice","The tenant has lived in the unit for more than five years"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD lease termination must be for cause — serious or repeated lease violations, criminal activity, or other documented good cause. Termination without cause is not permitted."},{"q":"Before initiating eviction proceedings, HUD-assisted owners must:","opts":["Obtain HUD's written approval for the eviction","Give the tenant the opportunity to request a grievance hearing","File a police report documenting the lease violation","Obtain a court order permitting eviction"],"ans":1,"exp":"Before filing for eviction, HUD-assisted owners must provide the tenant the opportunity to request an informal hearing under the property's grievance procedure."},{"q":"The minimum notice period for most lease terminations in HUD-assisted housing is:","opts":["7 days","14 days","30 days","60 days"],"ans":2,"exp":"For most violations, the minimum notice period is 30 days. The notice must specify the grounds, the effective date, and the tenant's rights."},{"q":"HAP contract terms — specifically the contract rent for a unit — may be changed:","opts":["At any time by the owner based on market conditions","Only through formal amendment with HUD approval and use of HUD-approved Annual Adjustment Factors","By the management agent unilaterally with 30 days' tenant notice","Annually without any formal process"],"ans":1,"exp":"Contract rent changes must follow the HAP contract process using HUD-published Annual Adjustment Factors or comparability studies, and require formal amendment."},{"q":"A HAP contract that has lapsed because it wasn't renewed in time means:","opts":["Tenants must pay full market rent immediately","The property loses its subsidy stream — there are no HAP payments without an active contract","Only new admissions are affected","The management agent must continue paying HAP from operating funds"],"ans":1,"exp":"A lapsed HAP contract means no assistance payments. The renewal process must begin at least 12 months before expiration."},{"q":"House rules that have not been reviewed and approved by HUD:","opts":["Are acceptable as long as they are reasonable","Are unenforceable and create MOR findings","May be enforced if tenants sign an acknowledgment","Are acceptable for safety-related rules only"],"ans":1,"exp":"House rules must have been reviewed and approved by HUD or the CA. Unapproved rules are unenforceable and create findings."},{"q":"Selective enforcement of house rules against some tenant groups more than others is a:","opts":["Permissible management discretion","Fair housing violation","Finding only if complaints are filed","Finding only if EIV data shows an income discrepancy"],"ans":1,"exp":"Selective enforcement of house rules against certain demographic groups is a fair housing violation even if the rules themselves are neutral."},{"q":"A tenant grievance hearing must be conducted by:","opts":["The property manager who made the contested decision","An impartial hearing officer not involved in the original decision","HUD's Office of Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity","A judge from the local housing court"],"ans":1,"exp":"The hearing officer must be impartial — typically someone who was not involved in the original decision being contested."},{"q":"A tenant's right to bring a representative to a grievance hearing includes the right to bring:","opts":["Only immediate family members","An attorney or tenant advocate","Only persons who witnessed the disputed event","Only other tenants from the same property"],"ans":1,"exp":"Tenants may bring any representative to a grievance hearing, including an attorney or tenant advocate."},{"q":"A 'no pets' policy in house rules applies to assistance animals:","opts":["Yes — all animals including assistance animals must comply with the no pets policy","No — assistance animal requests must be processed through the reasonable accommodation procedure","Yes, but with a higher pet deposit for assistance animals","Only for emotional support animals, not trained service dogs"],"ans":1,"exp":"Assistance animals are not pets. A no pets rule cannot be used to deny an assistance animal — the request must go through the reasonable accommodation process."},{"q":"An ownership transfer of a property with an active HAP contract requires:","opts":["No action — the new owner assumes the contract automatically","HUD approval before the transfer takes effect","Only notification to HUD within 60 days after the transfer","Notification to tenants only, not to HUD"],"ans":1,"exp":"Ownership transfers with active HAP contracts require HUD approval. Unauthorized transfers are HAP contract violations."},{"q":"When proposing a change to house rules, what process must be followed?","opts":["The owner may implement changes immediately if they are reasonable","Tenants must receive written notice (typically 30 days), then the proposed change must be submitted to HUD for approval","Only a simple majority of tenants must approve the change","Changes may be made unilaterally if they address safety issues"],"ans":1,"exp":"House rule changes require tenant notice (typically 30 days), followed by submission to HUD for approval before taking effect."},{"q":"Under VAWA, the lease bifurcation process is used when:","opts":["A household needs a larger unit","The management agent needs to remove the perpetrator from the lease while allowing the victim to remain","Both the victim and perpetrator agree to separate their tenancies","The tenant requests a roommate addition"],"ans":1,"exp":"Lease bifurcation allows termination of the perpetrator's portion of the joint lease while preserving the victim's tenancy rights."}]},"m123":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"The Reserve for Replacement account must be maintained:","opts":["In the property's general operating account for flexibility","In a separate interest-bearing account, not commingled with operating funds","In any account at the management agent's discretion","As a line item within the operating budget, not a separate account"],"ans":1,"exp":"The RFR must be in a separate interest-bearing account. Commingling with operating funds is an immediate finding."},{"q":"An owner who takes distributions from a property's cash in excess of the allowable surplus cash amount has:","opts":["Made a sound financial management decision","Violated the Regulatory Agreement — distributions may only be taken from surplus cash","Exercised their ownership rights under state law","Created a legitimate accounting entry that can be corrected later"],"ans":1,"exp":"Distributions may only be taken from surplus cash as calculated per the HUD formula. Excess distributions are Regulatory Agreement violations."},{"q":"The False Claims Act risk for affordable housing owners relates to:","opts":["Overstating property values in appraisals","Fraudulently obtaining federal funds through false HAP billing, distributions, or IOI transactions","Filing late audits with REAC FASS","Failing to maintain property insurance"],"ans":1,"exp":"The False Claims Act allows civil actions against owners who fraudulently obtain federal funds. Inaccurate HAP billing, improper distributions, and undisclosed IOI transactions create this risk."},{"q":"A Single Audit under OMB requirements is triggered when:","opts":["Any HUD-assisted property completes an annual audit","A property receives $750,000 or more in federal funds in a year","A property has more than 100 assisted units","The management agent is a for-profit entity"],"ans":1,"exp":"Properties receiving $750,000 or more in federal funds in a year are subject to OMB Single Audit requirements, which include compliance testing for federal programs."},{"q":"When is an annual audit due for a property with a December 31 fiscal year-end?","opts":["March 31 of the following year","June 30 of the following year","September 30 of the following year","December 31 of the following year"],"ans":2,"exp":"Audits are due within 9 months of the fiscal year-end. For a December 31 year-end, the audit is due by September 30."},{"q":"An 'identity of interest' relationship that is not disclosed to HUD is:","opts":["Only a concern if it involves an amount over $10,000","An immediate MOR finding — IOI relationships must be disclosed and may require HUD approval","Acceptable for small-dollar routine vendor contracts","A legal compliance issue separate from MOR review"],"ans":1,"exp":"All IOI relationships must be disclosed to HUD and may require approval. Failure to disclose is a MOR finding."},{"q":"The HAP billing voucher for a given month must reflect:","opts":["All units in the property regardless of occupancy status","Only currently assisted occupied units per their current certifications","The prior month's occupancy if the current month hasn't closed","An estimate based on the prior year's average"],"ans":1,"exp":"The HAP voucher must reflect currently assisted occupied units with HAP amounts matching current certifications exactly."},{"q":"Surplus cash at a HUD-assisted property is calculated:","opts":["As the balance in the operating account at year end","Semi-annually (June 30 and December 31) using the HUD-prescribed formula comparing available cash to required reserves and liabilities","Monthly based on the budget-to-actual comparison","Annually as part of the external audit"],"ans":1,"exp":"Surplus cash is calculated semi-annually using the HUD-prescribed formula. Only this calculation determines how much, if any, the owner may distribute."},{"q":"A management fee charged in excess of the amount in the approved management contract is:","opts":["Permissible if market rates have increased","A finding — only the approved management fee may be charged","Acceptable with retroactive HUD approval","Allowed if the additional fee is credited to the operating budget"],"ans":1,"exp":"Only the approved management fee may be charged. Additional unapproved fees are findings. Any additional fee structures require HUD approval."},{"q":"When the utility allowance exceeds a tenant's TTP, the tenant is entitled to:","opts":["A rent credit toward the next month's payment","A utility reimbursement payment, which the owner must pay and claim in HAP billing","No additional payment — the utility allowance is informational only","A reduced rent at their next annual recertification"],"ans":1,"exp":"When UA > TTP, the tenant owes no rent and may be entitled to a utility reimbursement. The owner pays this and claims it through HAP billing. Failure to pay is a finding."},{"q":"Audited financial statements must be submitted to HUD through:","opts":["Email to the HUD Field Office","REAC's Financial Assessment Subsystem (FASS)","The PBCA's local office","TRACS alongside certification data"],"ans":1,"exp":"Financial statements must be submitted to HUD through REAC FASS. Delivering a copy to the reviewer without FASS submission is insufficient."},{"q":"A RFR withdrawal made without prior HUD approval is:","opts":["Acceptable if the repair was genuinely needed","A serious MOR finding regardless of the reason for the withdrawal","Acceptable if documented within 30 days after the withdrawal","Only a finding if the withdrawal exceeds $10,000"],"ans":1,"exp":"Any RFR withdrawal requires prior HUD approval. Unapproved withdrawals are serious findings regardless of whether the repair was legitimate."},{"q":"A management letter finding from an annual audit that was not addressed in the following year's audit indicates:","opts":["The finding was too minor to address","A pattern of noncompliance that reviewers take very seriously","The auditor changed firms and dropped the prior year's findings","The finding was resolved informally and doesn't need to appear in the audit"],"ans":1,"exp":"Unresolved management letter findings that recur in subsequent audits indicate a pattern of noncompliance — a serious MOR concern."},{"q":"The HAP billing voucher amounts must reconcile precisely with:","opts":["Only the property's internal rent roll","Each tenant's current certification AND the TRACS database","Only the TRACS database","Only the prior year's voucher amounts adjusted for AAF"],"ans":1,"exp":"HAP voucher amounts must match both the current certification for each tenant and the TRACS database. Discrepancies with either source require correction."},{"q":"When retroactive HAP billing corrections reveal an overpayment, the owner must:","opts":["Keep the overpayment and apply it to the next period","Repay the overpayment to HUD and document the correction","Notify HUD but wait for HUD to reclaim the funds","Apply the overpayment as a credit to the management fee"],"ans":1,"exp":"Overpayments must be repaid. Maintain documentation of the discovery, calculation, and submission of the repayment."}]},"m131":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"What creates the primary demand for MOR consulting services?","opts":["HUD's requirement that all properties hire external consultants","The gap between HUD's regulatory requirements and most management agents' training and compliance practices","The mandatory HUD certification for all property managers","The high cost of self-directed compliance work"],"ans":1,"exp":"Most property managers learned on the job, accumulating informal knowledge and outdated practices that create a persistent compliance gap — which consultants help close."},{"q":"Which of the following is the highest-value MOR consulting niche mentioned in the course?","opts":["Routine file organization","Corrective Action Plan (CAP) consulting for properties under enforcement","Annual budget review","Utility allowance updates"],"ans":1,"exp":"CAP consulting is high-value because properties under corrective action face severe consequences, creating urgency and fee tolerance. The stakes are highest in this niche."},{"q":"What is the primary reason HOTMA creates a significant consulting opportunity in 2025?","opts":["HOTMA eliminated HAP contracts for some properties","Many properties haven't updated certifications, TSPs, and EIV processes for HOTMA — creating widespread non-compliance","HOTMA dramatically increased the complexity of physical inspections","HOTMA created new financial reporting requirements only for large portfolios"],"ans":1,"exp":"Many management agents received limited formal training on HOTMA before its January 1, 2025 effective date. Properties that haven't been updated are likely non-compliant in multiple areas."},{"q":"Errors and Omissions (E&O) insurance is essential for a compliance consultant because:","opts":["HUD requires all consultants to carry E&O insurance","It protects the consultant if a client attributes an adverse MOR outcome to incorrect advice provided","It covers the cost of correcting deficiencies found during an assessment","It is required by the state licensing board for housing consultants"],"ans":1,"exp":"E&O insurance protects the consultant if a client claims that incorrect advice led to an adverse MOR outcome. It is a non-negotiable professional protection."},{"q":"An engagement letter for a consulting engagement should define:","opts":["Only the fee and start date","Scope of services, fee and payment terms, start and end dates, liability limitations, confidentiality obligations, and dispute resolution process","The client's complete property history","The consultant's professional credentials and training"],"ans":1,"exp":"A comprehensive engagement letter protects both parties by defining scope, fees, timing, liability, confidentiality, and dispute resolution — preventing misunderstandings."},{"q":"Which fee structure is generally preferable for defined-scope MOR consulting engagements?","opts":["Hourly billing for all engagement types","Project-based (fixed) fees for defined scopes, with hourly billing reserved for open-ended engagements","Performance-based fees tied to the MOR rating achieved","Monthly retainer for all types of engagements"],"ans":1,"exp":"Fixed project fees make budgeting predictable for the client and incentivize the consultant to work efficiently. Hourly billing is appropriate for open-ended scopes."},{"q":"What annual recurring revenue could a consultant generate from 10 retainer clients at $1,000/month?","opts":["$10,000","$60,000","$120,000","$12,000"],"ans":2,"exp":"10 retainer clients × $1,000/month × 12 months = $120,000 per year in recurring revenue, before any project work."},{"q":"The most important distinguishing factor between a premium MOR consultant and a general practitioner is:","opts":["Higher fees regardless of service quality","Deep, current knowledge of HUD regulations and how they apply specifically to the client's situation","Proximity to HUD Field Offices","Number of clients served simultaneously"],"ans":1,"exp":"Premium consultants command higher fees because of their depth of current regulatory knowledge — particularly important after major changes like HOTMA."},{"q":"Why is a pre-engagement complimentary file sample review strategically valuable?","opts":["It satisfies HUD's requirement for third-party file review","If you identify specific deficiencies in their own files, you demonstrate your value more powerfully than any sales pitch","It allows you to quote a lower fee since you already understand the property","It is required by state licensing requirements for housing consultants"],"ans":1,"exp":"Finding specific, real deficiencies in a prospective client's files during a complimentary sample review establishes your expertise concretely before any fee is paid."},{"q":"When should you set expectations about likely MOR outcomes with a new client?","opts":["Only after the MOR is completed","During the initial engagement discovery, before the fee is agreed upon","Only if the client asks directly","At the exit conference after the actual MOR"],"ans":1,"exp":"Setting honest expectations upfront — about the likely scope of issues, timeline, and probable MOR outcome — builds trust and prevents disappointment."},{"q":"An MOR Readiness Assessment consulting product is best described as:","opts":["A one-time audit of physical building conditions","A comprehensive evaluation of the property's compliance posture using Form 9834, with a written findings report","A review of the property's financial statements only","A review limited to the EIV master binder"],"ans":1,"exp":"An MOR Readiness Assessment uses Form 9834 as the framework to evaluate every review area, producing a prioritized written findings and recommendations report."},{"q":"Which of the following is NOT a core MOR consulting service described in the course?","opts":["MOR Prep Package","HOTMA Compliance Assessment","NSPIRE Physical Inspection Service","Staff Training on EIV and certifications"],"ans":2,"exp":"The core MOR consulting services are the Readiness Assessment, Prep Package, HOTMA Assessment, Staff Training, and Ongoing Retainer. NSPIRE physical inspection is a separate specialty."},{"q":"What does it mean to 'position yourself as the person who prevents outcomes rather than responds to them'?","opts":["Refusing to work with properties that have received poor MOR ratings","Marketing proactive MOR readiness services rather than crisis response only","Guaranteeing that clients will receive Satisfactory ratings","Focusing only on financial management consulting"],"ans":1,"exp":"Positioning as a prevention-focused consultant means marketing ongoing readiness services — not just emergency response to failed MORs. Prevention clients are more stable and less stressful than crisis clients."},{"q":"What should be included in a HOTMA Compliance Assessment consulting service?","opts":["Physical inspection of all units","Review of certifications, TSP, EIV processes, and documentation for HOTMA compliance, effective January 1, 2025","Review of HAP contract renewal dates only","Review of the operating budget and RFR funding"],"ans":1,"exp":"A HOTMA Compliance Assessment focuses specifically on whether certifications, TSP, EIV processes, and documentation practices meet HOTMA requirements effective January 1, 2025."},{"q":"A client who has just received a Below Average MOR rating and is now under corrective action is best characterized as:","opts":["A difficult client to avoid since they are already non-compliant","A highly motivated potential client with urgent need and elevated fee tolerance","A low-priority prospect since the damage is already done","A client who does not need consulting since HUD will provide guidance"],"ans":1,"exp":"A client under corrective action faces serious consequences and is highly motivated to resolve them — creating urgency, fee tolerance, and a clear scope of work."}]},"m132":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"The first document to request from a prospective MOR consulting client is:","opts":["Their operating budget","Their most recent MOR report","Their HAP contract","Their EIV Participation Agreement"],"ans":1,"exp":"The most recent MOR report is the highest-value diagnostic tool — it reveals where the property has been deficient, which is likely where current deficiencies also exist."},{"q":"The pre-MOR file review should cover at minimum:","opts":["5% of occupied units","10% of occupied units or 10 files","20% of occupied units or 10 files, whichever is greater","50% of all files to be statistically valid"],"ans":2,"exp":"A thorough pre-MOR file review should cover at minimum 20% of occupied units or 10 files, whichever is greater — mirroring the standard HUD sample size."},{"q":"In a file review rating system, what does a 'Red' rating indicate?","opts":["The file is complete and fully compliant","A minor deficiency that is easily correctable","A significant deficiency requiring immediate corrective action","The file belongs to a high-income household"],"ans":2,"exp":"In a Green/Yellow/Red file rating system, Red indicates a significant deficiency requiring immediate attention — prioritizing the most critical files for correction first."},{"q":"Root cause analysis in a file review means:","opts":["Identifying who made the specific error in a file","Understanding why the error occurred systemically so the root cause can be corrected, preventing recurrence","Calculating the financial impact of each error","Documenting when each error was made for liability purposes"],"ans":1,"exp":"Root cause analysis identifies why errors occurred — training gap, process failure, etc. Fixing root causes prevents recurrence; fixing individual errors only solves this year's problem."},{"q":"A mock MOR should be scheduled at least how far in advance of the actual review?","opts":["One week before","Two weeks before","Four to six weeks before","Six months before"],"ans":2,"exp":"Schedule the mock MOR at least four to six weeks before the actual review to allow time to address findings before the real review."},{"q":"The mock exit conference serves what purpose?","opts":["To formally close the mock MOR engagement","To give the management team practice responding to findings in the same format as the actual exit conference","To provide a preliminary rating that will be sent to HUD","To give tenants an opportunity to raise concerns about management"],"ans":1,"exp":"The mock exit conference gives the management team practice presenting findings, responding professionally, and providing additional documentation — just as they will in the actual exit conference."},{"q":"After a mock MOR, what document drives the remaining pre-MOR work?","opts":["The updated HAP voucher","The mock MOR findings report, which becomes the corrective action work plan","The revised operating budget","The updated staff training schedule"],"ans":1,"exp":"The mock MOR findings report identifies specific deficiencies. This document becomes the prioritized work plan for the remaining weeks before the actual review."},{"q":"Staff training is necessary as well as file correction because:","opts":["HUD requires documented training as a standalone MOR item","Unless staff understand why errors were wrong and how to do it correctly, the same deficiencies will reappear at the next MOR","Training generates more revenue than file correction","Staff training is required under VAWA regardless of MOR"],"ans":1,"exp":"Correcting files addresses current symptoms. Training addresses the root cause — staff knowledge gaps — preventing recurrence at future reviews."},{"q":"A pre-test and post-test in a staff training session demonstrates:","opts":["That the trainer met their contractual obligation","Baseline knowledge levels, training effectiveness, and provides documentation of training completion","That the property is required to train staff annually","Staff compliance with EIV security requirements"],"ans":1,"exp":"Pre/post testing establishes baseline knowledge, demonstrates training effectiveness, and provides documented evidence of training completion — a valuable MOR record."},{"q":"If a client receives a good MOR outcome after your engagement, what should you do?","opts":["Immediately close the engagement and seek new clients","Propose an ongoing retainer to maintain the compliance posture achieved, and ask for a testimonial","Wait for them to call you before the next MOR","Share the client's property information with other potential clients as a case study"],"ans":1,"exp":"A good MOR outcome is the best moment to propose a retainer — the client sees your value clearly and wants to maintain it. Also request a testimonial while the satisfaction is fresh."},{"q":"Evidence packages for CAP completion should contain:","opts":["Only the management agent's statement that the item is corrected","The original finding, corrective action taken, documentation demonstrating completion, and date completed","A new lease for each tenant whose file was corrected","A certification from HUD accepting the correction"],"ans":1,"exp":"Evidence packages must document: the original finding, the specific correction, documented proof of completion (revised policies, training records, corrected files), and the date completed."},{"q":"The CAP must be submitted to HUD within how many days of receiving the MOR report?","opts":["7 days","14 days","30 days","60 days"],"ans":2,"exp":"The CAP must typically be submitted within 30 days of receiving the MOR report. Missing this deadline creates additional compliance exposure."},{"q":"A lessons-learned session after CAP completion serves what purpose?","opts":["To identify which staff member caused the most findings","To reinforce systemic improvements made and position ongoing consulting as quality assurance","To prepare the CAP for submission to HUD","To determine whether the management agent should be replaced"],"ans":1,"exp":"The lessons-learned session reinforces the improvements made, identifies remaining vulnerabilities, and positions the consultant's ongoing role as quality assurance."},{"q":"Scope creep in a consulting engagement means:","opts":["A finding that the file review underestimated the property's compliance issues","Additional work not included in the original scope, the most common cause of fee disputes","A client who expands their property portfolio after engagement begins","EIV discrepancies that expand beyond the original identified issues"],"ans":1,"exp":"Scope creep — work added beyond the original engagement scope — is the most common cause of fee disputes. Define scope carefully upfront and document changes."},{"q":"What is the primary business value of a detailed, organized mock MOR findings report?","opts":["It satisfies HUD's requirement for self-assessment","It gives the management team a specific, actionable work plan and demonstrates the consultant's professional thoroughness","It automatically reduces the severity of any subsequent actual MOR findings","It is required by professional liability insurers"],"ans":1,"exp":"A detailed findings report demonstrates professional rigor, creates a documented baseline, and gives the management team an actionable work plan with clear priorities."}]},"m133":{"title":"Chapter Quiz","questions":[{"q":"Where are your most likely first consulting clients to come from?","opts":["Cold calls to randomly selected affordable housing properties","People who already know you and trust your expertise — former employers, industry colleagues, contacts from training programs","HUD Field Office referrals","National advertising campaigns"],"ans":1,"exp":"First clients almost always come from existing relationships — people who already know your work. Warm outreach far outperforms cold outreach early in practice development."},{"q":"Your core value proposition as an MOR consultant should be expressible in:","opts":["A detailed 10-page capabilities statement","One to two sentences articulating the specific outcome you deliver for clients","A list of all HUD regulations you are familiar with","A description of your educational credentials"],"ans":1,"exp":"A clear one-to-two sentence value proposition — 'I help X achieve Y so they can Z' — is more memorable and persuasive than credentials lists."},{"q":"Thought leadership content for an MOR consulting practice might include:","opts":["Personal social media posts unrelated to housing","Articles in NAHMA News or housing association newsletters on specific MOR compliance topics","Annual holiday greeting cards to all contacts","Generic website content about affordable housing history"],"ans":1,"exp":"Articles on specific MOR topics — HOTMA changes, EIV compliance, VAWA updates — position you as an expert before the client ever calls."},{"q":"The most persuasive marketing content for an MOR consulting practice is:","opts":["A detailed biography of your credentials","Before/after case studies showing specific client outcomes (with permission)","A list of all HUD handbook chapters you have memorized","Testimonials from HUD reviewers praising your clients' compliance"],"ans":1,"exp":"Before/after case studies — 'Property X received Below Average twice; after our engagement they received Satisfactory and exited corrective action' — are far more persuasive than credentials."},{"q":"Which professional association is a primary networking venue for affordable housing consultants?","opts":["National Association of Realtors (NAR)","National Affordable Housing Management Association (NAHMA)","National Association of Home Builders (NAHB)","American Institute of Architects (AIA)"],"ans":1,"exp":"NAHMA is a primary professional association in affordable housing management. Joining and actively participating accelerates relationship-building in the target market."},{"q":"Referrals from which type of professional are most likely for MOR consulting work?","opts":["Residential real estate agents","Affordable housing attorneys, multifamily lenders, NSPIRE consultants, and management associations","Municipal code enforcement officers","Tenant advocacy organizations"],"ans":1,"exp":"Referral partners in adjacent services — housing attorneys, multifamily lenders, and NSPIRE consultants — serve the same clients and can refer business when clients need MOR expertise."},{"q":"Scaling a consulting practice by bringing on associates allows you to:","opts":["Avoid doing any compliance work yourself","Handle more simultaneous engagements and serve clients in geographies you cannot personally reach","Reduce your professional liability exposure","Eliminate the need for E&O insurance"],"ans":1,"exp":"Associates allow parallel delivery of assessments and training across multiple simultaneous clients and geographies, increasing practice capacity without the founder being a bottleneck."},{"q":"A 'productized service' in an MOR consulting practice means:","opts":["Selling software tools instead of consulting services","Converting customized consulting work into standardized deliverables delivered efficiently and consistently — like a checklist-based readiness assessment","Charging by the product (e.g., per file reviewed) rather than by project","Licensing your consulting methodology to other consultants"],"ans":1,"exp":"Productized services — standardized deliverables based on proven methodology — can be delivered consistently across multiple clients with reduced customization time."},{"q":"The most important ongoing investment in a compliance consulting practice is:","opts":["Purchasing compliance software tools","Staying current with HUD regulations through subscriptions, webinars, and professional associations","Building a large social media following","Hiring administrative support staff first"],"ans":1,"exp":"Staying current with HUD regulations — HOTMA, new guidance, PIH notices — is what differentiates a premium consultant. Without current knowledge, consulting advice can be harmful rather than helpful."},{"q":"Promising a client a guaranteed Satisfactory MOR outcome is:","opts":["An effective marketing strategy","Ethically problematic — over-promising damages your reputation if the guarantee cannot be kept","Required to win competitive engagements","Standard practice in the industry"],"ans":1,"exp":"Guaranteeing outcomes is over-promising. Outcomes depend on many factors outside the consultant's control. Honest expectation-setting is both ethical and better for long-term reputation."},{"q":"Developing deep expertise in a specialty area (e.g., HOTMA, Section 202, mixed-finance) allows you to:","opts":["Reduce your professional liability","Differentiate yourself from general practitioners and command premium fees","Avoid working with challenging properties","Reduce your engagement letter requirements"],"ans":1,"exp":"Specialty depth differentiates premium consultants from generalists. Deep expertise in high-demand areas commands higher fees and earns faster client trust."},{"q":"The ethical foundation of your consulting practice includes:","opts":["Advising clients on the minimum required to pass a MOR","Never advising document falsification, never accepting undisclosed compensation from vendors, and never exaggerating credentials","Recommending your preferred vendors to clients without disclosure","Sharing client information across engagements to provide better service"],"ans":1,"exp":"Ethical conduct — no document falsification, no undisclosed conflicts, no credential exaggeration — is the foundation of a sustainable practice. Your reputation is your most valuable asset."},{"q":"The mission alignment of MOR consulting with HUD's goals means:","opts":["Your work helps HUD avoid conducting MORs by keeping properties compliant","When you help a property achieve MOR compliance, you directly serve HUD's mission of ensuring families receive the quality of housing federal law requires","Your work primarily benefits property owners financially","Your work is in tension with HUD's oversight role"],"ans":1,"exp":"MOR compliance isn't just a regulatory exercise — it ensures residents receive the safe, decent, and affordable housing that federal subsidy is intended to provide. Your consulting work serves that mission."},{"q":"A reciprocal referral strategy means:","opts":["Paying referral fees to anyone who sends you a client","Also referring clients to other professionals when they need services you don't provide, building a network of mutual referral relationships","Requiring clients to refer other clients as a condition of engagement","Setting up a formal co-marketing program with other consultants"],"ans":1,"exp":"Reciprocal referrals — referring out when a client needs a fair housing trainer, CPA, or housing attorney — creates a network of professionals who send business back."},{"q":"Why are client testimonials and LinkedIn recommendations particularly valuable for an MOR consulting practice?","opts":["They satisfy HUD's requirement for consultant credentialing","They provide authentic evidence of real outcomes from a population (affordable housing managers) who are highly skeptical of unproven vendors","They are tax-deductible marketing expenses","They replace the need for engagement letters"],"ans":1,"exp":"Affordable housing managers are skeptical buyers. Testimonials from peer professionals who achieved real MOR outcomes are the most credible validation of your consulting value."}]}};
export const MOR_UNIT_TESTS = {"u7":{"title":"Unit 7: Understanding the MOR Process","passingScore":70,"questions":[{"q":"What is the primary purpose of a HUD Management and Occupancy Review?","opts":["Physical inspection of unit conditions","Assessment of management practices, documentation, and HUD regulatory compliance","Annual financial audit of the property","Verification of HAP contract terms"],"ans":1,"exp":"The MOR assesses management practices, policies, documentation, and compliance — not physical conditions."},{"q":"HUD Form 9834 serves as:","opts":["The certification form for each tenant","The official scoresheet and instrument used in every MOR","The HAP billing voucher","The income verification consent form"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD Form 9834 is the official MOR instrument. Every item a reviewer evaluates maps to a line on this form."},{"q":"HOTMA occupancy requirements became fully effective:","opts":["January 1, 2020","January 1, 2023","January 1, 2025","January 1, 2026"],"ans":2,"exp":"HOTMA's implementing regulations for Section 8 multifamily occupancy became fully effective January 1, 2025."},{"q":"A property with a Below Average rating typically receives MOR reviews:","opts":["Every five years","Every two to three years","Annually until performance improves","Only upon tenant complaint"],"ans":2,"exp":"Below Average and Unsatisfactory properties receive annual MORs until their performance improves."},{"q":"EIV use is mandatory under which CFR citation?","opts":["24 CFR 5.501","24 CFR 5.233","24 CFR 200.15","24 CFR 5.801"],"ans":1,"exp":"24 CFR 5.233 mandates EIV use for all covered HUD multifamily housing programs."},{"q":"Which entity may conduct a MOR in addition to HUD staff?","opts":["The state housing finance agency","A Performance Based Contract Administrator (PBCA)","The property's management agent","The independent auditor"],"ans":1,"exp":"PBCAs are contracted by HUD to administer Section 8 programs in a region, which includes conducting MORs."},{"q":"The five MOR rating levels from highest to lowest are:","opts":["Outstanding, Good, Average, Poor, Failing","Superior, Above Average, Satisfactory, Below Average, Unsatisfactory","Excellent, Above Standard, Standard, Below Standard, Deficient","Compliant, Mostly Compliant, Partially Compliant, Non-Compliant, Critical"],"ans":1,"exp":"The five official MOR rating levels are: Superior, Above Average, Satisfactory, Below Average, and Unsatisfactory."},{"q":"What is the standard tenant file sample percentage during a MOR on-site visit?","opts":["5%","10%","20%","50%"],"ans":2,"exp":"HUD typically reviews 20% of occupied units during the on-site visit, with a minimum of 10 files."},{"q":"The exit conference at the end of an on-site MOR allows:","opts":["Tenants to raise concerns about management","The reviewer to share preliminary findings and the property to provide clarifying documentation","The owner to appeal the preliminary rating","HUD to officially deliver the final MOR rating"],"ans":1,"exp":"The exit conference is when the reviewer shares preliminary observations and the management team can provide additional documentation or context."},{"q":"A Corrective Action Plan must typically be submitted to HUD within how many days of receiving the MOR report?","opts":["7 days","14 days","30 days","90 days"],"ans":2,"exp":"The CAP must be submitted within 30 days of receiving the MOR report."},{"q":"Since January 1, 2024, MORs must be conducted:","opts":["Virtually to reduce travel costs","On-site — remote reviews are no longer permitted","As either virtual or on-site at the reviewer's discretion","Using a hybrid approach approved by HUD"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD ended the pandemic-era remote MOR exception effective January 1, 2024. All MORs must now be conducted on-site."},{"q":"When reviewing prior MOR reports as a consultant, what is the highest-priority information?","opts":["The exact date and reviewer name","Recurring findings across multiple MOR cycles","The number of tenant files in the sample","The specific HAP voucher amounts reviewed"],"ans":1,"exp":"Recurring findings are the most statistically likely current deficiencies — they represent unresolved systemic issues."},{"q":"Which of the following can trigger an unscheduled MOR outside the normal review cycle?","opts":["A recent lease renewal for a long-term tenant","A fair housing complaint filed with HUD's FHEO","A REAC score above 80","A management fee increase"],"ans":1,"exp":"Fair housing complaints, tenant complaints, audit findings, and EIV noncompliance flags can trigger out-of-cycle MORs."},{"q":"A Performance Improvement Plan (PIP) is most likely issued when:","opts":["A property receives its first Satisfactory rating","A property has two or more consecutive Below Average or Unsatisfactory ratings","A property has a first-time Below Average finding","A property changes management agents"],"ans":1,"exp":"PIPs are formal HUD-owner agreements typically triggered by persistent poor ratings (multiple Below Average or Unsatisfactory results)."},{"q":"A staff member says 'I don't know, but I'll find out' during a MOR interview. This is:","opts":["A finding indicating inadequate staff training","Far preferable to guessing incorrectly — reviewers appreciate honest professional responses","Evidence that the property needs immediate remediation","Acceptable only for questions about physical inspections"],"ans":1,"exp":"'I don't know but I'll find out' is the right response when genuinely unsure. Incorrect guesses create additional scrutiny."},{"q":"What is the primary driver of the 'pattern vs. isolated deficiency' distinction in MOR reviews?","opts":["Whether the deficiency involves financial mismanagement","Whether the deficiency indicates systemic failure likely to recur, rather than a single error","Whether the finding involves a protected class","The dollar amount associated with the deficiency"],"ans":1,"exp":"Patterns suggest systemic failure. A pattern of deficiencies is treated more severely because it indicates the problem will continue without structural correction."},{"q":"The HAP contract gives HUD the right to conduct MORs. What happens if an owner refuses to permit the review?","opts":["HUD must obtain a court order before proceeding","The owner may be found in breach of the HAP contract","HUD can conduct the review without the owner's presence","There is no enforcement mechanism"],"ans":1,"exp":"Refusing to permit a MOR constitutes breach of the HAP contract — a serious compliance and enforcement issue."},{"q":"Which handbook is the primary occupancy reference for MOR compliance?","opts":["HUD Handbook 4350.1","HUD Handbook 4350.3 REV-1 Change-4","HUD Handbook 7420.8","HUD Handbook 4381.5"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD Handbook 4350.3 REV-1 Change-4 is the primary occupancy handbook governing tenant eligibility, certifications, rent calculation, and most MOR compliance topics."},{"q":"A property's MOR rating trajectory from Unsatisfactory (Year 1) to Satisfactory (Year 3) is viewed by HUD as:","opts":["Irrelevant — only the most recent rating matters","Favorably — it demonstrates genuine improvement over time","Negatively — any prior Unsatisfactory rating creates permanent scrutiny","Neutral until three consecutive Satisfactory ratings are achieved"],"ans":1,"exp":"A positive trajectory demonstrates genuine improvement and is viewed favorably by HUD. The trajectory matters, not just the most recent rating."},{"q":"Which MOR finding type carries the most automatic weight in reducing a property's overall rating?","opts":["Missing property insurance documentation","An expired AFHMP","A critical deficiency on Form 9834","A late TRACS transmission for one certification"],"ans":2,"exp":"Critical deficiencies on Form 9834 are specifically weighted to significantly reduce the overall rating — sometimes by themselves pulling the rating below Satisfactory."}]},"u8":{"title":"Unit 8: Desk Review Preparation","passingScore":70,"questions":[{"q":"The desk review package is typically due to the reviewer:","opts":["On the day of the on-site visit","One to two weeks before the on-site visit","When the MOR notice is received","Immediately after the exit conference"],"ans":1,"exp":"The desk review package is submitted one to two weeks before the on-site visit for the reviewer to analyze in advance."},{"q":"The rent roll is described as a foundational desk review document because:","opts":["It satisfies the EIV reporting requirement","It must reconcile with the HAP billing voucher, tenant certifications, and financial statements","It contains all tenant personal information in one place","It documents the property's gross income for tax purposes"],"ans":1,"exp":"The rent roll is cross-referenced against certifications, HAP billing, and financial statements — any discrepancy reveals a compliance issue."},{"q":"Audited financial statements for a December 31 fiscal year-end are due to HUD by:","opts":["March 31","June 30","September 30","December 31"],"ans":2,"exp":"Audits are due within 9 months of fiscal year-end. For December 31, that is September 30."},{"q":"The AFHMP must be updated at minimum every:","opts":["Year","Two years","Five years","Ten years"],"ans":2,"exp":"The AFHMP must be updated every five years or when there is a material change in marketing strategy. An expired AFHMP is a finding."},{"q":"Any RFR withdrawal requires:","opts":["Tenant notification","Owner's board approval","Prior HUD approval with supporting documentation","Management agent written authorization"],"ans":2,"exp":"All RFR withdrawals require prior HUD approval. Unapproved withdrawals are serious MOR findings."},{"q":"The EIV master binder must contain all of the following EXCEPT:","opts":["Signed EIV Participation Agreement","Documentation of required reports run at required intervals","All tenant income tax returns for the past three years","User training completion certificates"],"ans":2,"exp":"Tenant income tax returns are not EIV master binder documents. The binder contains participation agreements, user certifications, report run documentation, and discrepancy resolution."},{"q":"Using outdated VAWA forms (pre-2022 versions) in a 2025 MOR is:","opts":["Acceptable since VAWA forms rarely change","An immediate finding — current VAWA 2022 forms must be in use","Acceptable if the property notifies HUD in advance","Only a finding if a VAWA situation has actually occurred at the property"],"ans":1,"exp":"Using outdated VAWA forms is an immediate MOR finding. Properties must use current HUD Forms 5380 and 5382 reflecting VAWA 2022 requirements."},{"q":"A 'continuous desk review readiness posture' is best maintained through:","opts":["Scrambling to prepare files immediately upon receiving MOR notice","A monthly compliance calendar tracking EIV reports, certification dates, RFR deposits, and policy review intervals","Hiring additional staff only during MOR prep season","Outsourcing all compliance work to a third party"],"ans":1,"exp":"Continuous readiness requires ongoing monitoring through a compliance calendar — not reactive preparation only when a MOR is announced."},{"q":"A Certification Due List showing past-due certifications in the desk review package:","opts":["Is informational only and does not affect the MOR outcome","Immediately identifies a finding that the reviewer will investigate further","Is acceptable if no more than 10% of certifications are overdue","Only matters if the overdue certifications affect HAP amounts"],"ans":1,"exp":"Any overdue certifications identified in the Certification Due List are immediate findings — there is no acceptable threshold."},{"q":"Performing a pre-submission quality review of the desk review package by someone other than the assembler serves to:","opts":["Satisfy HUD's two-person review requirement","Catch items the original assembler missed due to familiarity with the files","Reduce the consultant's liability for the submission","Provide a second signature required by HUD on the cover letter"],"ans":1,"exp":"A second reviewer catches errors the assembler misses due to familiarity. This simple QC step reduces the risk of submitting an incomplete or inaccurate package."},{"q":"A Tenant Selection Plan that has not been updated to reflect HOTMA (effective January 1, 2025) is:","opts":["Acceptable during the HOTMA phase-in period","Non-compliant — TSPs were required to be updated by January 1, 2025","Acceptable if the owner is actively working on the update","Only a concern if the TSP is more than 10 years old"],"ans":1,"exp":"The window for HOTMA compliance phasing has closed. A pre-2025 TSP that hasn't been updated against HOTMA requirements is non-compliant today."},{"q":"The Multiple Subsidy Report is designed to identify:","opts":["Tenants whose income has changed significantly","Tenants potentially receiving housing assistance at multiple HUD properties simultaneously","Units that have been vacant for more than 30 days","Properties with duplicate HAP billing entries"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Multiple Subsidy Report identifies tenants who may be receiving housing assistance at more than one HUD-assisted location."},{"q":"When submitting an electronic desk review package, the recommended format is:","opts":["Word documents (.docx) for easy editing","Excel spreadsheets for data-heavy documents","PDFs with a consistent naming convention and clear folder structure","HTML files for online sharing"],"ans":2,"exp":"PDF format with consistent naming and organized folder structure is standard for electronic desk review submissions."},{"q":"Which of the following most strongly indicates that a management agent has a continuous readiness posture?","opts":["They are frantically preparing files after receiving the MOR notice","They submit a well-organized, complete desk review package within one week of the notice","They have a long list of pending corrections to make before the on-site visit","They hire a consultant only after receiving the MOR notice"],"ans":1,"exp":"A complete package submitted quickly after notice indicates that documents were already organized and current — the hallmark of a continuous readiness posture."},{"q":"The EIV Existing Tenant Search must be run within how many days before a tenant's move-in?","opts":["30 days","60 days","90 days","120 days"],"ans":3,"exp":"The Existing Tenant Search must be run within 120 days before move-in and evidence of the search must be in the tenant file."},{"q":"What does a qualified audit opinion signal to a MOR reviewer?","opts":["The auditor specializes in affordable housing","A potential problem with the accuracy or completeness of the financial statements","The audit was completed faster than usual","An enhanced level of audit scrutiny has been applied"],"ans":1,"exp":"A qualified audit opinion signals that the auditor could not confirm the accuracy of certain aspects of the financial statements — a significant red flag."},{"q":"A cover letter in the desk review package should address known compliance issues by:","opts":["Omitting them — only include documents that demonstrate compliance","Proactively disclosing them with accompanying corrective action documentation","Asking the reviewer to not include them in the MOR findings","Attributing them to the prior management agent"],"ans":1,"exp":"Proactive disclosure with corrective action documentation is viewed far more favorably than attempting to conceal known problems."},{"q":"The RFR account minimum monthly deposit is specified in:","opts":["The HAP contract","The property management agreement","The Regulatory Agreement","The annual operating budget"],"ans":2,"exp":"The minimum monthly RFR deposit amount is specified in the HUD Regulatory Agreement. It must be deposited every month without exception."},{"q":"An MOR Readiness Assessment consultant product is best targeted at:","opts":["Properties that just failed a MOR","Any HUD-assisted property as a proactive investment to maintain compliance and identify gaps before they become findings","Only properties receiving annual monitoring MORs","Only properties with more than 100 units"],"ans":1,"exp":"The MOR Readiness Assessment is appropriate for any HUD-assisted property as a proactive investment — not just those in crisis."},{"q":"Which of the following desk review deficiencies most directly creates a financial risk for the property owner?","opts":["An expired management contract","Past-due certifications that cause incorrect HAP billing","An outdated utility allowance schedule","Missing property insurance documentation"],"ans":1,"exp":"Past-due certifications often result in incorrect HAP billing — either overpayments that must be repaid or underpayments. The financial risk can extend back multiple years."}]},"u9":{"title":"Unit 9: Tenant Files & Certifications","passingScore":70,"questions":[{"q":"Which document must be in a tenant's initial application package to verify consent for HUD to access third-party income data?","opts":["HUD Form 50059","HUD Forms 9887 and 9887-A","The Existing Tenant Search printout","The EIV Income Report"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD Forms 9887 and 9887-A are the consent forms authorizing HUD and the owner to verify income from third-party sources."},{"q":"The annual recertification process must begin no later than how many days before the anniversary date?","opts":["30 days","60 days","90 days","120 days"],"ans":3,"exp":"Annual recertifications must begin at least 120 days before the anniversary date to allow time for income verification and processing."},{"q":"Under TRACS requirements, a certification must be transmitted within how many days of the effective date?","opts":["30 days","45 days","60 days","90 days"],"ans":2,"exp":"TRACS requires certifications to be transmitted within 60 days of the effective date. Late transmissions are MOR findings."},{"q":"A live-in aide's income is treated as:","opts":["Annual income subject to rent calculation","An excluded income source — live-in aide income is never counted","An asset if the aide is paid above minimum wage","A deduction from the household's adjusted income"],"ans":1,"exp":"A live-in aide's income is completely excluded from the household's annual income — only the tenant's household income counts."},{"q":"For a mixed-status family (some members with eligible immigration status, some without), HUD assistance is:","opts":["Denied to the entire household","Prorated based on the number of eligible members","Provided in full if the head of household is eligible","Suspended until all members achieve eligible status"],"ans":1,"exp":"Mixed-status families receive prorated assistance based on the ratio of eligible to total household members under 24 CFR Part 5."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, effective January 1, 2025, households where all adult members have fixed income may be eligible for:","opts":["Monthly recertification","Annual recertification only","Biennial (every two years) recertification","No recertification requirement"],"ans":2,"exp":"HOTMA created an optional biennial recertification cycle for fixed-income households, reducing administrative burden."},{"q":"The income verification hierarchy under HUD Handbook 4350.3 places which source at the top (most reliable)?","opts":["Tenant-provided documents","Third-party written verification","Upfront Income Verification (UIV) from databases","EIV income data"],"ans":3,"exp":"EIV data (Tier 1) is the most reliable source. The hierarchy is: EIV → UIV databases → third-party written → tenant-provided."},{"q":"An interim certification is required when:","opts":["A tenant's lease automatically renews","A tenant reports a decrease in income or an increase in family size that affects rent","The annual recertification is 30 days late","A management agent changes"],"ans":1,"exp":"Interims are required for changes that affect the tenant's rent — primarily income decreases and family composition changes."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, a lump-sum addition to income (such as an insurance settlement) is treated as:","opts":["Annual income spread over 12 months","An asset, not annual income","Excluded income","A one-time deduction"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA changed the treatment of lump-sum additions — they are now counted as assets, not spread as annual income."},{"q":"The minimum rent under Section 8 is currently:","opts":["$0","$25","$50","$75"],"ans":2,"exp":"The HUD minimum rent is $50. Tenants may request a hardship exemption, but it must be formally reviewed and documented."},{"q":"A student who is a part-time student enrolled in a degree program and not claimed as a dependent:","opts":["Is always eligible for Section 8 assistance","Must meet one of the specific student eligibility exceptions under 24 CFR 5.612","Is automatically eligible if under age 24","Has no special eligibility requirements"],"ans":1,"exp":"Students have specific eligibility rules under 24 CFR 5.612. Not all students are eligible — management must verify which exception applies."},{"q":"A tenant requests a unit transfer due to a disability-related need. This request is most properly handled as:","opts":["A standard transfer request processed in waiting list order","A reasonable accommodation request under Fair Housing and Section 504","An informal hearing matter","An emergency transfer under VAWA"],"ans":1,"exp":"A disability-related transfer request is a reasonable accommodation request and must be evaluated through the interactive accommodation process."},{"q":"Retention of tenant files after move-out is required for a minimum of:","opts":["One year","Three years","Six years","Ten years"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD requires tenant files to be retained for a minimum of three years after move-out (or longer if required by state law)."},{"q":"For purposes of the $480 dependent deduction, a 'dependent' is defined as:","opts":["Any person in the household who earns less than $480 per year","A household member who is not the head, spouse, or co-head, and is under 18, disabled, or a full-time student","Any household member under age 26","Any household member not working full-time"],"ans":1,"exp":"The $480 dependent deduction applies to household members who are not the head/spouse/co-head and are under 18, disabled, or full-time students."},{"q":"A tenant who fails to complete the annual recertification process despite proper notices may be:","opts":["Given an indefinite extension","Subject to lease termination for non-compliance","Automatically recertified at the prior year's income","Transferred to a smaller unit"],"ans":1,"exp":"Failure to complete recertification after documented proper notice is grounds for lease termination for non-compliance."},{"q":"The $50,000 HOTMA asset self-certification threshold applies to:","opts":["Assets above $50,000 — owners must verify; below is self-certification","Assets below $50,000 — tenants can self-certify; above requires third-party verification","All assets regardless of value","Only retirement accounts"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA allows tenants with net assets at or below $50,000 to self-certify. Assets above $50,000 require third-party verification."},{"q":"A citizenship declaration (HUD Form I-9 equivalent) must be signed by:","opts":["Only the head of household","Each household member age 18 and older","Each household member age 6 and older","Only employed household members"],"ans":2,"exp":"Each household member 6 years and older must sign a citizenship/eligible immigration status declaration."},{"q":"When a tenant requests a hardship exemption from the minimum rent, the owner must:","opts":["Deny it — minimum rent has no exceptions","Process the request and may suspend the minimum rent during the 90-day review period","Charge the minimum rent while the request is being reviewed","Refer the tenant to a social services agency"],"ans":1,"exp":"When a hardship exemption is requested, the minimum rent may be suspended during the 90-day review period while the owner evaluates the hardship claim."},{"q":"The Existing Tenant Search in EIV is used to:","opts":["Verify income of existing tenants","Check whether an applicant is already receiving HUD assistance at another property","Generate the income discrepancy report","Confirm employment for all household members"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Existing Tenant Search must be run before move-in to identify applicants who may already be receiving HUD assistance elsewhere."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, self-employment income calculation was changed to:","opts":["Include both gross receipts and documented business expenses as income","Disallow depreciation as a deduction from self-employment income","Require quarterly income reports for self-employed tenants","Treat all self-employment income as an asset"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA specifically disallowed depreciation as a deductible business expense for self-employment income calculations."}]},"u10":{"title":"Unit 10: Income, Assets & EIV Compliance","passingScore":70,"questions":[{"q":"Annual income for Section 8 purposes is defined as:","opts":["Prior year actual income as reported on tax returns","Anticipated total income from all sources for the 12 months following certification","Current monthly income multiplied by 12","Income verified by the most recent pay stub times 26"],"ans":1,"exp":"Annual income is forward-looking — it is the anticipated total income from all household sources for the next 12 months."},{"q":"The $400 elderly/disabled household deduction from adjusted income applies when:","opts":["The head, spouse, or co-head is 62 or older or disabled","Any household member is 62 or older","The household qualifies for an accessible unit","The household receives Social Security income"],"ans":0,"exp":"The $400 deduction applies when the head, co-head, or spouse is 62 or older, or is a person with a disability."},{"q":"Total Tenant Payment (TTP) is the greater of:","opts":["30% of monthly adjusted income or 10% of monthly gross income or the minimum rent","30% of annual income or 10% of annual gross income","50% of monthly income or the contract rent","The minimum rent or 40% of monthly income"],"ans":0,"exp":"TTP is the greater of: 30% of monthly adjusted income, 10% of monthly gross income, or the minimum rent ($50)."},{"q":"The passbook savings rate (currently 0.06%) is applied when:","opts":["A tenant's checking account balance exceeds $500","Net family assets exceed $5,000 — imputed income from assets is calculated","All household members have savings accounts","The tenant refuses to disclose asset details"],"ans":1,"exp":"When net family assets exceed $5,000, imputed income is calculated using the greater of actual income from assets or the passbook rate applied to total asset value."},{"q":"A childcare deduction is available for:","opts":["Any household with children under 13","Childcare expenses that allow a household member to work, seek employment, or attend school, capped at the income earned"],"ans":1,"exp":"The childcare deduction allows reasonable expenses for care of children under 13 that enable a household member to work or attend school, not to exceed the income earned."},{"q":"EIV use is described as mandatory under which regulation?","opts":["HUD Handbook 4350.3 Chapter 9","24 CFR 5.233","24 CFR 200.15","HUD Notice H 2013-06"],"ans":1,"exp":"24 CFR 5.233 is the regulatory citation mandating EIV use for all HUD multifamily covered housing programs."},{"q":"The EIV Income Report should be run at minimum:","opts":["Monthly","At each annual recertification and when resolving discrepancies","Every 90 days","At move-in and move-out only"],"ans":1,"exp":"The EIV Income Report must be run at each annual recertification (and any time a discrepancy is being investigated)."},{"q":"An EIV income discrepancy must be resolved within:","opts":["30 days of discovery","60 days of discovery","90 days of discovery","The next annual recertification"],"ans":1,"exp":"EIV discrepancies must be resolved and documented within 60 days. Unresolved discrepancies are MOR findings."},{"q":"The EIV Failed Pre-Screening Report identifies tenants who:","opts":["Failed the credit check during application","Have income data that could not be matched in the Social Security or HHS databases","Are behind on rent payments","Have pending eviction proceedings"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Failed Pre-Screening Report lists tenants whose SSN or identity data failed to match federal databases — requiring follow-up."},{"q":"Periodic assets include all of the following EXCEPT:","opts":["Savings accounts","Checking accounts","Personal property held for personal use (clothing, furniture)","Money market accounts"],"ans":2,"exp":"Personal property held for personal use (furniture, clothing, vehicles for personal use) is not counted as an asset."},{"q":"A tenant disposed of an asset below fair market value within the past two years. The asset is:","opts":["Ignored since the tenant no longer owns it","Imputed at its fair market value less the amount received — the difference is included in assets","Only counted if the difference exceeds $1,000","Counted as annual income"],"ans":1,"exp":"Assets disposed of below FMV within two years are still counted — the imputed asset value is the FMV minus what was actually received."},{"q":"The medical expense deduction for elderly/disabled households:","opts":["Deducts all medical expenses dollar for dollar","Deducts the amount of unreimbursed medical expenses that exceeds 3% of annual income","Deducts $500 automatically for elderly households","Deducts Medicare premiums only"],"ans":1,"exp":"The medical expense deduction is the amount of unreimbursed medical expenses exceeding 3% of annual (gross) income, for elderly or disabled households."},{"q":"EIV access must be terminated for a user who:","opts":["Takes a two-week vacation","Leaves the organization or no longer needs access for job duties","Has not run a report in 45 days","Transfers to a different property in the portfolio"],"ans":1,"exp":"EIV access must be immediately terminated when a user leaves the organization or no longer needs access as part of their job duties."},{"q":"The Multiple Subsidy Report is designed to detect:","opts":["Income from multiple employers","Tenants receiving HUD housing assistance at more than one property","Tenants with assets at multiple financial institutions","Households with multiple members receiving Social Security"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Multiple Subsidy Report identifies tenants who may be receiving housing assistance at more than one HUD-assisted location simultaneously."},{"q":"For a tenant with income from tips, the correct annual income figure is:","opts":["Actual tips reported on last year's tax return","Anticipated tips for the next 12 months based on current rate or year-to-date average","Tips as reported to the employer on Form 4070","Only declared tips from the last pay stub"],"ans":1,"exp":"Annual income is always forward-looking — anticipated tips for the next 12 months, typically based on a current rate or YTD average."},{"q":"Social Security cost-of-living adjustments (COLAs) are:","opts":["Excluded from annual income","Included in annual income at the new post-COLA rate","Only counted if the COLA exceeds 5%","Counted only in the year they first take effect"],"ans":1,"exp":"Social Security COLAs are included — annual income reflects the tenant's anticipated income at the post-COLA rate going forward."},{"q":"Real property held by a tenant (other than their primary residence) is treated as:","opts":["Excluded income","An asset valued at fair market equity (FMV minus mortgage balance)","Annual income equal to any rental income received","An asset only if it generates income"],"ans":1,"exp":"Real property equity (FMV minus outstanding mortgage) is counted as an asset. HOTMA clarified that a primary residence is generally excluded."},{"q":"A tenant who refuses to sign the EIV consent form (HUD 9887/9887-A) must be:","opts":["Allowed to remain without income verification","Denied admission or terminated from the program","Given a 90-day grace period","Recertified using only tenant-provided documents"],"ans":1,"exp":"Signing the consent forms is a condition of tenancy. Refusal to sign is grounds for denial of admission or termination."},{"q":"Under HOTMA, the threshold below which tenants may self-certify assets is:","opts":["$1,000","$5,000","$25,000","$50,000"],"ans":3,"exp":"HOTMA established a $50,000 net asset self-certification threshold. Note: the $5,000 passbook imputation rule is a separate, still-applicable rule."},{"q":"An EIV Participation Agreement must be signed by:","opts":["Every tenant at move-in","Each EIV user and their supervisor, before EIV access is granted","The property owner only","HUD staff and the PBCA only"],"ans":1,"exp":"Each user who accesses EIV must sign a Participation Agreement before being granted access. This document is kept in the EIV master binder."}]},"u11":{"title":"Unit 11: Waiting List, TSP & Fair Housing","passingScore":70,"questions":[{"q":"Applications on the waiting list must be date and time stamped because:","opts":["HUD requires a specific format for digital records","Date/time is the tiebreaker when all preferences are equal","Federal law requires it for all public records","It is required by the AFHMP"],"ans":1,"exp":"Date and time of application is the tiebreaker when applicants have equal preference status — it ensures first-come, first-served fairness."},{"q":"Before closing a waiting list, an owner must:","opts":["Provide 10 days' written notice to HUD","Provide 30 days' public notice through the same channels used to open the list","Obtain a court order","Notify only current applicants on the list"],"ans":1,"exp":"A 30-day public notice is required before closing a waiting list, published through the same channels used to publicize the list's opening."},{"q":"The Affirmative Fair Housing Marketing Plan (AFHMP) must be updated at minimum every:","opts":["One year","Two years","Five years","Ten years"],"ans":2,"exp":"The AFHMP must be updated every five years (or when marketing strategies change materially)."},{"q":"Under the AFHMP, new admissions must target a specific percentage of units for extremely low-income households (at or below 30% AMI). That percentage is:","opts":["10%","20%","40%","50%"],"ans":2,"exp":"The AFHMP income targeting requirement is 40% of new admissions for households at or below 30% AMI."},{"q":"Skipping an applicant on the waiting list without proper documentation:","opts":["Is permissible if done consistently","Is an immediate fair housing concern and MOR finding","Is acceptable for applicants with criminal history","Is permitted for unit size mismatches"],"ans":1,"exp":"Undocumented skips are serious findings — they raise fair housing concerns and indicate an inconsistently administered waiting list."},{"q":"A Tenant Selection Plan must include all of the following EXCEPT:","opts":["Income targeting requirements","Criminal history screening criteria","Individualized assessment language for criminal history (HOTMA)","The management fee structure"],"ans":3,"exp":"The TSP covers screening criteria, preferences, income targeting, and admissions policies — not the internal management fee structure."},{"q":"HOTMA's requirement for individualized assessment of criminal history means:","opts":["All applicants with any criminal history must be denied","Each applicant's criminal history must be evaluated considering nature, time elapsed, circumstances, and evidence of rehabilitation","Properties may establish a blanket ban on any felony conviction","Only convictions within the past year are reviewable"],"ans":1,"exp":"HOTMA requires individualized assessment — blanket bans based on criminal history are no longer permissible."},{"q":"Under the Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA), applicants denied based on a consumer report must receive:","opts":["No specific notice — only a general denial letter","An adverse action notice with information about the reporting agency and right to dispute","A 30-day cure period to correct their credit","A copy of the full credit report at no charge"],"ans":1,"exp":"FCRA requires adverse action notice when a consumer report (credit, criminal background) contributes to a denial."},{"q":"An applicant who is denied admission has the right to request an informal hearing within:","opts":["7 days","14 days","30 days","60 days"],"ans":1,"exp":"Rejected applicants have the right to request an informal hearing within 14 days of the denial notice."},{"q":"The seven federal protected classes under the Fair Housing Act are:","opts":["Race, color, national origin, religion, sex, disability, and familial status","Race, color, religion, sex, age, disability, and national origin","Race, color, national origin, citizenship, sex, disability, and familial status","Race, color, religion, sex, national origin, genetic information, and age"],"ans":0,"exp":"The seven FHA protected classes are: race, color, national origin, religion, sex, disability, and familial status."},{"q":"Disparate impact (as opposed to disparate treatment) is best described as:","opts":["Intentional discrimination based on a protected class","A facially neutral policy that disproportionately harms a protected class","Direct refusal to rent to a protected class","Intimidation of a protected class member"],"ans":1,"exp":"Disparate impact occurs when a neutral policy produces a discriminatory effect, even without discriminatory intent."},{"q":"Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act requires properties with 5% mobility-accessible and 2% sensory-accessible units only when:","opts":["The property has more than 10 units","Federal financial assistance is received (all Section 8 properties)","The property was constructed after 1991","The property has a specific number of disabled tenants"],"ans":1,"exp":"Section 504 applies to all federally assisted housing. The 5%/2% accessible unit requirement applies to properties receiving HUD financial assistance."},{"q":"A reasonable accommodation request must be granted unless:","opts":["The tenant cannot demonstrate the disability connection","It would fundamentally alter the program or impose an undue financial/administrative burden","The request is not in writing","It involves a physical modification to the unit"],"ans":1,"exp":"Reasonable accommodations must be granted unless they fundamentally alter the program or impose an undue hardship (financial or administrative burden)."},{"q":"Properties with 15 or more employees must designate a:","opts":["Fair Housing Officer","Section 504 Coordinator","ADA Compliance Manager","Civil Rights Director"],"ans":1,"exp":"Section 504 requires properties with 15 or more employees to designate a Section 504 Coordinator responsible for compliance and complaint handling."},{"q":"Waiting list purges must be conducted:","opts":["Annually, without prior notice to applicants","With prior written notice and a reasonable response period for applicants to confirm continued interest","Only when a waiting list is being closed","At management's discretion"],"ans":1,"exp":"Purges require advance written notice to applicants giving them a reasonable time to confirm their continued interest before being removed."},{"q":"A prospective tenant requests that the TSP be provided in large print due to a visual impairment. This is:","opts":["Unreasonable since the TSP is publicly posted","A reasonable accommodation request that must be honored","Optional at the management agent's discretion","A reasonable modification request"],"ans":0,"exp":"Providing the TSP in large print is a reasonable accommodation (change in policy/communication) that must be honored."},{"q":"Under the AFHMP, a property's marketing must reach housing choice populations by:","opts":["Advertising only on the property's website","Utilizing outreach methods specifically designed to reach groups underrepresented in the property's tenant population","Posting a notice in the local newspaper only","Mailing notices to all households within a 1-mile radius"],"ans":1,"exp":"The AFHMP requires affirmative outreach targeting groups least likely to apply — the marketing strategy must go beyond passive advertising."},{"q":"A management agent has a written policy rejecting all applicants with any rental history eviction within the past 10 years. Under HOTMA, this policy:","opts":["Is fully permissible as part of the TSP","Requires individualized assessment — blanket bans may have a discriminatory impact","Must be approved by HUD annually","Is permissible only for properties with more than 50 units"],"ans":1,"exp":"Blanket rental history bars must be evaluated for disparate impact and may require individualized assessment under HOTMA and fair housing principles."},{"q":"A staff member makes an off-hand comment to an applicant of a protected class that 'this neighborhood might not be for you.' This is best classified as:","opts":["Disparate impact","Steering","Redlining","Blockbusting"],"ans":1,"exp":"Steering is directing applicants toward or away from specific properties or units based on protected class characteristics."},{"q":"The interactive process in reasonable accommodation means:","opts":["The tenant must fill out an interactive form","The owner and tenant engage in good-faith dialogue to determine if and how an accommodation can be provided","The owner has 30 days to make a final decision","An accommodation is automatically granted once requested in writing"],"ans":1,"exp":"The interactive process is a good-faith dialogue between the owner and tenant to clarify the need and identify workable accommodation solutions."}]},"u12":{"title":"Unit 12: VAWA, Leases & Financial Management","passingScore":70,"questions":[{"q":"VAWA 2022 extended protections to cover which additional groups compared to prior versions?","opts":["Elderly tenants and veterans","LGBTQ+ individuals, including victims of sexual orientation-based violence","Undocumented immigrants","All tenants regardless of cause of lease violation"],"ans":1,"exp":"VAWA 2022 expanded protections to LGBTQ+ individuals and victims of violence motivated by sex stereotyping, sexual orientation, and gender identity."},{"q":"HUD Form 5380 (Notice of Occupancy Rights) must be provided to all tenants:","opts":["Only when a VAWA incident is reported","At application, lease signing/renewal, receipt of a notice to vacate, and within 14 days of any request","Annually at recertification","Only if the tenant requests it"],"ans":1,"exp":"Form 5380 must be provided at application, lease signing or renewal, notice to vacate, and within 14 days of any written request — not just when VAWA incidents occur."},{"q":"A tenant has 14 business days to complete HUD Form 5382 (VAWA Certification) after requesting VAWA protections. If they need more time:","opts":["The request is automatically denied","The owner may grant additional time at their discretion — extension is common practice","No extension is permitted under any circumstances","The tenant must file with HUD directly"],"ans":1,"exp":"While the deadline is 14 business days, owners regularly grant extensions. VAWA protections exist to help victims, not create barriers."},{"q":"The VAWA perpetrator exception allows:","opts":["Termination of all household members when a VAWA incident is reported","Termination of the perpetrator's tenancy while allowing the victim to remain","Immediate eviction of both the victim and perpetrator","No eviction in VAWA situations"],"ans":1,"exp":"Lease bifurcation allows the owner to remove the perpetrator and let the victim remain — an important protection that prevents victims from losing housing."},{"q":"An Emergency Transfer Plan under VAWA must use which HUD form?","opts":["HUD Form 5380","HUD Form 5381","HUD Form 5382","HUD Form 9887"],"ans":1,"exp":"HUD Form 5381 is the Emergency Transfer Plan form. Properties must have this plan in place and provide it to tenants upon request."},{"q":"For a VAWA emergency transfer, the victim's new unit location is:","opts":["Posted on the property's public bulletin board","Kept strictly confidential to protect the victim's safety","Shared with the local housing authority","Disclosed to the perpetrator if they request it"],"ans":1,"exp":"VAWA emergency transfer locations are strictly confidential. Disclosure could put the victim in danger."},{"q":"The HUD model lease for Section 8 is required to include all of the following EXCEPT:","opts":["The HAP amount","Grounds for lease termination","The owner's personal financial information","Tenant grievance procedures"],"ans":2,"exp":"The lease must include HAP amounts, termination grounds, and grievance procedures — but not the owner's personal financial details."},{"q":"Before an owner can evict a tenant, the owner must first:","opts":["File directly with the court","Complete the tenant grievance procedure and provide 30 days' written notice of termination","Obtain HUD approval for the eviction","Suspend the HAP payment"],"ans":1,"exp":"The lease termination process requires a 30-day written notice, completion of the grievance procedure, and only then can eviction proceedings be initiated."},{"q":"House rules (pet policies, parking rules, guest policies) become part of the lease only when:","opts":["They are posted in the lobby","They are approved by HUD and incorporated as a lease addendum","They are verbally communicated at move-in","They are posted on the property website"],"ans":1,"exp":"House rules must be HUD-approved and incorporated as a lease addendum to be enforceable."},{"q":"Audited financial statements must be submitted through which HUD system?","opts":["TRACS","REAC FASS (Financial Assessment Subsystem)","HUD APPS","iREMS"],"ans":1,"exp":"Audited financial statements for HUD-assisted properties are submitted through REAC's Financial Assessment Subsystem (FASS)."},{"q":"A Single Audit (formerly A-133 audit) is required when:","opts":["The property has more than 100 units","The property expends $750,000 or more in federal financial assistance in a year","The property has been cited in a prior MOR","The management agent has more than 10 properties"],"ans":1,"exp":"The Single Audit threshold is $750,000 in federal financial assistance expended in a year — applicable to many larger HUD-assisted properties."},{"q":"Surplus cash distributions from a HUD-assisted property require:","opts":["No special approval","Prior HUD approval based on the annual audit","Owner board vote only","TRACS confirmation"],"ans":1,"exp":"Distributions of surplus cash from HUD-assisted properties require prior HUD approval and are based on the annual audited financial statements."},{"q":"Reserve for Replacement monthly deposits are:","opts":["Optional and based on the owner's discretion","Mandatory as specified in the Regulatory Agreement — no exceptions","Required only during capital improvement years","Determined annually by the management agent"],"ans":1,"exp":"RFR monthly deposits are mandatory as specified in the Regulatory Agreement. Missing deposits are a serious MOR finding."},{"q":"Identity of Interest (IOI) disclosures are required when:","opts":["The management agent is an LLC","There is a financial relationship between the owner and management agent, vendors, or other contractors","The property refinances its mortgage","A new HAP contract is executed"],"ans":1,"exp":"IOI disclosures are required when the owner has financial relationships with the management agent or vendors — this prevents undisclosed related-party transactions."},{"q":"Under the False Claims Act, submitting incorrect HAP vouchers to HUD can result in:","opts":["Only repayment of the overage","Civil penalties of up to three times the overpayment amount plus additional per-claim penalties","No liability if the error was unintentional","Only a finding on the next MOR"],"ans":1,"exp":"The False Claims Act imposes treble damages and per-claim penalties for fraudulent submissions to the federal government — HAP overbilling qualifies."},{"q":"Utility reimbursements (UAP payments) are required when:","opts":["Tenants pay utilities directly and the utility allowance exceeds the TTP","The property's utility costs increase by more than 10%","All tenants in the property pay their own utilities","A tenant's income is below 30% AMI"],"ans":0,"exp":"Utility Allowance Payments (UAPs) are required when the utility allowance exceeds the TTP — the tenant receives the difference as a monthly reimbursement."},{"q":"The Capital Needs Assessment (CNA) is related to the RFR because:","opts":["CNAs replace the need for monthly RFR deposits","CNAs project future capital expenditures, informing whether RFR balances are adequate to fund upcoming needs","CNAs are filed with TRACS","CNAs determine the HAP contract amount"],"ans":1,"exp":"The CNA projects future capital needs over a 20-year horizon — RFR balances and deposit rates are evaluated against these projected needs."},{"q":"HAP billing reconciliation (comparing TRACS vouchers to HAP payment receipts) should be performed:","opts":["Annually at audit time","Monthly, to catch discrepancies before they accumulate","Only when a discrepancy is noticed","Quarterly"],"ans":1,"exp":"Monthly reconciliation of HAP billing against payment receipts is best practice — it catches errors early before they result in large overpayments or underpayments."},{"q":"A tenant has been absent from the unit for 60 days without notifying management. This may constitute:","opts":["An unauthorized sublease","Abandonment — a lease termination ground subject to the proper notice and grievance process","An emergency requiring welfare check only","No lease violation unless rent is also unpaid"],"ans":1,"exp":"Extended unauthorized absence can constitute abandonment — but management must still follow proper notice and grievance procedures before terminating."},{"q":"VAWA training for property staff should cover all of the following EXCEPT:","opts":["How to provide Form 5380 and when","Emergency transfer procedures and confidentiality","How to determine whether a victim is telling the truth","Documentation requirements for VAWA situations"],"ans":2,"exp":"Staff should never be trained to judge whether a victim is being truthful — VAWA protections are based on self-certification, not credibility evaluation."}]},"u13":{"title":"Unit 13: Building Your MOR Consulting Business","passingScore":70,"questions":[{"q":"The recommended pricing range for a comprehensive MOR Prep Package (full consulting engagement) is approximately:","opts":["$500–$1,000","$1,500–$3,000","$5,000–$12,000","$20,000–$50,000"],"ans":2,"exp":"A comprehensive MOR Prep Package — covering file review, staff training, and mock MOR — is typically priced at $5,000–$12,000 depending on property size and complexity."},{"q":"Errors & Omissions (E&O) insurance is essential for an MOR consultant because:","opts":["HUD requires all consultants to carry it","It protects the consultant if a client claims the consultant's advice contributed to a poor MOR outcome","It replaces the need for a written engagement letter","It covers physical damage to client files"],"ans":1,"exp":"E&O insurance protects the consultant from liability if a client claims the consultant's guidance was incorrect or incomplete and contributed to a compliance failure."},{"q":"The single most valuable document to obtain before beginning a client engagement is:","opts":["The current rent roll","The prior MOR report","The management agreement","The last annual audit"],"ans":1,"exp":"The prior MOR report reveals what findings were cited before — recurring findings are the most likely current deficiencies and set the engagement's priorities."},{"q":"In a mock MOR exit conference, the consultant's role is to:","opts":["Provide a perfect score to motivate the team","Deliver findings exactly as a real reviewer would — including severity ratings and preliminary CAP requirements","Summarize the property's best practices only","Coach staff on what to say to the actual reviewer"],"ans":1,"exp":"The mock exit conference must mirror a real one — candid findings, severity assessments, and a preliminary CAP. This prepares the team for the real experience."},{"q":"A Green/Yellow/Red file rating system during the file review phase serves to:","opts":["Color-code files for the reviewer's convenience","Quickly triage which files need immediate remediation (Red), which need attention (Yellow), and which are MOR-ready (Green)","Indicate income tiers for HAP billing purposes","Categorize files by move-in year"],"ans":1,"exp":"The traffic light system efficiently prioritizes limited prep time — Red files need immediate attention, Yellow need review, Green are ready."},{"q":"The optimal timing for a mock MOR is:","opts":["The day before the scheduled review","4–6 weeks before the actual MOR","Immediately after receiving the MOR notice","Six months before the expected MOR date"],"ans":1,"exp":"4–6 weeks allows time to find and fix issues identified in the mock review before the actual reviewer arrives."},{"q":"A retainer-based consulting model benefits a consultant primarily because:","opts":["Clients prefer monthly billing","It provides predictable recurring revenue and deepens the client relationship","It reduces the consultant's liability","It eliminates the need for E&O insurance"],"ans":1,"exp":"Retainers provide predictable monthly income and create ongoing relationships that are more profitable and stable than one-time engagements."},{"q":"The most effective business development strategy for a new MOR consultant is:","opts":["Cold calling HUD offices","Leveraging existing relationships from prior property management or compliance work","Advertising on social media only","Bidding on government contracts immediately"],"ans":1,"exp":"Warm relationships from prior compliance work are far more effective than cold outreach — people hire consultants they already know and trust."},{"q":"NAHMA and NLHA are valuable networking organizations because:","opts":["They provide HUD certifications","They connect consultants with affordable housing owners and management agents who are MOR clients","They administer the MOR process","They offer HUD-approved CAP templates"],"ans":1,"exp":"NAHMA (National Affordable Housing Management Association) and NLHA (National Leased Housing Association) are key industry groups where MOR clients congregate."},{"q":"During the pre-engagement discovery call, the most important questions to ask a prospective client are:","opts":["What is your budget and timeline?","When was your last MOR, what rating did you receive, and do you have a copy of the report?","How many units do you have and what is your occupancy rate?","What is your current management fee structure?"],"ans":1,"exp":"The prior MOR date, rating, and report are the highest-priority discovery information — they set the scope, urgency, and focus of the entire engagement."},{"q":"CAP consulting is described as a high-value niche because:","opts":["It is easier work than MOR prep","Properties that received poor ratings are highly motivated to improve and often willing to pay premium fees for a proven roadmap","HUD requires all CAPs to be prepared by outside consultants","CAP work has no liability exposure"],"ans":1,"exp":"Properties with poor ratings face real enforcement risk — they are motivated clients willing to invest in expert CAP guidance."},{"q":"Thought leadership content (articles, webinars, case studies) builds a consulting practice by:","opts":["Directly generating HUD referrals","Demonstrating expertise to potential clients and keeping the consultant top-of-mind when compliance needs arise","Replacing the need for networking","Satisfying CPE requirements for certifications"],"ans":1,"exp":"Thought leadership builds credibility and visibility — potential clients who read your work already trust your expertise before the first conversation."},{"q":"To scale a consulting practice beyond sole practitioner capacity, the most practical first step is:","opts":["Immediately hiring full-time employees","Training and certifying associates who can handle file reviews under the principal consultant's supervision","Acquiring a property management company","Obtaining a HUD contract"],"ans":1,"exp":"Associates allow capacity to expand without the cost and complexity of full-time employees — they handle the volume work while the principal maintains quality control."},{"q":"An engagement letter protects the consultant by:","opts":["Replacing E&O insurance","Clearly defining scope, deliverables, fees, and limiting liability for outcomes outside the consultant's control","Guaranteeing a specific MOR rating outcome","Binding HUD to the agreed timeline"],"ans":1,"exp":"A signed engagement letter defines the scope and limits the consultant's liability — without it, scope creep and disputes about deliverables are inevitable."},{"q":"The HUD multifamily database (publicly available) is useful for business development because:","opts":["It shows which properties have failed MORs","It allows consultants to identify all HUD-assisted properties in a geographic area and prioritize outreach by unit count and program type","It provides contact information for HUD reviewers","It shows current HAP contract expiration dates"],"ans":1,"exp":"The public HUD multifamily database lets consultants identify and target prospective clients by location, program type, and size."},{"q":"Root cause analysis during file review means:","opts":["Identifying every compliance error and listing them for the client","Identifying why errors are occurring — training gaps, process failures, or personnel issues — so the CAP addresses systemic causes","Blaming prior management for current deficiencies","Documenting every file error in detail for HUD"],"ans":1,"exp":"Root cause analysis goes beyond listing errors — it identifies why they occur so the corrective action addresses the system, not just the symptom."},{"q":"A referral network of housing attorneys, lenders, and NSPIRE consultants benefits an MOR consultant because:","opts":["They share fees on HUD contracts","They refer clients who need MOR prep to the consultant and vice versa — cross-referrals multiply business development reach","They provide free legal and financial advice","They satisfy HUD's third-party oversight requirements"],"ans":1,"exp":"Cross-referral networks multiply reach — attorneys encounter clients who need compliance help, lenders encounter properties before MOR reviews, creating warm inbound leads."},{"q":"Staff training during MOR prep should cover all of the following EXCEPT:","opts":["How to respond to reviewer questions honestly and professionally","Key regulatory concepts reviewers will probe (EIV, certifications, fair housing)","Scripts designed to mislead the reviewer","File organization standards"],"ans":2,"exp":"Training staff to mislead reviewers is unethical, potentially fraudulent, and counterproductive. Training should build genuine competence and honest confidence."},{"q":"Targeting 10 retainer clients at $1,000/month each generates approximately:","opts":["$60,000 per year","$120,000 per year","$180,000 per year","$240,000 per year"],"ans":1,"exp":"10 clients × $1,000/month × 12 months = $120,000 in annual retainer revenue — a viable and sustainable consulting business model."},{"q":"The most important factor in building a sustainable MOR consulting reputation is:","opts":["Charging the lowest fees in the market","Delivering measurable results — improved ratings, resolved findings, and clients who pass their next MOR","Obtaining every available HUD certification","Having the most polished marketing materials"],"ans":1,"exp":"Results win referrals. The consultant's reputation is built on client outcomes — properties that improve their ratings and pass subsequent MORs are the best marketing."}]}};
